<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Malaysia Stock Index Jumps 6 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- Malaysia's key stock index surged  
up 6 percent Friday on news that Morgan Stanley Capital 
International will reinstate Malaysia in its international stock 
indexes in February. 
</P>
<P>
	The Composite Index, which tracks 100 blue-chip stocks on the  
Kuala Lumpur stock exchange, closed at 772.88 points, up 43.92 
points. 
</P>
<P>
	An initial buying frenzy sent the index up 10 percent to top 800  
points in the first 15 minutes of trading Friday before shares gave 
up some of the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	Morgan Stanley's decision Thursday to reinstate Malaysia to its  
indexes, widely used by global fund managers to allocate 
investments, comes 11 months after Kuala Lumpur was expelled 
following the imposition of sweeping capital controls on Sept. 1. 
Those controls were relaxed in February, and taxes on investment 
gains are being lowered. 
</P>
<P>
	Thursday's announcement is expected to spur buying of Malaysian  
shares by investment funds that seek to mimic the performance of 
international indexes. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
