<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Mixed, Gold Up in Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar was mixed against other major  
currencies in European trading today. Gold prices rose. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0568 in late European trading, down  
from $1.0624 Thursday. Later, in afternoon trading in New York, the 
euro traded at $1.0565. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday,  
included 115.92 Japanese yen, up from 115.86; 1.5162 Swiss francs, 
up from 1.5071; 1.4773 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4848. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.6048, down from $1.6086.  
</P>
<P>
	In afternoon trading In New York, the dollar bought 115.73 yen  
and the pound was worth $1.6050. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth 1.8507 German marks, up from 1.8410; 
6.2070 French francs, up from 6.1743; 2.0853 Dutch guilders, up 
from 2.0743; 1,832.20 Italian lire, up from 1,822.54. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold in London was quoted at $260.35 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$260.30 on Thursday. In Zurich the bid price was $260.35, up from 
$260.25. Gold closed at $260.85 in Hong Kong, unchanged from 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver in London was quoted at $5.30 bid per troy ounce, down  
from $5.38. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
