<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Aug. 13, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Dow Soars 184.26 at 10,973.65  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks soared today as a new government report  
suggested inflation remains in check, raising hopes that the 
Federal Reserve need not be aggressive in raising interest rates to 
cool off the economy. At the close of trading on Wall Street, the 
Dow Jones industrial average was up 184.26 at 10,973.65, a gain of 
1.7 percent. For the week, the blue-chip index gained 259.62 
points. Broader stock indicators were also sharply higher and the 
Nasdaq composite index gained 85.67 points to 2,635.16. Leading the 
Dow industrials were American Express and J.P. Morgan. On the 
Nasdaq, Microsoft and Intel advanced. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures at Friday's close:  
Dow Industrials:        10973.65 + 184.26
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1953  Declines 1044  Unchgd  531
NYSE Volume:         674,994,490
Most Active NYSE issue:         America Online96 3/4   + 4
S&AMP;P 500:         1326.50 + 28.34
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          783.74  + 3.09
NASDAQ Composite Index:       2635.16 + 85.67
Gold(final) -    $261.70    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Fri.

</P>
<P>
	Iridium Consortium Files Chapter 11  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Iridium LLC slid into Chapter 11 today, unable  
to pay its debts on a satellite-based mobile phone network that 
cost billions to build but attracted only thousands of users. The 
international consortium, led by Motorola, said it is filing for 
protection from its creditors in a Delaware court under Chapter 11 
of the federal bankruptcy code. Iridium, the first of four 
satellite phone networks to offer service, stumbled out of the 
starting gate last November. Iridium shares closed down 1 3/16 at 3 
1/16. 

</P>
<P>
	MCI Network Problems Continue  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Continuing problems with data transmission  
technology provided by MCI WorldCom Inc. caused the Chicago Board 
of Trade to halt electronic trading today and disrupted high-speed 
service for nearly 30 percent of MCI's global data network 
customers. The problems at MCI WorldCom, the No. 2 U.S. 
long-distance carrier, began late last week during a system 
upgrade, when a glitch in its network kept customers from 
transferring information and partially disabled thousands of 
automated teller machines across the country. MCI stock rose 2 9/16 
at 78 11/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Pfizer Diabetes Treatment Fails  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Pfizer Inc. has stopped development of an  
experimental drug to treat nerve damage from diabetes, joining 
other big drug companies that have failed to find a cure for the 
often-debilitating condition. About half of the 16 million 
diabetics in the United States eventually will suffer from diabetic 
neuropathy, a complication characterized by extreme pain or loss of 
feeling in the hands and feet. Pfizer was in late-stage human 
testing of its drug Alond when the company realized it found no 
improvement in patients taking the pill. Pfizer stock closed up 
7/16 at 34 7/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Wholesale Prices Rise in July  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Falling prices for beef, vegetables and fruit  
partially offset a July increase in the cost of gasoline to nudge 
up wholesale prices by a modest 0.2 percent, the Labor Department 
reported today. Last month's increase in the Producer Price Index, 
which measures inflation pressures before they reach the consumer, 
followed a 0.1 percent drop in wholesale prices in June, the second 
decline this year. And excluding the volatile energy and food 
categories, wholesale prices were unchanged in July, after a 0.2 
percent decline in June. 

</P>
<P>
	Disney Might Sell Fairchild  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Walt Disney Co. reportedly has decided to  
sell Fairchild Publications, a magazine division that includes W, 
Women's Wear Daily, Los Angeles and Jane magazines. Conde Nast 
Publications and Hearst Magazines have been involved in bidding on 
the titles, a Disney executive told The New York Times. Conde Nast 
has offered $650 million for Fairchild. Disney shares closed up 1 1/8 
at 27 1/4. 

</P>
<P>
	TBS Pulls Plug on Women's Network  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Facing high costs and stiff competition, Time  
Warner's Turner Broadcasting System has suspended development of a 
new cable network aimed at women. TBS will devote the resources 
instead to two other networks in development, a new cartoon channel 
and a regional Southeastern channel, as well as promoting its 
younger networks like Turner Classic Movies and CNN Sports 
Illustrated. 

</P>
<P>
	Sun Air Being Liquidated  
</P>
<P>
	JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- South Africa's third-largest  
airline, which was mostly black-owned, closed down today because of 
undisclosed financial losses. The government board that rules on 
major acquisitions said Sun Air was ``a failing company'' and it 
was in the public interest to ensure an orderly shutdown. The board 
signed off yesterday on a plan to sell Sun Air's black-owned shares 
to South African Airlines, the country's largest carrier. It also 
approved the subsequent liquidation. 

</P>
<P>
	Pipe Sanction Request Clears Hurdle  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Commerce Department can consider punitive  
tariffs on foreign steel pipes used by oil and natural gas 
producers, a U.S. panel ruled today. The U.S. International Trade 
Commission found evidence that shipments of seamless pipes from 
Japan, the Czech Republic, Romania, South Africa and Mexico have or 
could hurt the U.S. steel industry, which blames low-priced imports 
for thousands of layoffs. 

</P>
<P>
	Big Oil Cos. Stop Nigerian Pumping  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- A joint-venture between Texaco Inc. and Chevron  
Corp. was forced to stop pumping oil off the coast of Nigeria today 
because angry residents in the area blocked supplies from reaching 
the company's platforms. Texaco Overseas Petroleum Co. of Nigeria 
Unlimited, or Topcon, declared force majeure and ceased production 
at its five oil rigs near the Niger River delta. Companies declare 
force majeure when an unpredictable, external event prevents them 
from meeting contractual obligations. 

</P>
<P>
	Gas Producer Gazprom Loses $5.9B  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Gazprom, the world's largest natural gas producer,  
said today that it lost 147 billion rubles, or $5.9 billion, last 
year as a result of Russia's financial crisis and a global slump in 
energy prices. The loss compared to a net profit of 20 billion 
rubles in 1997, the company's Web site said. That would be worth 
$800 million at current conversion rates, but about $3 billion at 
the conversion rate in effect in 1997. 

</P>
<P>
	New Bidder for Reynolds Emerges  
</P>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Days after aluminum giant Alcoa Inc. made  
an unsolicited offer for Reynolds Metals Co., a small Chicago 
company has reportedly upped the bid. On Wednesday, Alcoa, the 
world's largest aluminum company, offered $65 a share in cash and 
stock for the nation's third-largest aluminum maker. Alcoa valued 
the deal at $5.6 billion. At $65 a share, the deal would be worth 
$4.2 billion based on the number of Reynolds shares outstanding. 
Dow Jones Newswires reported today that Michigan Avenue Partners, a 
privately held investment firm, has also made a cash offer for 
Reynolds. Alcoa shares closed down 1 1/4 at 66 1/2. 

</P>
<P>
	Lucent Acquiring Xedia Corp.  
</P>
<P>
	MURRAY HILL, N.J. (AP) -- Lucent Technologies Inc. is acquiring  
Xedia Corp., a maker of corporate computer network gear, for about 
$246 million in stock, the companies announced today. Xedia, based 
in Acton, Mass., specializes in routers that act as a gateway from 
the Internet to a corporation's private network, allowing employees 
or customers to connect to the network from anywhere on the 
Internet. Lucent stock rose 2 1/16 at 65 13/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Economic Numbers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic numbers:  
</P>
<P>
	Producer prices: up 0.2 percent  
</P>
<P>
	Business inventories: up 0.3 percent  

</P>
<P>
	AP Financial NewsBrief by JEROME MINERVA  



  	   	
