<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nudists Gather for Convenion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MARCOLA, Ore. (AP) -- At the national convention for American  
nudists, carefree rounds of naked volleyball and topless horseshoes 
were played this week despite the brisk air and an even more 
chilling reality: laws nipping at their lifestyle. 
</P>
<P>
	The nearly 1,000 nudists who shivered this week in the 65-degree  
Cascade foothills spent much of their time developing strategies 
against such legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every do-gooder wants to jump on us,'' 75-year-old Bill Haller  
said as he floated naked in the crystal-blue waters of the nudist 
resort pool. ``Back in the old days, no one seemed to care about 
us. Now we're having to go to court to protect ourselves a lot more 
than we used to. 
</P>
<P>
	The 50,000-member American Association for Nude Recreation,  
based in Kissimmee, Fla., now has a government affairs division and 
a legal defense fund. 
</P>
<P>
	Eric Schuttauf, coordinator of the government affairs division,  
said some laws, such as those that regulate the consumption of 
alcohol at strip clubs or keep teens out of adult businesses, are 
so broadly written that they leave nudist groups exposed to a whole 
range of possible legal problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't play very well when the family sits down on the  
deck here for a tuna fish sandwich and dad wants to have a light 
beer,'' Schuttauf said, pointing to the lounge furniture where a 
buck-naked woman was stretched out with a book. 
</P>
<P>
	Cities such as San Diego are also beginning to crack down on  
nudity in areas where it was once tolerated, such as the popular 
strip called Black's Beach. After years of tolerating sunbathers in 
the buff, the city announced in June it would start enforcing a 
decades-old prohibition against nudity. 
</P>
<P>
	The AANR even hired a Washington lobbyist after Rep. Dave  
Weldon, R-Fla., sought to ban nude swimming and sunbathing at a 
remote beach along the Canaveral National Seashore. That effort 
last year failed. 
</P>
<P>
	At this year's convention, which ends Monday, Schuttauf hopes to  
replenish the group's legal fund through an auction of vacation 
trips. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, not all law changes aim to throw a cloak over nudism.  
</P>
<P>
	Last summer, the Berkeley, Calif., City Council voted to ease  
the town's anti-nudity law by giving police the option of just 
issuing a $100 ticket on first offense. Under the original law, 
officers had no choice but to arrest offenders, who faced a year in 
jail if convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	Top of the business agenda at this year's convention was the  
approval of three new nudist chapters, bringing the total number to 
238 in the United States and Canada. The only state that doesn't 
have one is Alaska. Florida has the most with 22. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the last 10 years, membership in AANR has increased by 76  
percent. Nearly 92 percent are 35 or older. 
</P>
<P>
	Members say the group focuses on wholesome fun for the whole  
family -- contrary to the stereotype that nudists are nature freaks 
or free-styling swingers. 
</P>
<P>
	To Linda Pace, the AANR's membership director, nudism is all  
about feeling comfortable with one's body and learning to judge 
people differently. Those values appeal to everyone from factory 
workers to corporate lawyers, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't matter whether the color of your collar is blue or  
white, when you're not wearing one,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	But even die-hard nudists have their limit. As the unseasonably  
cold temperatures moved in and the skies turned slate-gray, most of 
the delegates chose to shed their birthday suits in favor of 
sweatsuits and pants. 
</P>
<P>
	``We shed our clothes, not our common sense,'' Ms. Pace said.  
``Even nudists get cold.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
