<HEADLINE> Grains and Beans Mixed at Open / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grains and soybeans futures prices were mixed in  
early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade, where trading 
resumed on schedule after a power outage cut short Thursday's 
session. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat opened mixed before turning mostly higher on strong export  
news. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans were mostly lower in followthrough from Thursday's  
sharp decline, caused in part by a bearish crop production report 
from the U.S. Agriculture Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Heavy rains in parts of southern Illinois and southern Indiana  
also weighed on prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn was mixed in early trading on thoughts that Thursday's  
bearish crop report was overstated. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading opened on time today a day after the Board of Trade  
closed an hour early due to power outages in the downtown Loop 
area. The problems were blamed on the failures of two power 
transmission cables. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery rose 2 3/4 cents to $2.83 1/2 a bushel;  
December corn fell 1 cent to $2.22 1/4 a bushel; December oats fell 1/2 
cent to $1.16 a bushel; November soybeans fell 4 1/4 cents to $4.52 a 
bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Cattle and pork futures were mixed on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange today. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle rose 0.27 cent to 65.77 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle fell 0.30 cent to 77.10 cents a pound; August lean 
hogs rose 0.10 cent to 54.55 cents a pound; February pork bellies 
fell 0.37 cent to 56.45 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
