<HEADLINE> Wheat Higher, Beans Mixed on CBOT / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Wheat futures prices were higher while corn and  
soybeans were mixed Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat opened mixed before turning mostly higher on strong export  
news. The crop production report released by the U.S. Agriculture 
Department Thursday -- bearish for corn and soybeans -- was not 
negative for corn. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans opened lower in followthrough from Thursday's sharp  
decline, which was caused in part by the crop production report. 
Heavy rains in parts of southern Illinois and southern Indiana also 
weighed on prices, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices in some contract months turned to the positive side in a  
mixed day. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn also closed mixed as market participants weighed whether  
Thursday's bearish crop report was overstated. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading opened on time Friday a day after the Board of Trade  
closed an hour early due to power outages in the downtown Loop 
area. The problems were blamed on the failures of two power 
transmission cables. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery rose 5 cents to $2.85 3/4 a bushel;  
December corn fell 1/2 cent to $2.22 3/4 a bushel; December oats fell 1/2 
cent to $1.16 a bushel; November soybeans fell 2 1/4 cents to $4.54 a 
bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Live cattle futures were higher and feeder cattle mixed on the  
Chicago Mercantile Exchange, while lean hogs were mixed and pork 
bellies higher. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle rose .55 cent to 66.05 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle fell .13 cent to 77.27 cents a pound; August lean 
hogs rose .15 cent to 54.60 cents a pound; February pork bellies 
rose 1.38 cent to 58.20 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
