<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jerry Springer Rules Out Senate Run </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- He might have looked forward to six years as  
``the gentleman from Ohio.'' But television's Jerry Springer 
decided to follow the money. 
</P>
<P>
	Springer's office in Chicago issued a statement on Friday  
popping a political trial balloon that might have lured him back to 
Ohio, saying a return to the campaign trail was out of the question 
because of contractual obligations and a new talk-and-variety show 
about to debut in England. 
</P>
<P>
	It's ``impractical if not impossible for me to make a run for  
the Senate at this time,'' he said in the written statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Springer, who in a former life was a Cincinnati politician, had  
been courted by some of his old pals to run for the U.S. Senate 
after the usual suspects -- current members of Congress and former 
candidates -- decided 2000 wouldn't be their year. 
</P>
<P>
	With him out of the mix, Democrats presumably will find a  
nominee their party's presidential candidate won't mind being seen 
with in public. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think Democrats ought to be relieved,'' said political  
analyst Stuart Rothenberg. ``It would have been an embarrassment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The freshman Republican who might have had Springer for an  
opponent, Sen. Mike DeWine, had no comment, according to a 
spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	Ohio's Republican Party chief, though, rejoiced in the  
opposition party's difficulties. 
</P>
<P>
	GOP Chairman Robert Bennett said entertaining the idea of a  
Springer candidacy demonstrated that ``Name recognition and deep 
pockets are their only criteria.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ohio newspapers had huffed their outrage at the prospect of a  
Springer Senate race, and some Democrats who had been longing for a 
deep-pockets candidate said they couldn't accept Springer. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Ted Strickland, for instance, said Springer's television  
program was damaging and exploitive and he could have nothing to do 
with the man. 
</P>
<P>
	Organized labor leaders had encouraged a Springer candidacy,  
reasoning that his fame and wealth could offset the advantages of 
incumbency and maybe attract adults who usually don't bother to 
vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Strickland said he was still hoping to see his party's  
unsuccessful 1998 candidate, Mary Boyle, change her mind about 
running. Actively exploring the race was Columbus attorney Richard 
Cordray, a little-known former state representative who was shaping 
up to be the likely nominee. 
</P>
<P>
	Holly Armstrong of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee  
said ``Clearly DeWine is vulnerable and Richard Cordray represents 
an exciting opportunity to pick up that seat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Springer, 55, was mayor of Cincinnati for two terms and ran for  
governor in 1982 before starting a TV career. The spiciest episode 
of his political career came when he paid a prostitute with a 
check. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
