<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Victory Gallop's Career Cut Short </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. (AP) -- Victory Gallop, who had a stirring  
victory over Behrens in the Whitney Handicap just 12 days ago, has 
been retired from racing because of an injury to his left leg, 
trainer Elliott Walden announced Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 4-year-old son of Cryptoclearance tore a ligament in his  
left leg, an injury Walden suspects happened in the $600,000 Grade 
I Whitney at Saratoga. His next scheduled start was to be the $1 
million Pacific Classic at Del Mar on Aug. 29. 
</P>
<P>
	Walden said Victory Gallop, who finished his career with nine  
wins in 17 starts and earnings of $3,605,885, will be retired and 
stand at stud at Prestonwood Farm in Versailles, Ky. 
</P>
<P>
	Walden said a horse of lesser quality might have been given six  
months to rehabilitate the injured area. Even then, Walden said, 
the success rate of such treatment is usually minimal. 
</P>
<P>
	Although he is not certain, Walden suspects the suspensory  
injury occurred nearing the finish line in the Whitney, which 
Victory Gallop won by a nose. 
</P>
<P>
	``The way Behrens came back to him at the wire was a possible  
indication that something was wrong,'' Walden said. ``It certainly 
didn't happen while he was just galloping in the morning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite his obvious disappointment, Walden said, ``He was at the  
top of the heap. It's nice to know that he went out on a winning 
note. He has nothing to prove having won Grade Is at 3 and 4. 
</P>
<P>
	``He'll have a great career at stud because of his distance  
capability and his great turn of foot.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
