<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Polo Magazine Allowed To Continue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Polo Magazine won another round Friday in its  
match against New York fashion house Polo Ralph Lauren. 
</P>
<P>
	Though a federal magistrate in Dallas ruled against the magazine  
on Aug. 3 and ordered it to stop using the Polo name, the 5th U.S. 
Circuit Court of Appeals stayed that order, allowing the magazine 
to stay in print. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Magistrate Judge Mary Milloy ruled that the magazine's use  
of the name, published by Westchester Media Co., caused consumer 
confusion with the fashion house. 
</P>
<P>
	Polo Ralph Lauren asked Westchester to give up the name after  
its overhaul from a small specialty publication into a slick, 
broader-focused magazine that launched with about 1 million issues. 
Westchester responded by suing to protect the name secured by 
founder and former publisher Ami Shinitski in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys for the magazine had argued that it is the official  
publication of the U.S. Polo Association despite its transformation 
into a glossy lifestyles journal. 
</P>
<P>
	Arguments in the appeal are set for the week of Oct. 4.  


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
