<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Gains Sparked by Stocks Jump </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar made broad gains Friday against both  
the euro and yen, as currency traders drew confidence from a strong 
recovery in the U.S. stock markets. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0564, down  
from $1.0669 late Wednesday. The dollar also was quoted at 115.74 
Japanese yen, up from 115.62. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said the dollar continued a recent trend of following  
the direction of U.S. stocks, which jumped sharply Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The stock market is being used as a tool to assess what will  
happen in the currency market,'' said Kevin Harris, an 
international economist at MCM Currencywatch in New York. ``When 
you get that kind of rise in stocks, currency traders want to buy 
dollars.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.5159 Swiss francs, up from  
1.5012, and 1.4764 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4862. The British 
pound fell to $1.6057 from $1.6119. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Thursday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8515 German 
marks, up from 1.8332; and 6.2112 French francs, up from 6.1501. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
