<HEADLINE> Catfish Hunter Improves Slowly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENVILLE, N.C. (AP) -- Jim ``Catfish'' Hunter was slowly  
improving Friday, although his condition still was listed as 
critical five days after he hit his head on concrete steps at his 
home. 
</P>
<P>
	The 53-year-old Hunter remained in the intensive care unit,  
officials at Pitt County Memorial Hospital said. The Hall of Fame 
pitcher was conscious and responding to doctors and relatives, his 
family said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	``We continue to be quite hopeful and optimistic that Jimmy will  
recover and be back home in Hertford very soon,'' the family 
minister, the Rev. Keith Vaughan, said in the statement. ``We thank 
God for the progress that Jimmy has made thus far, and we are 
encouraged by the news coming from Greenville today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hunter, who retired in 1979 to his Hertford farm after 15 years  
in the majors and five World Series rings, was diagnosed last year 
with amyotrophic lateral sclerosis -- Lou Gehrig's disease, a 
gradual, irreversible deterioration of the muscles. 
</P>
<P>
	Hunter's wife, Helen, expressed gratitude Friday for the support  
from friends and fans. 
</P>
<P>
	``The cards and phone calls continue to pour in from  
everywhere,'' she said in a statement. ``We are saving every one, 
and when Jimmy is better, we will make sure that he sees them. It 
is such an encouragement to us that people care so much. We are 
truly grateful.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
