<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 10:54:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Appalachia Anti-Poverty Work Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) -- While much of the nation thrives amid a  
booming economy, officials gathered in impoverished Appalachia say 
now is the time to complete anti-poverty efforts begun in the 
1960s. 
</P>
<P>
	Appalachian states need to do more to develop their  
transportation systems and take advantage of economic opportunities 
federal programs have created, West Virginia Gov. Cecil Underwood 
said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood was the opening speaker at the second day of a two-day  
Appalachian Summit, sponsored by the U.S. Department of Housing and 
Urban Development. The summit is intended to foster the exchange of 
ideas among government officials, businesses and nonprofit groups 
in the region. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater was scheduled to  
address the conference later today. 
</P>
<P>
	The Transportation Department and the Appalachian Regional  
Commission have invested billions of dollars to develop 
infrastructure in the region, and the Appalachian corridor highway 
system has created new economic opportunities, Underwood told the 
group. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said the region still needs to develop other types of  
transportation. States needs to make greater use of their 
waterways, railroads and airports, such the regional airport 
proposed for southwest West Virginia, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Such an airport could bring new jobs, new products more  
developable land in that area,'' Underwood said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, U.S. Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo told the group  
that low unemployment in the rest of the country can translate into 
economic opportunity for jobless workers in Appalachia, 
</P>
<P>
	``Appalachia needs business, but business needs Appalachia,'' he  
said. ``The economic equivalent of air and water for business is 
new workers and new markets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kentucky Gov. Paul Patton said the region must emphasize the  
development of small start-up businesses as well as try to draw 
established businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to find activities that can use the workforce we have  
and accept the limitations that we have,'' Patton said. ``There is 
no silver bullet; it is not going to be fast and it is not going to 
be easy. ... But this conference can help turn the corner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The conference grew out of President Clinton's July tour of poor  
communities from Appalachia to Los Angeles, in which he highlighted 
what he touted as the ``untapped markets'' in America's inner 
cities and rural areas. 
</P>
<P>
	The summit, sponsored by the U.S. Department of Housing and  
Urban Development, is the first to bring together state governments 
in the 13-state Appalachian region with business, the Appalachian 
Regional Commission and four federal agencies. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuomo encouraged the groups to work on solutions to regional  
problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``Apathy here is the enemy,'' he said. ``Disbelief ... lack of  
energy and commitment and passion is the enemy. The American 
economy ... needs you in a way they have never needed Appalachia 
before. They need your workers.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990813.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 07:10:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Disabled Man Requests Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- Prosecutors won't oppose a severely  
disabled man's request to unplug the hospital ventilator that has 
kept him alive since 1967, when he broke his neck in a high school 
gymnasium. 
</P>
<P>
	Under New York law, patients can opt to discontinue lifesaving  
treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	What makes Bill White's circumstances uncommon is that he is  
believed to be one of America's longest surviving quadriplegics on 
a ventilator and, because he needs 24-hour care, has rarely left 
his hospital bed in 32 years. 
</P>
<P>
	After a weeklong review, Monroe County District Attorney Howard  
Relin's office concluded that White ``has the right to refuse 
treatment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``At this point, Bill has indicated he wants to go through with  
it,'' Strong Memorial Hospital spokeswoman Teri D'Agostino said 
Thursday. ``We're still leaving the door open for him to change his 
mind.'' The hospital said this morning that there was no change in 
his status. 
</P>
<P>
	White, 50, has asked that no details be released, the hospital  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	He asked hospital staff a few months ago to discontinue his  
ventilator treatment, which in all likelihood would end his life 
within minutes. The hospital eventually promised to honor his 
request a week ago but held off when Relin asked to review the 
case. 
</P>
<P>
	Motivated by ``concerns about his deteriorating health,'' White  
convinced a team of doctors, psychiatrists, social workers and 
patient advocates that he is mentally competent and not motivated 
by depression. 
</P>
<P>
	He was paralyzed from the neck down in March 1967 when, at age  
18, he bounced on a springboard and flew over the parallel bars. A 
student who was supposed to help him land was not ready. White 
knocked into him, veered off the mat and crashed headfirst on the 
wooden floor. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew instantly what happened -- I felt all the sensation go  
out of my hands,'' White said in a 1997 interview with the 
Rochester Democrat and Chronicle. 
</P>
<P>
	His hospital bill, which exceeds $200,000 a year, is paid by  
Medicaid, the federal-state health care program for the disabled 
and the indigent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990813.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 17:10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Players React to Graf Retirement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	In the Year of Retirement, add Steffi Graf.  
</P>
<P>
	``The mental toughness puts her right up there with the Michael  
Jordans, the Wayne Gretzkys and the John Elways,'' two-time U.S. 
Open champion Tracy Austin said of Graf. 
</P>
<P>
	``They all retired at the same time. What are they doing to  
us?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Graf announced Friday that she was calling it quits after  
dominating women's tennis and earning a women's record $21,839,777 
along with 22 Grand Slam tournament singles titles. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have done everything I wanted to do in tennis,'' the  
30-year-old Graf said during a news conference in Heidelberg, 
Germany. ``It is time to stop.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I can kind of sympathize with what she's going through because  
when you're at the top, it is not easy to maintain it,'' Pete 
Sampras, the top-ranked men's player, said. ``She had an 
unbelievable career, did it with a lot of class. 
</P>
<P>
	``She went out and got the job done and made the racket do the  
talking. I have always looked up to her the way she approached the 
game. She worked very hard and is a great athlete. But she has 
nothing to be ashamed of after winning 22 Grand Slams. That is not 
easy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Andre Agassi, the third-ranked man, said Graf's retirement ``is  
certainly a loss for tennis because in my opinion she is the best 
lady that has ever played, dominated on every surface. And on the 
other side of it, there is a sense of happiness for the next 
chapter of her life, which I am sure she is looking forward to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I was really expecting her to kind of end her career at the  
U.S. Open,'' said Lindsay Davenport, the Wimbledon champion and the 
defending U.S. Open champion, ``so it is a little bit of a 
surprise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``What I thought was really great was the older she got and the  
more she was winning, probably in the mid-'90s, the happier it 
seemed to make her. When she was playing in the '80s and just 
dominating, she never looked that happy and I think she really 
learned to appreciate the game the older she got and more she 
played.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1982, Graf played her first WTA Tour match in Filderstadt,  
Germany. The 13-year-old participated in the draw and pulled 
Austin's name as her first-round opponent. 
</P>
<P>
	``She was this ... kid who hit the ball so hard I couldn't  
believe it,'' Austin remembered Friday. ``It was 4-all in the first 
set and she was painting the lines.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Austin won the next 10 games, but knew she had seen the future  
of women's tennis. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew she was going to be a very, very good player,'' Austin  
said. ``She had a huge, huge forehand and she moved like a deer out 
there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The nimble footwork and big forehand changed women's tennis,  
although Graf, unlike many other young players, was not an 
overnight success. She didn't win her first Grand Slam tournament 
title until 1987, when she surprised Martina Navratilova in the 
final of the French Open. 
</P>
<P>
	``She was so disciplined. She was always focused, always trying  
100 percent,'' Austin said. ``Just very professional about her job 
and her work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bart McGuire, the WTA Tour's chief executive officer, said, Graf  
``has been a role model for women athletes in all sports. She has 
been a catalyst for the resurgence of women's tennis, especially in 
Europe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Steffi is a class act,'' McGuire said.  
</P>
<P>
	Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario played Graf in seven Grand Slam  
tournament finals, winning the 1989 French Open and the 1994 U.S. 
Open. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's been a great player, a great champion, a good person and  
a friend,'' Sanchez-Vicario said in Manhattan Beach, Calif., where 
she is playing in the Acura Classic. ``No one can replace Steffi. 
It's kind of hard to think she isn't going to be there anymore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Billie Jean King called Graf ``the all-time great singles player  
in women's tennis.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm glad that she is able to retire on her own terms and hope  
that she will keep some involvement and commitment to our sport the 
rest of her life,'' King said. ``We will miss her great athletic 
ability.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Austin, who's career was shortened by a back injury, said she  
wasn't surprised by Graf retiring. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a great loss for women's tennis, but I love the fact that  
she's doing it on her terms because after all of these injuries 
she's had, it's great that she's not going out because of an 
injury.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mary Pierce, whose lone Grand Slam tournament title came at the  
1995 Australian Open, was surprised at the retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	``But I'm happy for her that she feels at peace,'' Pierce said.  
</P>
<P>
	Wimbledon semifinalist Alexandra Stevenson said Graf's  
retirement ``gives me goose bumps. Also knowing I will never have 
the privilege of playing against her makes me sad. But I will 
memorize her graceful and courageous run at the 1999 French Open. 
Steffi Graf was always my measure of greatness.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
