<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Car Dealer Sued Over Payment Timer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Auto dealer Mel Farr thought he'd found a way to  
offer cars to people with bad credit, and protect his profits -- a 
high-tech dashboard gizmo that prevents cars from starting if the 
customer is delinquent on payments. 
</P>
<P>
	But now Farr, one of the nation's biggest car dealers, is facing  
a lawsuit from two women who contend the On-Time Device shut their 
cars down while they were driving. 
</P>
<P>
	Mandi Bergeron, 21, of Wixom, and Chavela Jones, 21, of Detroit  
sued Farr on Thursday. Their lawyer contends the device relegates 
people to second-class status. 
</P>
<P>
	``While I imagine that he believes he's doing the right thing, I  
think I am as equally concerned about those who are less fortunate 
and therefore most susceptible to this kind of abuse,'' said 
attorney Kenneth Hylton Jr. ``For him to cast this as a means of 
helping people move up and out of poverty is just absurd.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hylton's lawsuit contends the leases on the two vehicles should  
be voided, and it seeks damages of more than $25,000. 
</P>
<P>
	But Farr's company, which finances cars in urban areas where  
many people have credit problems, says the device helps it do 
business in a tough market. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got consumers who are schemers, liars, people who've  
never paid anyone,'' said Farr spokeswoman Charlene M. Mitchell. 
``It's a hard market to deal with. But most people are honest. It's 
the small percent that doesn't stay up-to-date that adds up to lot 
of dollars.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Mitchell also contended the device could not possibly have  
caused the cars to stall. 
</P>
<P>
	Farr, a former Detroit Lions running back, has 12 dealership  
franchises in Michigan and Ohio. With sales of $596.6 million last 
year, his company became the nation's largest black-owned business, 
according to Black Enterprise magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	The On-Time Device is made by a small California company called  
Payment Protection Systems, which says about 1,000 are in use 
around the country. Farr has put the device in about 200 vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	It consists of a keypad and a tiny light.  
</P>
<P>
	Customers who come to a payment center once a week get a  
six-digit code when they pay their bills. They punch in the code on 
the keypad and if it matches the proper code, the light turns green 
and the car can be started. 
</P>
<P>
	If more than a week passes without a new code, the light stays  
red, a buzzer sounds and the car won't start. 
</P>
<P>
	Hylton said the cars of both of his clients stalled while they  
were driving on a freeway. Both drivers managed to coast to a stop. 
One had to punch in an ``emergency code'' that gives owners a 
24-hour reprieve. The other waited a few minutes, then restarted 
her car. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they malfunction in two cars, they're likely to malfunction  
in others,'' said Hylton. They are accidents waiting to happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Mitchell denied the charge and said Farr tested the device  
in his own Lincoln Navigator for two months before deciding to use 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	``The car would keep going even if you haven't paid your bill,''  
she said. ``Theoretically you could keep it idling in the driveway 
all night.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Farr, whose dealerships operate mostly in the suburbs, has said  
he wants to expand his sales in large cities. With the help of the 
Rev. Jesse Jackson, Farr got backing from several Wall Street banks 
to fund his car financing unit, Triple M Financing. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Mitchell said most car dealers don't want to work in urban  
areas, creating a pent-up demand for vehicles. Such problems are 
more acute in Detroit, where poverty and a lack of public transit 
hinder the job prospects for many residents. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Farr could just keep doing business in the suburbs and not  
have these headaches, but he feels this is a market he want to do 
business in,'' Ms. Mitchell said. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, no customer with the device has fallen behind in  
payments, she said. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
