<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Top Acts Commit to NetAid Concerts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- George Michael, Celine Dion and Bono are among the  
top performers who are turning to the Internet for a massive 
concert to highlight world poverty. 
</P>
<P>
	NetAid will link overlapping shows in London, New Jersey and  
Geneva on Oct. 9 -- and broadcast the concerts worldwide over the 
Internet. Organizers are hoping to attract the largest audience 
ever for a live musical event. 
</P>
<P>
	The concerts are being organized by the United Nations  
Development Program and Cisco Systems Inc., an Internet network 
company based in San Jose, Calif.; proceeds will be used to help 
Kosovo refugees and African countries. A special charity, called 
NetAid Foundation, is being set up to handle the funds, organizers 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Other artists scheduled to appear include Jewel, The Corrs,  
Robbie Williams, Jimmy Page, Counting Crows, Eurythmics and Pete 
Townshend. The final lineup at each of the venues has yet to be 
announced. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a fantastic lineup of artists and all of them are  
committed to our cause of eradicating poverty,'' said promoter 
Harvey Goldsmith, who helped organize the Live Aid concerts to 
benefit Ethiopia in 1985. 
</P>
<P>
	A total of 110,000 tickets will be available for both the London  
concert at Wembley Stadium and the concert at Giants Stadium in 
East Ruthersford, N.J. The Geneva event will be smaller and by 
invitation only. 
</P>
<P>
	The concerts will also be broadcast later on TV worldwide.  
</P>
<P>
	People will be able to donate money via the Internet at the  
NetAid site due to be set up next month. But the organizers said 
their main intention is to highlight extreme poverty and encourage 
people to join together to fight it. 
</P>
<P>
	They want their Internet site, which will be an ongoing site, to  
reach 1 billion people. The concerts are being used to launch the 
effort. 
</P>
<P>
	``The potential of NetAid is to harness the resources of the  
Internet to help impoverished people to set up an infrastructure so 
that it is easier for the developed world to help,'' said Chris 
Dedicot, managing director of Cisco. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
