<HEADLINE> Gas Producer Gazprom Loses $5.9B </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Gazprom, the world's largest natural gas producer,  
said Friday that it lost 147 billion rubles, or $5.9 billion, last 
year as a result of Russia's financial crisis and a global slump in 
energy prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The loss compared to a net profit of 20 billion rubles in 1997,  
the company's Web site said. That would be worth $800 million at 
current conversion rates, but about $3 billion at the conversion 
rate in effect in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Gazprom said the figures were calculated using international  
accounting standards 
</P>
<P>
	The company posted a loss because of last summer's financial  
crisis, triggered by the government's default on Treasury debt and 
devaluation of the ruble, according to the auditor's report posted 
on the Gazprom site. 
</P>
<P>
	``The operations of the group have been significantly affected  
by instability in the Russian Federation's economy, caused in part 
by its currency volatility, and may continue to be so for the 
foreseeable future,'' the statement said. Last year's tumble in 
energy prices also dragged down financial results. 
</P>
<P>
	The company holds about a third of the world's known gas  
reserves. Its press office didn't return phone calls seeking 
comment. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
