<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tariff Complaints in Steel Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The steel industry, unwilling to declare  
victory despite recent reductions in imports, continues to press 
for additional punitive tariffs. 
</P>
<P>
	The industry won a preliminary ruling Friday on foreign steel  
pipes used by oil and natural gas producers and has cases pending 
on several other product lines. U.S. producers already won tariffs 
on Japanese shipments of a core product: hot-rolled carbon steel. 
</P>
<P>
	``The ongoing protectionist campaign to disrupt the steel market  
is continuing,'' said Brink Lindsey, director of the Center for 
Trade Policy Studies at the Cato Institute, which generally opposes 
trade sanctions. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we have seen over the past several months is a rampage by  
the U.S. steel industry in filing unfair trade cases,'' he said. 
``The results are an ongoing disruption of U.S. steel trade.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The domestic steel industry contends tariffs and other sanctions  
are needed to combat low-priced imports, which it blames for 
company bankruptcies and thousands of layoffs. It argues that 
foreign governments and their producers illegally engage in 
practices that artificially lower prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The case acted on Friday affects seamless pipes. The U.S.  
International Trade Commission found evidence that shipments from 
Japan, the Czech Republic, Romania, South Africa and Mexico have or 
could hurt the U.S. industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Tariffs under consideration could lead to higher prices for  
pipes bought by oil and natural gas producers, which are struggling 
themselves because of dwindling prices. 
</P>
<P>
	With a few exceptions, the U.S. government has generally sided  
with the domestic industry in the cases it has filed since the 
Asian economic crisis caused import levels to surge. 
</P>
<P>
	The rulings in the main hot-rolled steel case have contributed  
to a 27 percent reduction in imports since November. U.S. steel 
prices have risen somewhat this year, and companies have brought 
back some workers. 
</P>
<P>
	But the industry is not backing down from its complaints.  
</P>
<P>
	``It will be a while before the steel industry recovers even if  
things continue on a positive direction,'' said Greg Mastel, 
program director for international trade studies at the Center for 
National Policy, a Washington think tank. ``Even though imports are 
coming down from a peak, it's still at a high level.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Bob Ney, R-Ohio, said the sanctions would help avert a  
rebound in foreign shipments. Industry officials worry that as soon 
as tariffs are imposed against a particular country on a particular 
product, that country would produce other products and other 
countries would fill the void. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to lock this thing down so this hemorrhaging of jobs  
will not occur again,'' he said. ``If the message is not made clear 
enough, this could happen again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to requests for tariffs, the industry has turned to  
Congress and the Clinton administration for additional help. 
</P>
<P>
	A bill that would create a $1.5 billion loan program for  
struggling steel, oil and gas producers awaits President Clinton's 
signature to become law. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, meanwhile, recently announced a 12-point action plan  
that included a pledge to oppose international loans that would 
further subsidize imports. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990813.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 23:00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bucks Name Grunfeld As New GM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. FRANCIS, Wis. (AP) -- Ernie Grunfeld, fired as the New York  
Knicks' general manager just before they went on a roll that took 
them to the NBA Finals, is taking over in the Milwaukee Bucks' 
front office. 
</P>
<P>
	Grunfeld replaces Bob Weinhauer, who was let go by the Bucks  
earlier this week after two years as general manager. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bucks decided not to renew Weinhauer's contract shortly  
after free agents Michael Curry and Dell Curry said they would 
leave the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Grunfeld, 44, spent nine years as the Knicks' general manager  
before he was fired in April. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Herb Kohl, owner and president of the Bucks, said Grunfeld  
was the only person he approached for the job. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you look for a winner, you look for someone who's done  
it. Ernie Grunfeld has done it,'' Kohl said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	New York canned Grunfeld when the Knicks slumped to 21-21 and  
were in danger of not making the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	New York then became the first No. 8 playoff seed to advance to  
the NBA Finals. The Knicks knocked off Miami, Atlanta and Indiana 
before losing the finals in five games to the San Antonio Spurs. 
</P>
<P>
	Grunfeld took heat for trading four players, including the  
popular Charles Oakley, for Latrell Sprewell and Marcus Camby, who 
initially had difficulty fitting into the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, Sprewell and Camby played key roles in lifting the Knicks  
into the finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Grunfeld attributed the Knicks' early losses to ``an awkward  
time of year'' caused by the players' lockout. 
</P>
<P>
	``New York is a town of instant gratification,'' Grunfeld said.  
``I've been in the game all my life -- for over 20, 25 years -- and 
you can't just put a group of players together and expect them to 
be a cohesive unit right away, especially without practice time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Grunfeld was drafted by the Bucks and played the first two of  
his nine NBA seasons in Milwaukee. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he took his family on vacations to Milwaukee each summer  
while he was with the Knicks. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a great basketball town,'' Grunfeld said.  
</P>
<P>
	Grunfeld likely will not have the final say on personnel matters  
with the Bucks. Coach George Karl is expected to make the team's 
final decisions. 
</P>
<P>
	The new general manager said he would spend the next few days  
talking with Karl and the players. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to sit with them and we want to see what direction we  
really want to go in and what things are possible to get done,'' he 
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
