<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 94 Killed in Indonesian Rioting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMBON, Indonesia (AP) -- Government security forces overwhelmed  
by recent east Indonesian religious rioting that has left at least 
94 people dead denied today that troops gunned down rioters inside 
a church. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, unrelated violence continued in Indonesia's  
northwestern Aceh province. Four police officers died after a group 
of civilians opened fire on their jeep. 
</P>
<P>
	In the eastern Maluku province, witnesses said the death toll  
from clashes between Muslims and Christians included 24 people shot 
by troops in and around a Protestant church in Galala, a suburb of 
the provincial capital of Ambon. Those shootings were Tuesday and 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Church secretary Benny Tamaela said he saw security forces  
shooting at battling mobs armed with homemade spears, bows and 
arrows and gasoline bombs. 
</P>
<P>
	``They all were shot to death, and it was very much regretted  
that some were shot inside the church,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the dead were Christians, he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Police spokesman Jekriel Philip denied that anyone was shot at  
the church, and said the rioters were killed in neighborhoods 
nearby. The bodies of several dead Christians were later brought to 
the church, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hospital officials reported five Muslims killed today as  
security personnel broke up riots south of Ambon. Prior to that, 
Philip said at least 89 people had been killed and another 455 
wounded since rioting erupted July 24. 
</P>
<P>
	Tensions eased considerably today, Philip said, with troops  
patrolling the streets. 
</P>
<P>
	Police have been reinforced in recent days by a battalion of  
Indonesia's toughest soldiers. The unit was one of two deployed 
after local security forces proved incapable of quelling the 
running battles. Media reports said an additional 600-man marine 
battalion was on its way to boost the security forces. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 400 people have died this year in a series of clashes  
and riots between Christians and Muslims in Maluku, 1,450 miles 
northeast of Jakarta. 
</P>
<P>
	In Aceh, the four police officers died today after five  
unidentified civilians on motorcycles opened fire on a jeep 
carrying six officers, North Aceh police chief Lt. Col. Syafei 
Aksal said. 
</P>
<P>
	Muslim separatists want the oil-rich region, about 1,100 miles  
northwest of Jakarta, to break away from Indonesia. More than 250 
people have been killed in clashes between government forces and 
the Aceh rebels since May. More than 100,000 civilians have been 
displaced. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
