<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Daewoo Sells Home Appliance Unit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- South Korea's debt-ridden Daewoo Group  
has agreed to sell most of its electronic home appliance unit to 
U.S. investment fund Walid Alomar &AMP; Associates for $3.2 billion, 
Daewoo officials said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Walid Alomar will take over Daewoo Electronics Co.'s assets in  
South Korea, the United States, Latin America, Japan, Australia, 
England and France, Daewoo Electronics President Yang Jae-yoel 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Daewoo Electronics, South Korea's No. 2 home appliance maker,  
generates $3.3 billion in annual sales in those countries. 
</P>
<P>
	After the sale, Daewoo will only operate its plants in China,  
Vietnam, Myanmar, eastern Europe and Brazil -- about $833 million in 
annual revenues, Yang said. 
</P>
<P>
	Walid Alomar, based in Beverly Hills, Calif., has formed a  
company called New DEC (Daewoo Electronics Co.) to operate Daewoo 
Electronics. It plans to use the existing workforce and market its 
products under Daewoo brand names. 
</P>
<P>
	All details of the deal will be worked out by Sept. 9, Yang  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Daewoo Electronics is a key unit of the ailing Daewoo Group,  
which narrowly escaped becoming South Korea's largest-ever 
bankruptcy when creditors agreed in June to delay its debt 
repayment for six months. 
</P>
<P>
	In return, Daewoo promised to unload most of its assets to cut  
debt. Daewoo has $48 billion in debts, and about half of them are 
coming due within a year. 
</P>
<P>
	The major operation Daewoo will be keeping is its core  
automobile group, Daewoo Motors Co. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
