<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> L.A. Suspect Charged With Murder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTEREY PARK, Calif. (AP) -- Ismael Ileto quietly listened to  
the details of his brother's death -- of how the postman filling in 
for a colleague agreed to mail a letter and was shot nine times, 
police say, simply for being a federal employee of Filipino 
descent. 
</P>
<P>
	The randomness and violence of Joseph Ileto's murder, an hour  
after a shooting rampage at a Jewish community center, left his 
brother speechless. He looked down, shook his head once and bit his 
lip. 
</P>
<P>
	``This family has been shocked and grieving through this whole  
thing,'' Ismael's wife, Deena, said, squeezing her husband's hand. 
``We can't imagine anyone who would want to hurt another person 
like this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Los Angeles County prosecutors on Thursday charged white  
supremacist Buford O. Furrow Jr. with murder in the death of the 
39-year-old Ileto, a shooting U.S. Attorney Alejandro Mayorkas said 
was carried out ``deliberately, maliciously and with 
premeditation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Federal prosecutors had already charged Furrow in the shooting  
on Wednesday; it is a federal crime because Ileto was a government 
worker on duty when he was killed. A federal-local task force will 
decide whether he will be tried jointly by state and federal 
authorities or face separate trials. 
</P>
<P>
	Either murder charge could lead to a death sentence.  
</P>
<P>
	The county also charged Furrow with five counts of attempted  
murder in Tuesday's attack at the community center that woundded 
five people. Two remain hospitalized, including 5-year-old Benjamin 
Kadish, who was in critical condition. 
</P>
<P>
	Furrow, 37, told investigators he had no intention of shooting  
small children and that they ``got in the way'' as he shot at a 
teen-age counselor and the center's receptionist, the Los Angeles 
Times reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the newspaper, Furrow said he scouted three  
prominent Jewish institutions -- the Museum of Tolerance, the 
Skirball Cultural Center and the University of Judaism -- while 
shopping for places to kill Jews. 
</P>
<P>
	He found security too tight at the facilities and stumbled upon  
the North Valley Jewish Community Center in suburban Granada Hills 
after pulling off a freeway to get gas, the newspaper quoted an 
unidentified source as saying. It was unclear when Furrow made his 
scouting trip, though museum staff recalled seeing someone who 
resembled Furrow two or three months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	After the charges were announced, Furrow was led into a federal  
courtroom for arraignment. Looking around at the crowd of mostly 
reporters, he smiled and said to his public defender, ``They all 
like me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chief Magistrate Judge Carolyn Turchin refused bail for Furrow,  
who has had mental problems as well as ties to hate groups in the 
Northwest. 
</P>
<P>
	The district attorney's complaint alleged that Ileto ``was  
intentionally killed because of his race or nationality.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Furrow allegedly confessed that he stopped the postal worker on  
a quiet suburban street and asked him to send a letter. When Ileto 
agreed, Furrow pulled out a gun and shot him as he tried to run 
away, Mayorkas said. Ileto was filling in for another carrier. 
</P>
<P>
	Furrow told investigators Ileto was a good ``target of  
opportunity'' because he was nonwhite -- he thought the postman was 
Hispanic or Asian -- and because he worked for the U.S. government. 
</P>
<P>
	Furrow had stayed in a hotel near Los Angeles for two nights  
before the crimes, the Times reported. After abandoning a stolen 
car following the shootings, he reportedly got a haircut, bought a 
shirt and took a taxi to Hollywood where he searched unsuccessfully 
for a prostitute. 
</P>
<P>
	Furrow then had several beers before flagging down a taxi  
driver, the newspaper reported. Hovik Garibyan, 31, said Furrow 
paid him $800 in large bills for a ride to Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	``He just paid me and he fell asleep,'' Garibyan told The  
Associated Press. ``He laid down in the back seat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Furrow was brought back to Los Angeles late Wednesday aboard a  
U.S. Customs helicopter after waiving extradition. 
</P>
<P>
	As relatives arrived from Chicago and New York for a funeral  
Saturday, the family of the slain postman tried to come to terms 
with the pain of their loss and a fear that speaking out might lead 
to more violence. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now that we have a son, I'm kind of looking behind my back,''  
Ismael Ileto said. ``It could happen to you, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A few miles away, the community center remained closed and under  
guard. A half-dozen flowers lay by the fence. A handwritten poster 
hung nearby read: ``Our prayers with you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The center was expected to reopen Monday.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're all looking forward to being in our own place again and  
continuing with our lives,'' said preschool teacher Ruby Diamond. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
