<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Town Gears Up for Only V-J Parade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOOSUP, Conn. (AP) -- Bill Poprosky and the boys at American  
Legion Post 91 are getting ready for the town's biggest annual 
event -- one of the nation's only V-J Day parades. They're expecting 
at least 10,000 uniformed marchers Sunday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Although World War II ended more than 50 years ago, Japan's  
surrender is still cause for celebration in this tiny village near 
the Rhode Island border. No matter that Japan is now an important 
ally and trading partner of the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just doing our part to remember history and the  
sacrifices that were made,'' said Poprosky, a past president of the 
Moosup American Legion and the parade chairman for the past 11 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Hostilities between the United States and Japan ended Aug. 14,  
1945, five days after the second of two atomic bombs was dropped on 
the island nation. The formal surrender was signed Sept. 2, 1945. 
</P>
<P>
	V-J Day generally comes and goes with little fanfare -- although  
the small mining town of Arma, Kan., also traditionally has a 
celebration and parade to commemorate the day. Rhode Island 
recognizes the second Monday of August as a state holiday called 
Victory Day. 
</P>
<P>
	Poprosky, a Vietnam veteran who spends his weekends working  
behind the bar in the Post 91 clubhouse, said there's strong 
support for the parade in Moosup. The former textile mill town has 
hundreds of military veterans among its 4,704 residents, Poprosky 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	There are no Japanese people in Moosup, said town Clerk Helen  
Coombs. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a few Vietnamese, but I don't know of anybody who's  
Japanese,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, census figures for 1990 showed that only about 3,800 of  
Connecticut's 3.3 million residents are of Japanese ancestry. Only 
57 were listed in Windham County, where Moosup is located. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Coombs, who has marched in several parades, says the event  
can draw ``as many as 25,000 visitors, including observers and 
marchers, if the weather is good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday's marchers will include members of the American Legion,  
AmVets, Veterans of Foreign Wars, Disabled American Vets, and 
others. 
</P>
<P>
	But Moosup resident Anne Radei doesn't expect many locals will  
be curbside on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've all seen it many times before,'' she said. ``I don't  
plan to go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at the Japanese consulate in Boston, which handles the  
New England region, said they take no position on the parade, a 
Moosup tradition since 1946. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, some people at the parade wore T-shirts bearing  
nuclear mushroom clouds and the message: ``Made in America. Tested 
in Japan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The T-shirts were made by Ed Mennuti, commander of American  
Legion Post 19 in Willimantic. His wife, Mary, president of the 
Post 19 Ladies Auxiliary, said the shirts will be back this year by 
popular demand, for $13 apiece. 
</P>
<P>
	``We got 150 printed up and I've sold half of them already,''  
she said last weekend. ``I've no doubt I'll sell them all.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
