<HEADLINE> 4 Taiwan students Killed in Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. ANTHONY, Idaho (AP) -- A rental van carrying Taiwanese  
exchange students towards Yellowstone National Park overturned in 
rural eastern Idaho, killing four passengers and injuring six 
others. 
</P>
<P>
	All but one of the van's occupants were ejected from the vehicle  
after it rolled over on Highway 20 early Thursday. Three women were 
dead at the scene and another died at a hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	The eight women and two men were about 40 miles southwest of  
Yellowstone when the driver lost control and the van flipped once. 
</P>
<P>
	``The driver said she didn't know what happened,'' said Deputy  
Brian Loseke of the Fremont County Sheriff's Office. ``It appears 
she fell asleep at the wheel.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The vacationers, all exchange students in their 20s and 30s from  
New York City, were traveling toward Yellowstone's west entrance in 
Wyoming, Loseke said. 
</P>
<P>
	Articles recovered from the van indicated that the tourists  
landed at Salt Lake International Airport on Wednesday night and 
rented a 15-passenger van. Loseke said the group drove through the 
night to get as far north as St. Anthony, about 220 miles from 
where they began. 
</P>
<P>
	The identities of the dead and injured were withheld pending  
notification of family members, Loseke said. At least two people 
were in critical condition. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
