<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Predicts Success in Straw Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CEDAR RAPIDS, Iowa (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush said Friday  
he has ``a good chance'' of winning the Iowa Straw Poll over his 
Republican competitors, but he aimed his sharpest comments at the 
Clinton administration. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush said the straw poll will be a good test of his campaign  
organization. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to look at it as an opportunity to bolster my  
organization and find out whether we need work -- if we need any 
work at all,'' the front-runner for the GOP presidential nomination 
told reporters before addressing an enthusiastic crowd of about 400 
at a park in downtown Cedar Rapids. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to get the most votes, I'd like to be in first,''  
Bush said. ``I think I have a good chance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Later, in a speech in Indianola, Bush touched on the subject of  
gun control, saying there is a ``false illusion'' that new laws 
alone could prevent new outbreaks of violence in America. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush has been criticized by Democrats for not supporting gun  
control measures, and he is talking about the issue more frequently 
at campaign stops. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I'm on the right side of the issue,'' Bush said,  
explaining that he thinks enforcement of current gun laws would 
make streets safer. ``I've been saying that all along. I may have 
raised it a decibel.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The straw poll Saturday is an Iowa GOP fund-raiser traditionally  
seen as an early gauge of organizational strength, but this 
summer's event took inflated importance, partially because Bush 
declared he would go all out to win it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know it's inconvenient for those of you who want to go  
fishing or play golf,'' Bush said, ``but we are talking about the 
future of our country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He told the crowd, which included numerous parents and their  
children, that he would be the best choice to lead the country at 
the turn of the century. 
</P>
<P>
	He chided President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore, who is  
seeking the Democratic Party's presidential nomination, for taking 
so much credit for a booming economy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Prosperity is not a given. It just doesn't happen. You listen  
to some of the folks in the executive branch, it sounds like they 
invented prosperity,'' Bush said in a line that has become a staple 
of his campaign appearances. ``I'd like to remind people, they no 
more invented prosperity than they invented the Internet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He was poking fun at Gore's assertion that he invented the  
Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush said he would be a vastly different president than Clinton.  
</P>
<P>
	``We must elect a president who will set goals worthy of a great  
nation, a president who will stand on principles, not on polls, and 
a president who will not use his office to reflect public 
opinion,'' Bush said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Should I be fortunate enough to become your president, when I  
put my hand on the Bible, I will swear to not only uphold the laws 
of the land, I will swear to uphold the dignity and the honor of 
the office to which I have been elected,'' Bush said, receiving 
sustained applause. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush said bolstering education, putting criminals in jail,  
reducing government regulations and rebuilding the nation's 
military would be top goals. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, who has campaigned far less in Iowa than most of the other  
GOP hopefuls, stayed for more than an hour with the crowd in Cedar 
Rapids, signing autographs, shaking hands and posing with people 
for pictures. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday evening, Bush was standing on a porch with his wife Laura  
outside a farming community called Indianola, which less than a 
30-minute drive of south of Des Moines, addressing about 200 
supporters. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope you're going to Ames. I'm counting on you,'' Bush said.  
``I hope you join Laura and me, and send a message that I'm the 
best guy for the Republican Party.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
