<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> L.A. Suspect Scouted Jewish Groups </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Authorities found a map marking the addresses  
of three Jewish organizations on the day a gunman attacked the 
North Valley Jewish Community Center, the founder of the Simon 
Wiesenthal Center said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wiesenthal center, the University of Judaism and a third  
local address related to Israel were circled on the map, Rabbi 
Marvin Hier said. He didn't know what the third address was. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were told by the FBI that we had been a prime target for  
this attack,'' Hier said. ``They had found physical evidence to 
that effect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hier said that at the time he had been told to keep the  
information confidential. Hier did not know where the map was found 
or whether it allegedly belonged to the shooting suspect, Buford O. 
Furrow. 
</P>
<P>
	Furrow, 37, the white supremacist suspected in Tuesday's  
community center attack and killing of a postal worker, surrendered 
Wednesday in Las Vegas. By then he had been identified after police 
discovered a van loaded with ammunition and a car he allegedly 
carjacked. 
</P>
<P>
	The Simon Wiesenthal Center, named after the famed Nazi hunter,  
researches the Holocaust and hate groups and operates the Museum of 
Tolerance. The University of Judaism is in the Bel Air section of 
Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe we were a prime target because of the work that we  
do combatting these haters,'' said Hier. 
</P>
<P>
	The Los Angeles Times, citing an unidentified source, reported  
Friday that Furrow said he scouted the Museum of Tolerance, the 
University of Judaism, and a third institution, the Skirball 
Cultural Center, a museum on Jewish culture. It said he found 
security too tight and stumbled upon the North Valley center when 
he simply got off a freeway to get gas. 
</P>
<P>
	Furrow told investigators he had no intention of shooting small  
children and that they ``got in the way'' as he shot at a teen-age 
counselor and the center's receptionist, the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hier said he was skeptical that only one person was involved.  
</P>
<P>
	``Calling this man a loner is an absolute mistake,'' he said.  
``I'm very skeptical that he could be familiar with L.A. in such a 
short time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During an arraignment Thursday, Furrow looked around the court  
at the crowd of mostly reporters, smiled and said to his public 
defender, ``They all like me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chief Magistrate Judge Carolyn Turchin refused bail for Furrow,  
who has had mental problems and ties to hate groups in the 
Northwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Los Angeles County prosecutors charged Furrow with murder in the  
death of the 39-year-old postal worker Joseph Santos Ileto and five 
counts of attempted murder in the attack at the community center. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal prosecutors had already charged Furrow in the Ileto  
shooting on Wednesday; it is a federal crime because Ileto was a 
government worker on duty when he was killed. A federal-local task 
force will decide whether he will be tried jointly by state and 
federal authorities or face separate trials. Either murder charge 
could lead to a death sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said Ileto was targeted because he was a federal  
employee of Filipino descent. 
</P>
<P>
	``This family has been shocked and grieving through this whole  
thing,'' Deena Ileto, sister-in-law of the victim, said Thursday. 
``We can't imagine anyone who would want to hurt another person 
like this.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
