<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 10:54:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 27 Run To Be Mayor of Baltimore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- For the first time in 28 years, an incumbent is  
not running for mayor of Baltimore, creating a political 
free-for-all that isn't doing much for the troubled city's 
reputation. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 27 candidates who entered the race to replace Mayor Kurt  
Schmoke, six have arrest records and three have filed for 
bankruptcy. Supporters of the front-runner have disrupted a rival's 
news conference, and another leading candidate falsely claimed in 
campaign literature that he had a college degree. 
</P>
<P>
	``What an embarrassment,'' wrote Barry Rascovar, deputy  
editorial page editor at The Sun. ``It could be the worst group of 
contenders in the city's long history.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't long ago that a mayor of Baltimore could go on to  
become governor. But these days the job doesn't attract people with 
a national profile. A movement to draft NAACP President Kweisi 
Mfume, which even involved changing the residency requirement to 
run, failed. 
</P>
<P>
	As Baltimore's population continues to dwindle, political  
observers say, political power goes with it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody seems to want the job, especially nobody who's  
well-qualified,'' said James Gimpel, a professor of government at 
the University of Maryland. ``The action in Maryland politics has 
shifted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Urban flight has transferred power from Baltimore to the suburbs  
of the nation's capital, helping Gov. Parris Glendening become the 
first governor elected from the Washington area since 1812. 
</P>
<P>
	Suburban Montgomery and Prince George's counties are among the  
fastest-growing in the state, while this decade, Baltimore has lost 
more than 90,000 residents, or 12.3 percent of its population, 
dropping to 645,593. 
</P>
<P>
	Baltimore's high murder rate, rampant drug abuse, financial woes  
-- and the glare of political and media attention from Washington -- 
make the job of mayor a tough one. 
</P>
<P>
	``Worthy political elites take a look at that hand of cards and  
say `I'm not playing,''' Gimpel said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the field of 27 who filed to run in the Sept. 14 Democratic  
primary -- generally the race to win in this predominantly 
Democratic city -- is Dorothy Joyner, who was jailed on burglary 
charges when a police officer recognized her during a TV 
appearance. She was later disqualified because she failed to file 
financial disclosure forms. 
</P>
<P>
	Phillip A. Brown Jr., a perennial candidate, has been convicted  
of larceny, shoplifting and impersonating a police officer. He is 
running while facing charges of harassment and reckless 
endangerment. 
</P>
<P>
	Schmoke, the city's first elected black mayor, announced in  
December he would not seek a fourth four-year term and will work 
for a high-powered Washington-based law firm. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the most critical election in at least 12 years,'' said  
State Comptroller William Donald Schaefer, a former Baltimore mayor 
who went on to serve two terms as governor. ``It's an opportunity 
to move the city forward which has so many good things going for it 
but lacks leadership.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schaefer had been considered a possible candidate himself, but  
he and others urged Mfume to run. Mfume announced in May he felt he 
could do more good at the Baltimore-based National Association for 
the Advancement of Colored People. 
</P>
<P>
	That has left three top candidates, each of whom failed to carve  
out support of 30 percent or higher in a recent poll. 
</P>
<P>
	Carl Stokes, a former city councilman, lost ground when he was  
forced to admit that his campaign literature falsely listed him as 
a Loyola College graduate. He attended the Baltimore school but did 
not graduate. 
</P>
<P>
	City Council President Lawrence Bell III still holds the lead in  
the polls, but The Sun has reported that a bank repossessed his 
Mustang convertible due to nonpayment and that he was sued for 
failing to pay his bills. On Aug. 5, about 50 of Bell's supporters 
crashed a rally for another candidate, City Councilman Martin 
O'Malley. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, O'Malley, who is white, has emerged as a strong contender  
to lead a city where three out of five people are black. Bell and 
Stokes are both black. 
</P>
<P>
	Bell's support measured 29 percent, O'Malley's 26 percent and  
Stokes' 20 percent in a poll conducted last weekend by a research 
firm. The margin of error was four percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	As Schaefer summed up: ``You have one fellow who's made some  
tactical errors by having his people try to destroy somebody else 
and has financial difficulties, another one who puts out literature 
that's not true, and another relatively young man who hasn't made 
any tactical errors, except that he is white.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
