<HEADLINE> Ex-SLA Fugitive Seeks Name Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- Former fugitive Kathleen Ann Soliah is  
seeking to have her name legally changed to Sara Jane Olson, the 
name she used to elude police for nearly a quarter century. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Soliah adopted the alias after settling in Minnesota, where  
she fled and became a doctor's wife, local stage actress and mother 
of three girls. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said a name change would not affect proceedings  
against Ms. Soliah, who faces charges she planted bombs under 
police cars during the 1970s as a member of the Symbionese 
Liberation Army. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors allege the act was retaliation for a 1974 shootout  
with police in which six SLA members were killed. The bombs did not 
go off. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Soliah pleaded not guilty to all charges after being  
arrested in June in her St. Paul neighborhood. She remains free on 
bail while awaiting trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Soliah filed an application Thursday in Ramsey County  
District Court seeking the name change. 
</P>
<P>
	A motion filed earlier by Ms. Soliah's attorneys said her use of  
an alias was a ``response to fear of government reprisal for her 
association with SLA members,'' not the indictment. 
</P>
<P>
	In her application, Ms. Soliah asks to correct the birth date  
listed on her Minnesota driver's license and notes she has ``no 
felony convictions.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
