<HEADLINE> Jagr Denies Criticizing U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Jaromir Jagr says he was misquoted in a Czech  
tabloid which reported he said the difference between his native 
Czech Republic and Pittsburgh was ``heaven and hell.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I would never say anything bad about America,'' Jagr told the  
Pittsburgh Post-Gazette. ``America made me what I am. Pittsburgh 
made me what I am.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jagr last season won both the Hart Memorial Trophy as the NHL's  
most valuable player and the Art Ross Trophy as the league's 
scoring champion. He has a $48 million six-year contract, one of 
the richest ever in the league. 
</P>
<P>
	His comments in that article generated criticism in Pittsburgh  
in letters to editor and in radio talk shows. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would be angry too, if I read something like that,'' Jagr  
said. ``I would like to apologize to everybody in Pittsburgh, 
except that I don't have anything to apologize for, since I never 
said anything.'' 
  	   	
</P>
