<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Tries To Keep Airline Aloft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OTTAWA (AP) -- The government has suspended parts of its  
competition laws for 90 days to give its troubled airline industry 
time to seek ways to restructure. 
</P>
<P>
	The move Friday, initiated by financially troubled Canadian  
Airlines Corp., appeared designed to try to keep the Calgary-based 
carrier aloft and maintain national competition. 
</P>
<P>
	But it's not clear how successful the strategy -- which requires  
cooperation between such competitors as Canadian and rival Air 
Canada -- will be. 
</P>
<P>
	Parts of the Competition Act were lifted to let the major  
carriers discuss things such as possible changes to pricing, routes 
and potential alliances, said Industry Minister John Manley. 
</P>
<P>
	Otherwise, the situation could become desperate for Canadian,  
added Transport Minister David Collenette. ``We believe that 
Canadian came to the view that unless some measure of this nature 
was used, then they would start to perhaps not discharge some of 
their service obligations,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Competition Act prohibits industry players from getting  
together to divide up their markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Lifting those rules for a limited time, ``allows the airlines to  
be able to talk to each other, to look at sensitive information, 
without running afoul of the law,'' said Collenette. 
</P>
<P>
	Canadian has lost about $124 million Canadian ($84 million U.S.)  
in the first half of this year alone and nearly went bankrupt in 
1996. 
</P>
<P>
	CEO Kevin Benson has suggested his airline and Air Canada look  
at sharing service on marginal routes to keep both companies alive. 
</P>
<P>
	But Montreal-based Air Canada is doing well financially and may  
not be interested in helping out its competitor, an industry 
analyst warned. 
</P>
<P>
	``What Canadian Airlines wants is to cooperate on routes to  
reduce losses, they want to stop flying on certain routes and share 
aircraft with Air Canada and things like that,'' analyst Jacques 
Kavafian of Yorkton Securities told CBC Newsworld. 
</P>
<P>
	``Canadian wants to talk, but I wonder if (Air Canada) will  
answer the phone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Air Canada has to see benefits for itself before it will talk,  
said Doug Port, a spokesman for Air Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	``The key thing for us is if it makes good long-term business  
sense for us and makes a sustainable benefit for our shareholders, 
then we're interested.'' If Canadian is putting up a for sale sign, 
that could catch Air Canada's eye, he added. 
</P>
<P>
	The government has made it clear previously it would like to  
maintain competition in the industry but Friday ruled out any 
financial aid for Canadian. 
</P>
<P>
	The carrier has hit financial turbulence frequently in its  
12-year history and was bailed out several years ago with an 
investment infusion from American Airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	However, under federal foreign content rules, American only  
could take a maximum 25 percent ownership stake in the airline. 
</P>
<P>
	While there has been widespread speculation Ottawa might  
increase that maximum, Collenette said the government had no such 
plans. 
</P>
<P>
	Canadian desperately needs to begin to show a profit in order to  
attract further investment, noted Kavafian. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
