<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former Democratic Fund-Raiser Fined </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Former Democratic fund-raiser John Huang will  
serve a year's probation but no jail time for his admitted role in 
skirting campaign finance laws. 
</P>
<P>
	A judge warned him to continue aiding federal investigators.  
</P>
<P>
	``These matters should not be taken lightly,'' said U.S.  
District Judge Richard Paez, who also fined Huang $10,000 and 
sentenced him to 500 hours of community service. ``I expect that 
you will cooperate with everyone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Huang pleaded guilty Thursday to conspiracy for violating  
campaign finance laws, a resolution that came in spite of a 
congressman's bid to delay the case. 
</P>
<P>
	``Your honor, I'm very sad and embarrassed by my mistakes that  
have brought disrepute to my family and my community,'' Huang told 
Paez. ``I'm glad the court has given me the opportunity to serve my 
community.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Huang's lawyer, Ty Cobb, said outside court that his client  
would testify before Congress if called, and would perform 
community service by educating the Asian-American community about 
participation in the political process. 
</P>
<P>
	Huang, a former executive of the Jakarta-based Lippo Group, was  
the Democrats' chief fund-raiser for the Asian-American community 
in 1996. He brought in $1.6 million in questionable donations that 
later were returned. 
</P>
<P>
	Specific charges against him involved only an illegal $2,500  
donation to the campaign committee of Los Angeles mayoral candidate 
Michael Woo in 1993, and an illegal $5,000 donation to California 
Victory Fund '94 that was shared by Sen. Dianne Feinstein's 
re-election committee, the Democratic senatorial campaign committee 
and the state Democratic Party. 
</P>
<P>
	Huang could have been sent to prison for five years.  
</P>
<P>
	It was clear from government documents that ``although Mr. Huang  
did not play a minor role, he was not the main leader,'' Cobb said. 
</P>
<P>
	Assistant U.S. Attorney Daniel O'Brien does not suspect Huang of  
involvement in espionage and said that Huang was ``candid and 
truthful'' in his 20 sessions of interviews with government 
investigators. However, the government left open the possibility 
that he could be called as a witness in espionage investigations. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., the chairman of the House Committee on  
Government Reform, last month pressed U.S. Attorney General Janet 
Reno to seek postponement of sentencing for both Huang and 
fund-raiser Charlie Trie because they had not testified before 
Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	The government was granted a six-week delay to assess Trie's  
cooperation. 
</P>
<P>
	Trie has pleaded guilty to two counts involving campaign finance  
violations and pledged to cooperate in the investigation. 
Prosecutors have recommended three years' probation. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
