<HEADLINE> Dalai Lama Gives Lecture at Theater </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Live, from the Beacon Theater, it's ... the  
Dalai Lama? 
</P>
<P>
	At a theater better known for rock n' roll and beer, the exiled  
leader of Tibetan Buddhists gave a four-hour lecture titled 
``Training the Mind/Opening the Heart.'' He started with 
traditional Tibetan chants and a humble assessment of his own role 
in the world. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't feel that I have some higher understanding,'' the  
Nobel Peace Prize winner told a $75-a-head audience. ``I am just a 
small, ordinary Buddhist monk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Dalai Lama plans to teach meditation for three days at the  
Beacon and then speak Sunday in Central Park. More than 20,000 
people are expected to attend that event. 
</P>
<P>
	Actor Richard Gere, a longtime follower, was at his side during  
a news conference in which the Dalai Lama spoke about the purpose 
of his visit. 
</P>
<P>
	``My main purpose for coming here is for some explanation of  
Buddha dharma (divine law), as well as to promote a general 
understanding of human values,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not here to convert people,'' he said. ``I think it's  
better to keep your own tradition. ... Everybody has the potential 
to make a contribution to human development.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
