<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Suicide' Horse Race Canceled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OMAK, Wash. (AP) -- For decades, 20 horses and their riders have  
plunged together down a sandy cliff each August before fording the 
Okanogan River below and dashing toward the finish line in a nearby 
rodeo arena. 
</P>
<P>
	It's called the ``Suicide Race,'' a name animal-rights activists  
have long found apt: Since 1983, 13 horses have been euthanized due 
to race injuries, including one in each of the last three contests. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite a 64-year history, the race has been scrubbed from this  
year's Omak Stampede, a days-long rodeo that began Thursday in this 
small north-central Washington town. Members of the Colville 
Confederated Tribes, whose members largely comprise the daredevil 
field, are boycotting the event in a dispute with rodeo and city 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Indian leaders say that, with each passing year, Stampede  
organizers have pushed their Indian encampment -- the site of 
traditional stick games, dancing and crafts -- farther away from the 
hub of activity at the Stampede. 
</P>
<P>
	Confederation chairwoman Colleen Cawston said the tribe pulled  
out after new city parking regulations directed crowds further from 
the Indian village. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's been numerous things building up,'' she said.  
``Sometimes, you have to make a hard decision to have a better 
future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Organizers cited the boycott in canceling the race last week, as  
well as what they said are dangerously high waters on the Okanogan. 
</P>
<P>
	The cancellation has left a big gap in the Stampede, which  
brings in more than $2 million annually to this windblown town. 
More than 400 residents volunteer their time to paint corrals, 
stencil signs and market the show. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you think of the Omak Stampede, you think of the Suicide  
Race,'' said Warren Willey, a 30-year racegoer from Federal Way, 
Wash. With the race and the Indian encampment gone from this year's 
event, he and his wife Lorraine say they may go to a rodeo in a 
bigger city. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials say Stampede ticket sales are still strong, but a few  
have demanded refunds in the wake of the cancellation and been 
refused. 
</P>
<P>
	Cawston said the Colvilles will welcome the public to their own  
nearby event this weekend, with dancing competitions, a dinner and 
horse endurance races. 
</P>
<P>
	Stampede president Fred Winningham said he's saddened by the  
tribe's absence, and says city and rodeo officials will meet with 
Confederation leaders after this year's Stampede in an effort to 
get them to return next year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have a lot of hope that the three entities can get together  
and cool heads will prevail,'' Winningham said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990813.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 16:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Soar / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Treasury bonds rallied on Friday after a  
government report of tame wholesale prices calmed investor fears 
that the Federal Reserve would have to raise interest rates to try 
to check inflation pressures. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the newly auctioned 30-year Treasury bond shot up  
$11.25 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the 
opposite direction, fell to 6.10 percent from 6.14 percent from 
Thursday's auction. 
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Department reported that prices at the wholesale level  
rose a modest 0.2 percent in July as a huge jump in energy prices 
overwhelmed a sharp drop in food costs. 
</P>
<P>
	The increase in the Producer Price Index, which measures  
inflation pressures before they reach the consumer, matched the 0.2 
percent rise in May. Wholesale prices had actually fallen 0.1 
percent in June, only the second decline this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The modest increase in July eased concerns that the Fed would  
push up rates, an action that could erode the value of fixed-rate 
securities already held by investors. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader secondary market, prices of short-term Treasury  
securities ranged from 3/32 point to 1/4 point higher, and 
intermediate maturities ranged from 7/16 higher to 5/8 point higher, 
reported Bridge Telerate, a financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.74 percent with a  
discount of 4.62 percent, down 0.02 percentage point from late 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Six-month yields were 5.05 percent while the discount was  
unchanged at 4.86 percent. One-year yields were 5.15 percent with a 
discount of 4.90 percent, down 0.04 percentage point from late 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, slipped to 5.06 percent from 5.13 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 3/32 to 113 16/32. The average yield to 
maturity was unchanged at 5.82 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
