<HEADLINE> Penguins Sign Center Straka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- The Pittsburgh Penguins avoided contract  
arbitration Friday by signing center Martin Straka to a multi-year 
contract. 
</P>
<P>
	The contract is expected to more than double Straka's $500,000  
salary of last season. 
</P>
<P>
	By reaching terms, Straka avoided an arbitration hearing  
scheduled Saturday in Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
	Straka, 26, was 11th in the NHL with a career-high 83 points  
last season and played in his first all-star game. He also led the 
Penguins with 11 points, including six goals, in their first-round 
playoff upset of the New Jersey Devils and 15 points in their two 
playoff series. 
</P>
<P>
	Straka has 125 points (54 goals, 71 assists) in two seasons  
since rejoining the Penguins in 1997. He first played for 
Pittsburgh from 1992-95, then was traded to Ottawa and later played 
for the New York Islanders and Florida Panthers before re-signing 
with Pittsburgh as a free agent. 
</P>
<P>
	A native of the Czech Republic, he was the Penguins' first-round  
draft choice in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Defenseman Darius Kasparaitis, forward Kip Miller and center Jan  
Hrdina remain unsigned. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
