<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets ended the week mixed  
Friday, with the key index surging 6 percent in Kuala Lumpur on 
news that Morgan Stanley Capital International will reinstate 
Malaysia into its emerging market indexes in February. 
</P>
<P>
	The Malaysian key Composite Index, which tracks 100 blue-chip  
stocks, rose 43.92 points, or 6.02 percent, to close at 772.88. 
</P>
<P>
	Dealers said the prospects of Malaysia returning to the indexes,  
which are used by some funds to allocate assets and measure 
performance, reversed a recent trend of foreign selling. 
</P>
<P>
	The international investment bank expelled Malaysia from its  
indexes after the country imposed capital controls on Sept. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Taiwan shares also surged as investors flocked back onto the  
bourse after an announcement that Morgan Stanley will raise the 
Taiwan weighting in its indexes. 
</P>
<P>
	The Taipei Stock Exchange's Weighted Stock Price Index rose  
295.81 points, or 4.03 percent, to 7,626.05. 
</P>
<P>
	The increased weighting to 100 percent from 50 percent in the  
closely-monitored MSCI will begin in February and should attract 
greater foreign interest in the market, dealers said. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese shares closed higher for the fifth straight session.  
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo's benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 12.20  
points, or 0.07 percent, to finish the day at 17,435.17. On 
Thursday, the average closed up 211.81 points, or 1.23 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei slipped as low as 17,284.70 early in the morning  
session, after the yen's early surge caused concern about the 
impact of a stronger Japanese currency on corporate earnings, 
traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	A stronger yen makes Japanese exports more expensive abroad and  
thus less competitive, and reduces the dollar-denominated earnings 
of exporting companies when translated into yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, news that Japan's first-quarter economic  
growth was more robust than originally thought sent the dollar 
falling against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar was quoted at 114.92 yen, down 0.76 yen from late  
Thursday in Tokyo and also below its late New York level of 115.62 
yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The Economic Planning Agency announced that Japan's economy grew  
2.0 percent during the January-March period, slightly higher than 
the 1.9 percent growth it initially reported in June. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange closed lower on  
profit-taking. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hang Seng Index, the Hong Kong market's key indicator of  
blue chips, fell 1.3 percent, or 171.57 points, to close at 
12,608.18. On Thursday, the index surged 341.95 points, or 2.7 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading remained thin because many investors stayed on the  
sidelines to await the release of the U.S. price index later Friday 
for signs on whether the U.S. Federal Reserve will raise interest 
rates later this month, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong interest rates usually follow rate movements in the  
United States because the Hong Kong dollar is pegged to the 
American currency. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Share prices closed lower as market sentiment was  
damped by the announcement that Malaysia is to be reinstated in the 
Morgan Stanley Capital International indexes on concerns that fund 
managers could switch their funds to Malaysia. The Straits Times 
Index fell 43.13 points, or 2.14 percent, to 1,969.68. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Share prices closed sharply lower on uncertainties over  
the impact that the Daewoo Group's financial woes may have on the 
markets. The Korea Composite Stock Price Index fell 31.88 points, 
or 3.4 percent, to 917.47. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed slightly higher. The  
benchmark NZSE-40 Capital Index rose 1.21 points, or 0.05 percent, 
to 2,166.01. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine shares closed lower as investors, still  
anxious over a possible increase in both U.S. and domestic interest 
rates, cashed in gains from Thursday's rebound. The Philippine 
Stock Exchange Index fell 16.58 points, or 0.8 percent, to 
2,170.99. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian share prices closed higher, boosted by late  
buying in main resources and financial stocks. The All Ordinaries 
Index closed at 2,958.8, up 14.8 points, or 0.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian shares closed lower. The main Composite  
Index fell 1.3 percent, or 7.509 points, to 557.709. 
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai stock prices closed slightly higher. The Stock  
Exchange of Thailand index rose 2.29 points, or 0.5 percent, to 
423.78. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
