<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rockies' Astacio Returns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Colorado Rockies right-hander Pedro Astacio was  
back on the field Friday, less than 24 hours after turning himself 
in to police following an alleged altercation with his estranged 
wife. 
</P>
<P>
	Astacio, arrested on charges of third-degree assault, a  
misdemeanor, pinch-hit for the Rockies in their 14-13 loss to 
Montreal in the first game of a Friday doubleheader. He is 
scheduled to pitch against the Expos on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Other than to talk about his play, the Rockies weren't saying  
much about Astacio on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Since his arrival in August 1997, Pedro Astacio has been a  
solid performer and person on our club,'' the Rockies said in a 
prepared release. ``At this time, Pedro's teammates and the 
Colorado Rockies organization are in full support of him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Astacio's lawyer, Dan Murphy, has told his client not to speak  
with reporters because of the pending charges. 
</P>
<P>
	``The facts in this complaint are very much in dispute,'' Murphy  
said. ``I am confident that the district attorney's office is not 
going to try this case in the media, nor will Mr. Astacio and I.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Astacio, who is 12-9 with a 4.88 ERA, surrendered to authorities  
in Arapahoe County on Thursday. Police said they received a 911 
call from a woman late Wednesday night. The woman said her 
estranged husband had been arguing with her and hit her in the face 
before leaving the house. 
</P>
<P>
	The suspect later was identified as Astacio.  
</P>
<P>
	Astacio, 29, leads the Rockies in victories and is fourth in the  
National League with 149 strikeouts. He was acquired from the Los 
Angeles Dodgers on Aug. 18, 1997, for infielder Eric Young. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Astacio did not miss a start and topped 200 innings  
for the third straight season. He also became one of only three 
pitchers in Rockies history to win 13 games in a season. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
