<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rugova To Work With U.N. in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Amid a fresh round of violence  
against Serbs and peacekeepers, ethnic Albanian leader Ibrahim 
Rugova assured international leaders today that his party will 
cooperate with the United Nations as well as with rival ethnic 
Albanian groups. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, violence against peacekeepers continued. German  
troops came under machine-gun fire Thursday afternoon during a 
mine-clearing operation near the southwestern town of Suva Reka, 
the German defense ministry said. There were no reported 
casualties. 
</P>
<P>
	A Russian soldier was shot in the shoulder by a sniper on  
Thursday while on guard duty near Gnjilane in southeastern Kosovo, 
officials of KFOR, the international peacekeeping force, said 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	Faced with continuing law and order problems, the U.N. mission  
announced a new regulation today that allows peacekeepers and U.N. 
police to detain and even expel anyone deemed a threat to public 
order. 
</P>
<P>
	Rugova, who has twice won unofficial presidential elections,  
told reporters his Democratic League of Kosovo party, known as the 
LDK, was prepared to work with Kosovo Liberation Army leader Hashim 
Thaci, who has also claimed leadership of the province. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am the elected president of Kosovo,'' Rugova said. ``And we  
will altogether closely cooperate, including Mr. Thaci and others 
and as such we will all participate in international administrative 
bodies until new elections.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But in a joint interview published today in France's three main  
newspapers, Rugova sounded less conciliatory. 
</P>
<P>
	``After NATO arrived in Kosovo, small groups of KLA came down  
from the mountains and went into towns and villages. It's normal 
that they put people in charge,'' Rugova said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now, an agreement must be reached because running the whole  
country cannot be left to the KLA.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rugova's moderate party boycotted the first meeting last month  
of a 12-member council created to promote ethnic cooperation, 
complaining that the party deserved more than two seats. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States and other NATO countries have criticized the  
boycott and put pressure on Rugova to come back from self-imposed 
exile in Italy. He returned less than two weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	In a clear attempt to win favor with Western governments, many  
of whom favor Rugova over the militant KLA, Rugova praised the 
international peacekeeping mission. 
</P>
<P>
	``The situation in Kosovo is continuing in a positive  
direction,'' Rugova said. ``All political forces should fully 
cooperate with KFOR (peacekeepers) and international 
administration, those being the guarantees for the reconstruction 
of a free and democratic Kosovo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also today, more than 10,000 people marched peacefully through  
Pristina, the provincial capital, to urge the international 
community to increase pressure on Serbia to release thousands of 
ethnic Albanians held there for alleged terrorist offenses. 
</P>
<P>
	International officials in the province are counting on the  
cooperation of Rugova and other leaders to help put an end to 
continuing ethnic Albanian attacks on Serbs, as well as scuffles 
with NATO-led peacekeepers. 
</P>
<P>
	Thursday's sniper attack against the Russian soldier took place  
in Robotovo, five miles north of the southeastern Kosovo town of 
Gnjilane, peacekeeping officials said. The soldier was recovering 
today in a Russian military clinic in Kosovo Polje. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, NATO said troops searched two locations Thursday,  
one in Prezovica, where several weapons were seized, including 
three submachine guns, one grenade launcher and several land mines. 
A source familiar with the operation said American troops were 
involved, and it was a Serb weapons cache. 
</P>
<P>
	In Susica, KFOR seized four rifles, 14 hand grenades, two  
anti-tank rockets and 4,000 rounds of ammunition. Another team 
seized five AK-47 rifles from a truck crossing the border from 
Albania at Morini. 
</P>
<P>
	In Cernica, three miles southwest of Gnjilane, an ethnic  
Albanian was found with a 9 mm pistol. Peacekeeping troops searched 
nearby houses, detaining 10 men and confiscating one shotgun, three 
assault rifles, several hand grenades and 600 rounds of ammunition. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, ethnic Albanians opened fire on British  
peacekeepers who were patrolling an area where Serbs had been 
threatened and told to leave. Seven ethnic Albanians were detained 
following the shootout and a car chase in a Serb area just north of 
Pristina, said British Lt. Col. Robin Hodges. Two of the seven were 
wounded by British fire. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
