<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Slides, Tokyo Stocks Higher / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- News that Japan's first-quarter economic growth was  
more robust than originally thought sent the dollar tumbling 
against the yen today. Tokyo share prices gained. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 114.92 yen at late afternoon, down 0.76 yen  
from late Thursday in Tokyo and also below its late New York level 
of 115.62 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 12.20 points,  
or 0.07 percent, to finish the day at 17,435.17. On Thursday, the 
average closed up 211.81 points, or 1.23 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Economic Planning Agency announced that Japan's economy grew  
2.0 percent during the January-March period, slightly higher than 
the 1.9 percent growth it initially reported in June. 
</P>
<P>
	If the growth pace set in the last quarter were to continue, GDP  
would expand 8.1 percent this year, the EPA said. That was up from 
the 7.9 percent announced in June. GDP is the measure of all goods 
and services produced in a country. 
</P>
<P>
	The yen has recently strengthened against the dollar amid  
optimism that the economy is showing signs of emerging from a 
prolonged downturn. today's announcement was likely to enhance such 
thinking. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 122.76 yen, down  
from 123.36 yen late Thursday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar ranged between 114.48 yen and 115.41 yen in today's  
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, share prices finished higher for the fifth  
straight session as the yen's readjustment from morning rallies and 
buying interest among local investors buoyed sentiment. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei initially slipped as low as 17,284.70 early in the  
morning session, after the yen's early surge caused concern about 
the impact of a stronger Japanese currency on corporate earnings, 
traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	A stronger yen makes Japanese exports more expensive abroad and  
thus less competitive, and reduces the dollar-denominated earnings 
of exporting companies when translated into yen. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average gained 1.59  
points to 10,789.39 at Thursday's close. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 4.05 points, or 0.03 percent, to 1,442.49. The 
TOPIX closed up 17.80 points, or 1.25 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 455.06 million shares changed hands on the first  
section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange, up from 322.87 million shares 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Retreating issues outnumbered advancers 617 to 518, while 147  
issues were unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 214 10-year Japanese government  
bond rose to 1.8500 percent from Thursday's finish of 1.8250 
percent, driving its price down to 99.57 yen from 99.78 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
