<HEADLINE> Western Digital Cuts Singapore Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SINGAPORE (AP) -- U.S. disk-drive maker Western Digital Corp.  
said Friday it will cut 2,500 jobs in Singapore by the end of 1999 
and move some operations to Malaysia, where labor costs are lower. 
</P>
<P>
	About 325 employees were laid off Friday, and the next cut will  
be made in early October, said John Coyne, Western Digital's vice 
president of Asian operations. 
</P>
<P>
	The company will move its desktop disk-drive manufacturing  
operations from Chai Chee, its only Singapore facility, to its 
plant in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, by September. The move will reduce 
staff strength in Singapore to 1,700. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kuala Lumpur plant plans to hire 1,700 people, adding to the  
existing 4,300 staff, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Western Digital, based in Irvine, Calif., is one of the largest  
independent manufacturers of PC hard disk drives. It reported sales 
of $2.7 billion last year. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
