<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Accuses Coke in Antitrust Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- Italian authorities have accused Coca-Cola Co. of  
abusing its dominant market position through questionable trade 
practices, according to a preliminary report released today. 
</P>
<P>
	The report alleges Coke offered discounts to retailers who  
displayed its products more prominently than those of competitors. 
It also says the company allegedly discriminated against 
wholesalers who refused to displace competitor's products. 
</P>
<P>
	Coke's marketing practices have come under scrutiny of  
regulators in several countries in recent months. In July, European 
Union officials raided Coke's offices in Austria, Denmark, Germany 
and Great Britain as part of an inquiry into the company's 
marketing practices. Authorities in Chile and the United States are 
also looking into allegations of unfair practices by Coke. 
</P>
<P>
	Italy's antitrust authorities have been investigating Coca-Cola  
Co. for unfair business practices for more than a year, Italian 
officials said today. The investigation was spurred by a complaint 
from rival PepsiCo. 
</P>
<P>
	Coke has until Oct. 29 to answer the accusations in the report  
it received from Italian regulators. The authority said it would 
issue a final ruling in the case by mid-December. 
</P>
<P>
	If Coca-Cola is found to have violated fair business practices  
it could be fined up to 10 percent of its annual sales in Italy, or 
$83 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Alessandro Magnoni, spokesman for Coca-Cola Italia in Milan,  
said the company is aware of the inquiry. 
</P>
<P>
	Coca-Cola's products account for about 46 percent of Italy's  
soft drink market, Italian news reports said. 
</P>
<P>
	Pepsi complained to Italian authorities in November 1997 that  
Coke was unfairly and systematically trying to exclude it from that 
market. The antitrust inquiry started in June 1998. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
