<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Frankel May Not Have Invested Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) -- Fugitive financier Martin R. Frankel,  
accused of embezzling billions of dollars from insurance companies 
in five states, may have fled with as little as $50 million, a 
newspaper reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest estimate, though still a significant amount, is a  
fraction of the $3 billion he originally is accused of stealing. 
</P>
<P>
	Citing a source close to the federal investigation, the  
Greenwich Time reported Thursday that Frankel may not have invested 
any of the insurance company money he was paid to manage. 
</P>
<P>
	The source told the newspaper that Frankel may have suffered  
from ``trader's block'' -- a psychological inability to complete a 
financial transaction -- and sought help from a hypnotist and at 
least one psychiatrist to deal with the problem. 
</P>
<P>
	Frankel, who remains at large, apparently had a computer program  
which would comb through actual transactions to create the 
appearance of huge returns on investments. 
</P>
<P>
	The program ``monitored actual market trades, so when the client  
got the statement and checked on a particular security -- by looking 
in The Wall Street Journal, for example -- the computer-generated 
earning would match exactly with what it would have actually 
earned,'' the source said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Say he wanted to show an insurance company their investments  
earned $20 million. The program would come up with the trades to 
match that amount,'' the source said. 
</P>
<P>
	The statements Frankel sent to investors apparently led to the  
early estimates of losses, which ranged from more than $200 million 
to as much as $3 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	When insurance regulators in April began questioning the  
legitimacy of Frankel's Liberty National Securities, the brokerage 
he allegedly ran from a fortified mansion in Greenwich, regulators 
apparently believed the insurance investments had grown to as much 
as $950 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``But it appears that all Marty took was whatever the insurance  
companies first gave him to invest,'' the source said, speaking on 
condition of anonymity. ``So we're not looking at billions of 
dollars, or even hundreds of millions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As much as $2 billion more was supposedly missing from a  
charitable foundation Frankel had created; that money, too, may 
have existed only on paper, investigators said. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal grand jury has been investigating Frankel since  
mid-May. He disappeared in early May and remains on the loose. A 
warrant has been issued for his arrest on fraud charges. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990813.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 16:00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Big Oil Cos. Stop Nigerian Pumping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- A joint venture between Texaco Inc. and Chevron  
Corp. was forced to stop pumping oil off the coast of Nigeria on 
Friday because angry residents in the area blocked supplies from 
reaching the company's platforms. 
</P>
<P>
	Texaco Overseas Petroleum Co. of Nigeria Unlimited, or Topcon,  
declared force majeure and ceased production at its five oil rigs 
near the Niger River delta, said Rachel Moore, a London-based 
Texaco spokeswoman. Companies declare force majeure when an 
unpredictable, external event prevents them from meeting 
contractual obligations. 
</P>
<P>
	Topcon typically pumps about 50,000 barrels of crude oil a day  
at its platforms near the city of Warri in southern Nigeria. 
</P>
<P>
	``Production won't be resumed until we consider it safe and  
secure to do so,'' Moore said. 
</P>
<P>
	The company evacuated all employees from its rigs after the  
latest in a series of disruptions of its crude production. 
</P>
<P>
	Protesters recently commandeered a helicopter subcontracted to  
Topcon and kidnapped its six passengers and crew members. All 
hostages were later released, Moore said. 
</P>
<P>
	Residents in the southern Niger Delta, site of most of the  
country's drilling, have grown increasingly bitter over 
exploitation of the oil resources. They accuse the central 
government of greed, while their region is plagued by lack of 
development and abject living conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	The protests -- including sabotage of pipeline installations --  
have cost Nigeria about $1 billion in oil revenue so far this year, 
industry leaders said after a meeting Thursday with the state-owned 
Nigeria National Petroleum Corp. to discuss ways to create a 
peaceful environment for oil operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Also at the meeting were senior officials of Shell Petroleum  
Development Corp., Chevron, Elf Aquitaine SA, Mobil, Texaco, 
Nigeria Liquefied Natural Gas Ltd., Addax Petroleum Development 
Co., Pan Ocean and Agip. 
</P>
<P>
	The managing director of the Nigeria National Petroleum Corp.,  
Jackson Gauis-Obaseki, said Thursday that the violence had gone 
beyond normal communal unrest. 
</P>
<P>
	``When people start hijacking helicopters, kidnapping people and  
asking for ransom, it is no longer a protest,'' he said. ``What 
we're dealing with now is the perpetration of crime and banditry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Gauis-Obaseki also said oil companies bore some  
responsibility for degrading the environment and not helping to 
alleviate unemployment. 
</P>
<P>
	He also blamed community leaders, who he said received large  
sums of money from the oil companies without passing them on to 
their people. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nigerian National Oil Co. owns 60 percent of Topcon. Texaco  
and Chevron each has a 20 percent stake. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990813.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 20:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rapids 1, Mutiny 0 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- Jorge Dely Valdes scored with 29 seconds to  
play Friday night and give the Colorado Rapids a 1-0 victory over 
the Tampa Bay Mutiny. 
</P>
<P>
	Dely Valdes put home a header following a pass from Kevin  
Anderson. It was his ninth goal of the season and snapped the 
Rapids' 301-minute goal-scoring drought in regulation. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mutiny played shorthanded over the final 55 minutes after  
Manny Lagos received a red card for a hand ball. On the ensuing 
penalty kick, Tampa Bay goalkeeper Scott Garlick made a lunging 
save of a shot by Wolde Harris. 
</P>
<P>
	The match was delayed twice in the first half because of injured  
players. 
</P>
<P>
	Colorado midfielder Ross Paule was taken from the field on a  
stretcher in the 42nd minute with a concussion and eye injury after 
an airborne collision with Tampa Bay's Ritchie Kotschau. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's my understanding he has a cut under his eye, a possible  
fractured, depressed cheekbone and a concussion,'' Rapids coach 
Glenn Myernick said of Paule's injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	Tampa Bay captain Dominic Kinnear hurt his neck in the 28th  
minute. The injury, which a team spokesman said is not considered 
serious, occurred when Kinnear made head-to-head contact with Dely 
Valdes. 
</P>
<P>
	``The doctor felt like he's going to be OK,'' Mutiny coach Tim  
Hankinson said of Kinnear. ``Whether that means by Wednesday (next 
game at New England) or OK in general, we'll have to see. Dom has a 
big heart and a hard head and I'm sure he'll be fighting to line up 
next week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kinnear and Paule were taken to Tampa's Memorial Hospital for  
X-rays. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
