<DOCNO> APW19990813.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 00:30:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Rockets Mum on Pippen Trade Demand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- A report that Scottie Pippen wants to be traded  
to Phil Jackson's Los Angeles Lakers is just another bump in 
Houston Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich's rebuilding job. 
</P>
<P>
	``This job, I've found, has a lot of obstacles in it, and this  
is just another one,'' Tomjanovich said Thursday. ``We deal with 
them the best way we can. I just try to stay positive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tomjanovich would not, however, answer questions about whether  
Pippen wants to stay in Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	``You guys would have to ask him that,'' he said. ``I do my  
things privately with my players, and these things basically stay 
private.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pippen's agent, Jimmy Sexton, told the Houston Chronicle that  
the Rockets and Lakers discussed a trade and that Pippen hopes to 
be reunited with Jackson. 
</P>
<P>
	The former Chicago Bulls star, acquired by Houston in a  
sign-and-trade agreement last January, has complained about his 
role in the Rockets' offense. 
</P>
<P>
	During the first season of a five-year contract, Pippen averaged  
14.5 points, the lowest since his rookie year. He hit a career-low 
43.2 percent of his shots. 
</P>
<P>
	But Sexton told the newspaper that Pippen has nothing against  
the Rockets. 
</P>
<P>
	``He and Phil Jackson have an extremely close relationship from  
11 years working together day in and day out,'' he said. ``Scottie 
is an attractive piece of the puzzle for a lot of teams, but it 
probably would not be an issue if Phil Jackson was not there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tomjanovich said he plans to tailor the Rockets' game plan to  
Pippen next season. 
</P>
<P>
	``With Scottie Pippen, (we) probably did more than any other  
player we've acquired ... to accommodate,'' he said. ``You know, 
there are going to be plays where you have to throw the ball to the 
other guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sexton did not return a call Thursday from The Associated Press,  
and Lakers officials refused comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading Pippen wouldn't be easy. Any deal would require  
adjustments to offset the $14.8 million he counts against the 
salary cap. 
</P>
<P>
	Pippen reportedly told Robert Barr, the Rockets' senior  
executive vice president for basketball affairs, to seek a trade 
with the Lakers. 
</P>
<P>
	Sources have told the Houston Chronicle that the Lakers offered  
Glen Rice and former Houston forward Robert Horry, a deal the 
Rockets repeatedly have turned down. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything is difficult now,'' Rockets vice president Carroll  
Dawson told the newspaper. ``It's all harder than it used to be. It 
used to be if somebody had a bad practice, you could trade him that 
night. The bigger the salary, the more involved it gets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barr, who had been with the team for 16 years, resigned  
Wednesday, saying he needs a break from basketball and wants to 
spend more time with his family. Barr also has refused comment on 
Pippen's future. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite disappointing offensive numbers for 1999, Pippen  
averaged 6.5 rebounds and was named to the NBA All-Defensive first 
team. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990813.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 16:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AT&AMP;T Sues Intel Over Phone Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- When Ma Bell gets tough with deadbeat customers,  
she's not kidding around. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T Corp., the nation's largest telecommunications company,  
sued Intel Corp., the world's largest computer chip maker, for 
allegedly stiffing it on a $5,164.07 long-distance phone bill. 
</P>
<P>
	That might seem like pocket change for AT&AMP;T, a $64 billion  
company that is spending more than $100 billion to provide phone 
service through cable TV lines, or for Intel, with $27 billion in 
annual sales. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T initially refused Friday to explain why it went to court  
earlier this week to resolve such a seemingly trivial matter 
between corporate giants. But later in the day the company withdrew 
the suit, saying it was a foul-up that occurred because Intel's 
phone bill was inadvertently sent to a collection agency. 
</P>
<P>
	In the suit filed Wednesday in U.S. District Court in San Jose,  
Calif., AT&AMP;T alleged Intel refused to pay a bill for the seven 
months ended June 27. It also sought attorney fees. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just going to find out what happened and try to resolve  
it with the customer,'' AT&AMP;T spokesman Randy Shields said after the 
lawsuit was withdrawn. 
</P>
<P>
	``It sounds like an unfortunate mistake, and we'll move on from  
here,'' said Chuck Mulloy, a spokesman for the Santa Clara, 
Calif.-based computer chip giant. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeffrey Kagan, an independent industry analyst based in Atlanta,  
speculated that AT&AMP;T may have wanted to make an example out of 
Intel so other corporate customers pay up. ``This may wind up 
costing them more than they'll pay for it, but they can't afford to 
have a precedent set,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T probably isn't going to cut off Intel's service, but it has  
been getting tougher with customers. Last year, for instance, the 
company began charging residential customers a minimum of $3 a 
month even if they don't make any long-distance phone calls. 
</P>
<P>
	To be sure, the company needs to cut costs amid a torrid  
acquisition spree, including its purchases of the TCI and MediaOne 
cable TV networks, which vaults it into the position of No. 1 cable 
TV company in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	But next to those moves, a lawsuit seemed a bit out of  
proportion, said Kagan. ``What are they going to be complaining 
about next?'' he asked. ``They have bigger fish to fry.'' 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990813.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 17:10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Forbes Gains With Pricey Organizing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Pat Buchanan was just settling into the  
booth for his radio interview, but blanched a bit at the lead-in 
item the station broadcast -- a voter turnout commercial for Steve 
Forbes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Forbes has moved up,'' sighed Buchanan, referring to the  
progress the wealthy publisher has made in the race for the 
Republican presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Using many of the tools from the business world, Forbes has  
built an expensive and high-tech campaign organization that's 
getting increasing respect in political circles, and making his 
campaign for the GOP presidential nomination a serious one. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes insists the issue is one of a message that's beginning to  
resonate. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we are getting our message out and, ultimately, that  
is how you win,'' Forbes said. 
</P>
<P>
	While virtually every campaign has a Web site and uses computers  
heavily, Forbes takes high-tech to a higher level, and aides said 
it's central to his campaign strategy. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're trying to push that envelope,'' said political director  
Bill Dal Col. ``We're using the Internet for the 2000 election like 
they did TV for the '60 election.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Forbes pulled into the Iowa State Fair on Friday with all  
the garish splash of campaigns past, his bus was draped with 
banners and had loudspeakers blaring ``Stars and Stripes Forever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But inside, there was a world-class communication effort using  
satellite phone technology which allows him to stay constantly in 
contact with Internet even when his bus is rolling through remote 
parts of the state. That allowed sophisticated marketing techniques 
like updating the campaign's database in real time as new backers 
are garnered. 
</P>
<P>
	It also allows an unfiltered vehicle for the campaign's message  
to find its way to backers. 
</P>
<P>
	Dal Col said the Internet has proven to be a useful tool for  
interactive work with potential backers, communicating with them 
but also luring them in. 
</P>
<P>
	``We used our Web site to get 25,000 volunteers,'' said Dal Col.  
</P>
<P>
	Forbes made a splash in the last election cycle with a  
relentless television assault on then-front-runner Bob Dole. 
</P>
<P>
	This time, Forbes is spending heavily on advertising, but it's a  
far more sophisticated campaign. He's running traditional 30-second 
spots where he talks about his ideas, but also featuring warm and 
fuzzy spots where his daughters talk about their father, and also 
using the often overlooked medium of radio. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes also aired a live, 30-minute ``town hall'' meeting Friday  
featuring some of the state's leading social conservatives in a 
call-in format on the eve of a big GOP straw poll. 
</P>
<P>
	That was designed ``to get to know Steve Forbes up close and  
personal,'' the spot said. He pushed hard on economic issues, but 
also made it clear he was a staunch abortion opponent and spoke 
fondly of his weeks of intense grassroots campaigning in the state. 
</P>
<P>
	``They want real change,'' said Forbes. ``You go out on a trip  
like this and you know that people know a lot more than we give 
them credit for.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990813.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 00:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FAA Unveils Plans To Reduce Delays </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Aviation Administration hopes a  
new plan will end this summer's spate of air traffic delays, which 
have left airline executives and some passengers fuming. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency, in a letter to the nation's major carriers, said one  
element of the plan will be to have its command center in Herndon, 
Va., start coordinating traffic flows in bad weather. That should 
eliminate conflicts between local centers spread across the 
country. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the FAA will let the center minimize the use of  
extra buffers that are otherwise routinely established between 
planes in bad weather. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency has also pledged to develop a policy in which  
airplanes held on the ground because of bad weather will be given a 
specific projected departure time. Such information can then be 
relayed to passengers. 
</P>
<P>
	Airline passengers, who have suffered through hundreds of delays  
this summer, should start seeing the effect of the changes within 
the next several weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, the FAA said a long-term improvement hinges on the  
continuation of the agency's $13 billion modernization program, as 
well as congressional approval of a plan to renew the agency for 
another five years. Included in that ``reauthorization'' bill, now 
stalled in the Senate, is language that would let the FAA start 
charging fees for some of its services. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we and the airlines developed is a short-term program  
that we believe will have the effect of reducing the delays,'' 
Eliot Brenner, the agency's chief spokesman, said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all agree that what's needed over the longer term is the  
FAA's steady program modernizing the system, which is why the 
long-term reauthorization is so important to us,'' Brenner said. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent months, airlines have united in protest about air  
traffic delays, saying they are costing them money and contributing 
to rising passenger discontent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Air Transport Association, the airlines' trade group,  
estimates the more than 308,000 air traffic control delays last 
year cost the industry $4.1 billion -- up from $3.9 billion in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will never have the on-time record we want unless the (FAA)  
can ensure that their system keeps up with growth,'' Jim Goodwin, 
chairman of United Airlines' parent, UAL Corp., said in Chicago 
last month. 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA, which runs the air traffic control system and is  
responsible for ensuring passenger safety, contends that only 3 
percent of air traffic problems are attributed to equipment 
troubles. It says three-quarters of all delays are caused by bad 
weather, especially in the summer, when thunderstorms are common. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, the agency is in the midst of a long-awaited  
program to upgrade its computers and displays in en route centers 
and facilities controlling traffic near airports. The FAA is also 
studying technology that would free pilots from the limits of the 
existing system of aerial highways and let planes fly routes picked 
by the pilots, a concept called ``free flight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter to American Airlines President Donald Carty, which  
mirrored letters sent to other airline executives, FAA 
Administrator Jane Garvey said the agency benefited from the 
carriers' suggestions. 
</P>
<P>
	``The FAA is committed to do its part to follow through on the  
action items on which the airlines and we have agreed,'' Garvey 
wrote. ``Those actions, along with individual airline efforts to 
review and amend internal policies and procedures as appropriate, 
will lead us toward the improvements we are both seeking.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990813.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 17:10:12 </DATE_TIME>
