<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Talks With Union Begin at Boeing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Job security, control of pension funds and work  
schedules are at the top of the slate as Boeing Co. and its largest 
union head into round-the-clock negotiations Monday on a new 
three-year contract. 
</P>
<P>
	The talks come at a crucial time for Boeing, which is facing  
tough competition from Airbus Industrie to build planes for the 
world's airlines. If a strike occurs, it could cut short Boeing's 
financial recovery following two troubled years. 
</P>
<P>
	Plans call for a final company offer by Aug. 27 and a union vote  
Sept. 1, when ``it's either settled or it's strike,'' said Dick 
Schneider, head negotiator for the International Association of 
Machinists and Aerospace Workers. The union represents 44,000 of 
Boeing's 210,000 workers worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	``Both parties are there to negotiate a contract, not a  
strike,'' Schneider said. 
</P>
<P>
	The current contract expires Sept. 2. The Machinists have gone  
on strike in two of the past three contract talks, most recently 
for 69 days in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing is having a banner year, with plans to deliver a record  
620 planes in 1999. But the company, under pressure from rival 
European consortium Airbus, also has been working for over a year 
to streamline its operation. 
</P>
<P>
	For the union, Schneider said Friday, ``the key issue is job  
security for our members.'' Thousands of jobs were eliminated 
already this year, and 1,334 additional workers in the Puget Sound 
area got notices last week that they will be laid off in 60 days. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing spokesman Peter Conte said the work force ebb and flow is  
based on production rates that are keyed to market forces. Conte 
said there was an unusual surge in hiring in 1996 and 1997 ``as 
shops were ramping up production'' and trying to resolve production 
problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Schneider said that while the union understands Boeing must  
remain competitive with Airbus, the Machinists want reductions in 
the practice of farming out work to subcontractors not covered by 
the contract. 
</P>
<P>
	The average machinist at Boeing earns $40,000 a year, not  
counting benefits or overtime. 
</P>
<P>
	The company views outsourcing as critical to remaining  
competitive, ``which enhances job security for thousands of Boeing 
employees,'' Conte said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a memo to managers, however, company negotiator Jerry Calhoun  
said Boeing is willing to work with the union on the subcontracting 
issue. 
</P>
<P>
	Calhoun said one way to provide greater job security is to go to  
a seven-day, 24-hour-a-day work schedule, something the union 
opposes. 
</P>
<P>
	Since World War II, Boeing has basically run a five-day  
operation. Those working weekend shifts are paid overtime. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bottom line is the company would save $400 million over  
the three-year agreement in overtime costs'' with a seven-day 
schedule, Schneider said, noting that ``candidly, we have workers 
who like to work a lot of overtime.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Conte said the details of ``alternative work schedules'' remain  
to be worked out at the table. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has been characterized as a company desire to no longer pay  
overtime,'' he said. ``It would perhaps reduce some levels of 
overtime but would by no means eliminate it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fewer than 30 percent of U.S. employees work the so-called  
standard Monday-to-Friday daytime schedule, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The union contends that evenly dividing the workforce among  
three shifts going five days a week -- rather than the current 
practice of having the majority on days -- would produce the same 
results as a seven-day week. 
</P>
<P>
	The pension fund issue is one of control: Boeing has it, the  
union wants it. 
</P>
<P>
	The Boeing pension plan contains $15 billion for both the  
Machinists and about 1,400 salaried employees. Its liabilities -- 
funds needed to cover current and future retirees -- are about $11 
billion, Conte said. 
</P>
<P>
	The union wants future pension contributions to go to its own  
National Pension Plan. Schneider cited concerns over a possible 
Boeing buyout by corporate raiders who could liquidate the pension 
fund, as well as possible misuse of fund proceeds by the company. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing says such a switch would cost $45 million to $50 million  
a year -- and leave extremely vulnerable the 1,400 salaried 
employees covered by the plan. And while a robust stock market has 
kept the fund healthy without recent company contributions, 
``Boeing does not violate those funds,'' Conte said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
