<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tiffany Expert Guilty in Grave Scam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A leading expert on Tiffany windows has been  
convicted of teaming with a graveyard bandit to sell valuable 
stained-glass stolen from cemeteries. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury found Alastair J. Duncan guilty on Thursday of all six  
counts against him, including conspiracy. He faces up to 10 years 
in prison on each count when he is sentenced Oct. 27. 
</P>
<P>
	The nine-day trial in U.S. District Court pitted the reputation  
of the 57-year-old Duncan, a respected art expert, against the word 
of a high school dropout who claimed to have stolen more than 80 
graveyard pieces over 15 years. 
</P>
<P>
	During the trial, the jury learned that mausoleums and  
cemeteries are inviting targets for the theft of glass created by 
Louis Comfort Tiffany because they often have little or no 
security. 
</P>
<P>
	Anthony Casamassina testified that he broke into cemeteries and  
mausoleums, snatching 20 to 30 stained glass windows and several 
vases, statues and pedestals since the mid-1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	Casamassina said he had once worked as a caretaker at a cemetery  
until he was fired after stealing a marble pedestal. 
</P>
<P>
	Although he was a high school dropout, Casamassina was  
well-schooled in the artistry of graveyards, having used one of 
Duncan's books to learn about Tiffany glass and which cemeteries 
held some of the better works. 
</P>
<P>
	At the center of the case was a 9-foot-tall, 5-foot-wide Tiffany  
window Casamassina had stolen in 1993 from a New York cemetery. 
</P>
<P>
	Benjamin Brafman, Duncan's lawyer, was unimpressed by the  
government's case, which included conversations secretly taped by 
Casamassina, saying his client had no idea he had purchased a 
stolen Tiffany window. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know what's pathetic about the government's case?'' he  
said during his closing argument. ``Eighty percent of the 
documentation that they showed you as evidence came from my client. 
Mr. Duncan calls the FBI. He learns that the window he has dealt 
with is stolen. He doesn't run to destroy the window. He doesn't go 
burn all of the documentation that a guilty person would do. He 
calls the FBI.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Assistant U.S. Attorney Stephanos Bibas told the jury that  
when Duncan learned the FBI was investigating its disappearance, he 
``rushes into the FBI spinning a story, telling part truth, part 
lie.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Duncan was no stranger to the FBI, but the last time he was  
helping agents, not being investigated by them. He aided federal 
investigators probing the theft of a Tiffany landscape ``River of 
Life'' window from an Indianapolis mausoleum in the mid-'90s. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
