<HEADLINE> Slain Postman in Calif. To Be Buried </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTEREY PARK, Calif. (AP) -- Ismael Ileto clutched his wife's  
hand as he listened to the details of his brother's murder -- how 
the postal worker was chosen at random by a white supremacist and 
gunned down, police say, because he was of Filipino descent. 
</P>
<P>
	Unable to speak, he looked down, shook his head and bit his lip.  
</P>
<P>
	``There's no sense in it. We wouldn't want anyone to go through  
what we've been going through,'' said Ismael's wife, Deena Ileto. 
</P>
<P>
	As more relatives arrived from Chicago and New York for the  
funeral, planned for Saturday, the family of 39-year-old Joseph 
Santos Ileto tried to come to terms with the agonizing pain of 
their loss -- and a fear that speaking out might lead to more 
violence. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want any threats after this from the group this  
person's from,'' said Ismael Ileto, sitting with his family at 
their mother's house in this suburb east of Los Angeles. ``Now that 
we have a son, I'm kind of looking behind my back. It could happen 
to you, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The family had purposely avoided watching a televised news  
conference Thursday where a charge of murder and five counts of 
attempted murder were announced against Buford O. Furrow Jr., who 
has a history of mental problems and ties to hate groups. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors say Furrow shot five people at a Jewish community  
center Tuesday, then an hour later killed Ileto as he delivered 
mail in a San Fernando Valley neighborhood. Ismael and Deena Ileto 
had to tell Joseph's mother, Lilian, of her son's death. 
</P>
<P>
	Furrow is accused of shooting Ileto nine times, several to the  
back of his head. He allegedly confessed that the postal worker was 
a good ``target of opportunity'' to kill because he was non-white 
and worked for the federal government. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just want these people not to hurt people anymore, no  
matter what race or color,'' Deena Ileto said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
