<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jerry Springer Rules Out Senate Run </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Television talk show host Jerry Springer has  
decided that he won't give up his world of drag queens, cheating 
lesbians and bisexual love triangles for a chance to become Senator 
Springer. 
</P>
<P>
	His office in Chicago issued a statement Friday popping that  
political trial balloon because of contractual obligations and his 
new talk-and-variety show about to debut in England. 
</P>
<P>
	Springer issued a statement that it was ``impractical if not  
impossible for me to make a run for the Senate at this time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Springer, who once was a Cincinnati politician, had been courted  
by some of his associates in Ohio to run for the U.S. Senate after 
several current members of Congress and former candidates decided 
not to run in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	With Springer out of the mix, Democrats may find a more  
traditional candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think Democrats ought to be relieved,'' said political  
analyst Stuart Rothenberg. ``It would have been an embarrassment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The freshman Republican who might have faced Springer in the  
next election, Sen. Mike DeWine, had no comment, according to a 
spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	Ohio GOP Chairman Robert Bennett said for Democrats to even  
consider the idea of a Springer candidacy demonstrated: ``Name 
recognition and deep pockets are their only criteria.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ohio newspapers had huffed their outrage at the prospect of a  
Springer Senate race, and some Ohio Democrats who had been longing 
for a deep-pockets candidate said they couldn't accept Springer. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Ted Strickland, of Ohio's 6th District, said Springer's  
television program was damaging and exploitative, and he could have 
nothing to do with the man. 
</P>
<P>
	Springer's spokeswoman, Linda Shafran, said the man who was host  
of that is arguably America's most controversial talk show was 
working on a late-night show tentatively set to debut in England on 
the ITV network, in September. 
</P>
<P>
	``Springer at 10 p.m.'' will be like ``The Tonight Show,'' with  
a combination of talk segments and comedy sketches, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 55-year-old Springer was mayor of Cincinnati for two terms  
and ran for governor in 1982 before starting a TV career. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
