<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 17:06:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Newport Hopes To Host America's Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWPORT, R.I. (AP) -- The sailors are confident, hungry and a bit  
nervous, too. And why not? It's been 16 years since the New York 
Yacht Club and this city lost the America's Cup, yacht racing's 
holy grail. 
</P>
<P>
	Once proud defenders, they are now challengers for a prize the  
yacht club owned for 132 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Young America, the yacht club's racing team, has spent more than  
three years testing and tweaking boat designs and strategies to 
reclaim the Cup. On Friday, a model of a new narrower hull was 
unveiled. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have what it takes to win, the desire and the commitment,''  
said John K. Marshall, president of Young America. But even more 
than that, he admits winning takes a fast boat. 
</P>
<P>
	Marshall and the rest of Young America must wait until they test  
their two boats in October's challenge races in New Zealand to know 
for sure if they have that. 
</P>
<P>
	``Until we see (results from) that first race, we won't know,''  
he said. ``That's what makes it such a great race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The next race for the Cup is in New Zealand in February 2000. A  
sailing team from that country won the Cup at San Diego in 1995 in 
dominating fashion. San Diego's loss may be Newport's gain, since 
the winning team gets to take the Cup home. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Yacht Club has said Newport would again play host  
to the races if Young America wins. 
</P>
<P>
	First, however, Young America must beat racing teams from 10  
countries, along with entries from San Diego and San Francisco, in 
the challenge races. The winner takes on New Zealand next year. 
</P>
<P>
	David Gordon, Newport's mayor, made sure he was on hand Friday  
for the crew's official sendoff. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Cup returns to Newport, the boost in tourism and spending  
by racing teams and their suppliers could pump up to $50 million 
into the local economy, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``But more than the economic impact is the pride and tradition  
associated with having it here,'' he said. ``We are the home of the 
America's Cup.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Marshall said the Young America boats will have a narrow, carbon  
fiber hull and a steel keel made of a special alloy. The sides of 
the hulls will be marked by shark images. 
</P>
<P>
	The boats are designed to be versatile in difficult and  
constantly changing racing conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	Marshall said defending the Cup had became sort of ``routine''  
for New York Yacht Club teams before they lost it in 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	He hopes that kind of letdown will be felt by New Zealand, which  
has never had to defend the Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're out to reclaim a national prize,'' he said. ``That's  
very energizing.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
