<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Iridium Consortium Files Chapter 11 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Iridium LLC, the ambitious satellite-based  
mobile phone network, is finally relenting to the call of 
bankruptcy court. 
</P>
<P>
	With a shove from its creditors and a reassuring nod from  
parental guardian Motorola, the consortium announced Friday that it 
would restructure a crushing $3 billion debt load under Chapter 11 
of the federal bankruptcy code. 
</P>
<P>
	The move hardly came as a surprise, since there was no chance  
the venture would meet the subscriber targets stipulated by its 
loan agreements. Many observers were expecting that Iridium would 
miss a $90 million interest payment due on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, it was a disappointment after weeks of talks designed to  
avoid the blemish of bankruptcy, which could further discourage 
investors and customers -- especially with a rival satellite venture 
named Globalstar due to introduce service in the coming months. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only reason they were trying to avoid bankruptcy was the  
stigma associated with it,'' said Phelps Hoyt, a corporate bond 
analyst for KDP Investment Advisors in Montpelier, Vt. 
</P>
<P>
	``The parties actually weren't that far from coming to an  
agreement,'' said Hoyt, adding that the bankruptcy reorganization 
will give Iridium some breathing room. ``Everybody loses if they 
call it a day and liquidate this company.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Iridium's stock plunged $1.18 3/4 to $3.06 1/4 on Friday before the  
Nasdaq Stock Market halted trading. Shares are now worth less than 
5 percent of what they sold for slightly more than a year ago, when 
Iridium's prospects seemed so bright. 
</P>
<P>
	The first hint of trouble came four months ago when Iridium, the  
first of four satellite-based telephone networks to introduce 
service, reported that it had signed up only 10,000 subscribers 
since its November launch -- a fraction of the subscriber forecasts 
used to secure Iridium's loans. 
</P>
<P>
	Early Iridium customers complained about complex calling plans  
with rates of up to $9 a minute, as well as big clunky phones that 
were in short supply, cost $3,500 and were confusing to operate. 
</P>
<P>
	In June, the company introduced a simplified rate structure,  
slashing charges as much as 65 percent. Motorola and the Japanese 
company Kyocera cut the prices on their Iridium phones by more than 
half. New, sleeker models are expected soon. 
</P>
<P>
	It's unclear how well the new marketing plan has worked, but the  
change in strategy clearly came too late to persuade Iridium's 
lenders. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, two days after the company announced that it had  
again violated the terms of its loan agreements, a group of Iridium 
bondholders filed a petition to force a bankruptcy reorganization. 
</P>
<P>
	Soon after, Iridium announced that it would go voluntarily.  
</P>
<P>
	Motorola, Iridium's largest investor and operator of Iridium's  
66-satellite system, said in a statement Friday that it would 
continue to provide its full operational support for Iridium and 
all current and future subscribers during the reorganization. 
</P>
<P>
	``Given the progress being made to date to restructure Iridium's  
capital structure, we are optimistic that a restructuring plan can 
be accomplished within 30 days,'' Motorola said in Iridium's 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the mobile phone maker also warned that its willingness  
to provide additional financial support to Iridium ``continues to 
depend on a substantial degree of participation in a financial 
restructuring by all other relevant parties with a significant 
financial interest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While the 30-day forecast may prove too optimistic with so many  
investors and so many creditors to satisfy, experts said the case 
needn't drag on for months and months. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you have that much money and that much brain power at  
work, chances are you will find a solution,'' said Steve Towbin, a 
bankruptcy attorney at D'Ancona and Pflaum in Chicago. ``Nobody in 
a situation like this would want a liquidation,'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
