<HEADLINE> Kia Motors Recalls U.S. Sedans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Kia Motors is recalling more than 32,000 sedans  
because of a flaw in fuel system hoses. 
</P>
<P>
	The Korea-based company has been notifying consumers since  
mid-July that the fuel vapor hoses in its 1996 and 1997 Sephias 
could leak and must be replaced, said Tim McCurdy, manager of 
quality assurance for the company's U.S. division. 
</P>
<P>
	The flaw will be repaired at no cost to consumers. It will cost  
the company an estimated $75 per each vehicle to correct the 
problem through its network of 530 dealers nationwide, McCurdy 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kia was notified of the problem last month by the California Air  
Resources Board, which found problems with the hose during a 
routine test. 
  	   	
