<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> European Stocks Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- European stocks closed Friday at a three-week  
high, after United States inflation data calmed fears of a sharp 
interest rate hike. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. government said producer prices for July rose 0.2  
percent, sparking a surge in New York bond and equity markets. That 
prompted a rally in stock markets across Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	London's FTSE 100 index of blue-chip shares closed up 1.5  
percent at 6245.1. Frankfurt's Xetra DAX index rose 1.8 percent to 
5,219.43 and the Paris CAC-40 index climbed 1.6 percent to 
4,434.28. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of 592 European companies rose 4.91  
points, or 1.6 percent, to close at 304.60, the highest since July 
22, when it closed at 306.75. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial services stocks were the best performers Friday, with  
a gain of 3.6 percent in the index. Pharmaceuticals followed gains 
in New York Thursday, sending the index up 2.6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index, which tracks 297 companies in  
countries that joined the single currency, closed up 5.21 points at 
317.75. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 50 Index rose 70.13 points to 3,710.57,  
while the Dow Jones Stoxx 50 Index closed up 67.00 points at 
3,656.49. 
</P>
<P>
	Amsterdam was among the best performing markets, with a gain of  
2.0 percent in the AEX index to 564.44, with blue-chip banking 
shares leading the gains. ING shares closed at 50.40 euros, up 2.75 
euros, after the banking and insurance giant said it will buy the 
58.2 percent stake in Germany's BHF bank it doesn't already own. 
</P>
<P>
	German banks also rose with Commerzbank stealing the limelight  
as takeover fever gripped the sector. Shares of Commerzbank, which 
has recently been linked with BFG bank as a merger candidate, rose 
2.50 euros to 33.11 euros. BHF shares were nearly 30 percent higher 
by the market's close, up 10.05 euros to end the day at 44.25 
euros. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
