<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reds' Avery Played With Pain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Now that he's on the mend, Cincinnati Reds  
starter Steve Avery admits that there's been something wrong with 
him all season. 
</P>
<P>
	Avery had surgery Aug. 5 to repair a tear in the underside of  
his rotator cuff, remove a bone spur and repair his labrum. The 
left-hander won't be able to throw a ball again for three to four 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	He wasn't surprised by what doctors found in the shoulder.  
</P>
<P>
	``I knew something was (wrong) in there, but I've just been  
throwing with it for a while,'' Avery said Friday. ``This year it 
just got a little worse and harder to deal with, so it was time to 
do something. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once I started pitching the way I did my last two starts, you  
realize you're not doing the team any good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Avery, 29, signed with the Reds as a free agent last Dec. 11  
after two seasons with Boston. He was the Reds' most consistent 
pitcher early in the season, even though he was giving up a lot of 
walks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was kind of surprised by it,'' Avery said. ``I didn't really  
feel 100 percent. I think maybe it was the first time around the 
league and they didn't know what to expect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 19 starts overall, Avery went 6-7 with a 5.16 ERA, walking 78  
in 96 innings. The sore shoulder prevented him from having good 
workouts between starts, something that took a toll as the season 
went along. 
</P>
<P>
	``Really, the game wasn't the problem. It was the four days  
in-between,'' he said. ``I had a hard time preparing for my starts 
and that's where you get your strength and build your confidence 
with your location.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He expects to be fully recovered next season. The question is  
where he'll wind up. 
</P>
<P>
	Avery had a $500,000 salary this season. There's a mutual option  
for another year at $3 million, but the Reds can buy it out for $1 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Avery wouldn't be surprised if the Reds decided to buy out the  
final year of his contract, making him a free agent. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd hope to come back,'' Avery said. ``I like it here. They've  
treated me well. But if they choose not to bring me back, that's 
fine, too. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think I'll have any trouble finding a place to pitch,  
especially if I feel better.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
