<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 16:40:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Berkshire's Net Earnings Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- Lower earnings from Berkshire Hathaway's  
insurance holdings resulted in a nearly 50 percent decline in 
second quarter net profit. 
</P>
<P>
	Net earnings in the three months ended June 30 for the holding  
company of multibillionaire investor Warren Buffett were $572 
million, or $376 per class-A share, compared to $1.1 billion, or 
$947 per share, in the second quarter of 1998, the company said 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The performance of General Re, the nation's largest reinsurer  
acquired by Berkshire in December 1998, and a lower underwriting 
profit from car insurer GEICO, were primary factors in the holding 
company's quarterly decline. 
</P>
<P>
	General Re's first-half earnings from operations, before  
accounting adjustments, were $293 million this year, compared to 
$517 million in 1998. General Re's decline in earnings was 
primarily due to significant underwriting losses this year compared 
to near-breakeven underwriting results in the same period last 
year, Berkshire said. 
</P>
<P>
	GEICO generated a pre-tax underwriting profit of $20 million in  
the first half of 1999, compared to $154 million in 1998. That 
result was expected because of rate reductions taken in the past 
two years and increased marketing expenditures. GEICO's business 
continues to accelerate in all categories of auto insurance, 
Berkshire said. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of Berkshire's earnings come from insurance, though the  
company also holds stock in companies including Coca-Cola and the 
Washington Post. Berkshire cautions that investment gains or losses 
for any given period have no predictive value. 
</P>
<P>
	Berkshire's first half earnings were $1.1 billion, or $733  
million per class-A share, compared to $1.8 billion, or $1,529 per 
share in the first half of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Berkshire announced its earnings after financial markets had  
closed Friday. In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, shares 
fell $505 to $66,100. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
