<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fast End to Indonesia Probe Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The International Monetary Fund urged a quick  
resolution Friday of an Indonesian investigation of a banking 
scandal to avoid a loss of investor confidence at home and abroad. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency also said an international auditing firm should be  
brought in to confirm the investigation's findings. 
</P>
<P>
	The scandal involves an alleged $70 million payment from  
recently nationalized PT Bank Bali to a private company controlled 
by Setya Novanto, deputy treasurer of President B.J. Habibie's 
ruling Golkar party. 
</P>
<P>
	Novanto says he did nothing illegal. Both Indonesia's finance  
minister and the chairman of the country's bank restructuring 
agency said the transaction was inappropriate and are 
investigating. 
</P>
<P>
	This scandal and another involving the country's largest and  
third-largest private banks have dampened hopes for economy 
recovery. The country's currency the rupiah has fallen 10 percent 
this week, and share prices have fallen on the Jakarta stock 
exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	``The IMF is extremely concerned about recent reports alleging  
irregularities in a transaction involving the IBRA, Bank Indonesia 
and a private bank,'' an IMF spokesman said, reading an IMF 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The IBRA is the bank restructuring agency, Bank Indonesia the  
central bank. 
</P>
<P>
	``We expect the investigation to be concluded in a matter of  
days. We also fully support the appointment of an international 
auditing firm to validate the findings of the investigation,'' the 
statement said. ``Anything short of this will further damage 
domestic and international investor confidence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An IMF mission is due to return to Indonesia in September for a  
regular review of the country's economy and government policies. 
</P>
<P>
	The lending agency paid Indonesia $460 million at the beginning  
of August as part of $43 billion international rescue package 
promised in November 1997 when the country's economy collapsed. The 
next installment is due to be paid in October. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
