<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley Challenges Gore on Abortion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Former Sen. Bill Bradley is challenging Vice  
President Al Gore to make clear just where he stands on the issue 
of federal funding for abortions. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley, who is Gore's only opponent for the 2000 Democratic  
presidential nomination, issued the challenge Thursday following 
seemingly conflicting statements on abortion by Gore's staff. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it is time for him to answer what his position is,''  
Bradley said in an interview with The Associated Press. ``On this 
issue in particular you've got to say what you believe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore spokesman Chris Lehane tried to clarify Gore's position  
when asked about the vice president's position on federal funding 
for abortions. 
</P>
<P>
	Lehane said Gore's position has been to support the current  
federal law -- ``federal funding of abortion in situations involving 
incest, rape and when the life of the mother is endangered.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He was later asked if Gore favored Medicaid funding for poor  
women's abortions without the restrictions in the current law. 
``The vice president supports federal funding for abortions, 
period,'' Lehane said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bradley campaign, however, released a series of statements  
by Gore, both as a congressman and senator, showing he was opposed 
to federal funding for abortions. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have consistently opposed federal funding of abortion,''  
Gore said in a newspaper story in 1984. ``I believe the government 
should not participate in the taking of what is arguably a human 
life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Gore's change of positions since he was in Congress -- as  
Bradley's campaign alleged -- Lehane said that the important issue 
is only his current position. 
</P>
<P>
	``The issue shouldn't be what his position was a decade ago,''  
Lehane said. 
</P>
<P>
	Associates say Gore has shifted to the point that he now favors  
no restrictions on federal funding for abortions. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore addressed the issue himself at a campaign stop in Iowa, but  
without giving any details. 
</P>
<P>
	``I support federal funding, if that's what you're asking,''  
Gore said in response to a question shouted by a reporter. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bradley challenge was prompted by a story in Sunday's Des  
Moines Register in which a Gore spokesman said the vice president 
was against federal funding for abortion except in cases of rape, 
incest, or the need to save the life of the mother. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokesman Roger Salazar retracted that statement and said he had  
inaccurately depicted Gore's position, and that the vice president 
opposes restrictions on abortion funding. 
</P>
<P>
	White House aides say President Clinton, during the 1992  
campaign, said he would not veto any bill that allowed for the 
Medicaid funding of abortions, and they said he has not addressed 
that exact question since. 
</P>
<P>
	National Abortion Rights Action League president Kate Michelman  
said Gore's position on federal funding for abortion has 
``evolved'' over the years. 
</P>
<P>
	She also said that she is confident that Gore's position mirrors  
her group's, and that he is in favor of Medicaid funding for poor 
women's abortions. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have confidence that the vice president does support  
Medicaid funding for abortion for poor women,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Michelman said regardless of differences between the two  
Democrats, they are still far better choices than any of the 
Republican candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	``The issue here,'' Michelman said, ``is that Gore and Bradley  
both would protect the right of a woman to choose.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990813.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 10:54:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Candidates Pushing Hard in Iowa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- In a feverish burst leading to the  
weekend straw poll the campaigns have buses criss-crossing the 
state and their phone banks are buzzing -- in some cases with the 
candidates taking their own calls. 
</P>
<P>
	While aides say her phones have been hot for weeks, former  
Cabinet secretary Elizabeth Dole joins in today, manning her 
campaign headquarters for personal pitches. 
</P>
<P>
	The upcoming Iowa straw poll on Saturday is being portrayed as a  
turning point in the fight for the Republican presidential 
nomination -- and the candidates are responding in kind. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Forbes has bought up last-minute television ads and Lamar  
Alexander has campaigned in virtually every corner of Iowa in the 
last month. 
</P>
<P>
	George Bush arrived in Davenport Thursday night to begin a  
weekend of campaigning for straw poll votes, adding a special plea 
to his well-worn stump speech. 
</P>
<P>
	``Saturday is a pretty important test. So I'm here not only to  
share what's in my heart and tell you why I'm running, I'm hear to 
ask you to come to Ames. It's important,'' Bush told about 600 
supporters at a rally. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush met with about 500 Hispanics in Davenport today and urged  
them to vote in Saturday's straw poll. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many of you never may never have participated in the  
Republican caucuses. It's important that you participate, important 
that you come,'' said Bush, opening his first full day of 
campaigning for Saturday's contest. 
</P>
<P>
	Pollsters say polling for Iowa's political events is tough  
because it is hard to identify the population that will show up for 
the caucus and the straw poll. 
</P>
<P>
	One poll taken for several television stations of likely caucus  
attendees showed Bush with almost a 3-1 lead over Forbes and 
another taken by a Maryland firm called Research 2000 showed Bush 
and Forbes in a dead heat. The other candidates were grouped 
together behind Bush and Forbes in both polls. 
</P>
<P>
	Virtually all of the Republican rivals have built substantial  
organizational efforts for the straw poll. Only Arizona Sen. John 
McCain is absent, calling the straw poll a ``scam.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's not a cheap deal. Bush admits to spending $750,000, and  
accuses Forbes of spending $2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not discussing budgets,'' said Forbes aide Bill Dal Col.  
``This is a test along the way to February. This is a check to see 
who can deliver.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Forbes bus has been rumbling around the state for nearly two  
months, all pointing to Saturday night. He has bought a half-hour 
of television time Friday evening to air a campaign commercial 
featuring prominent social conservatives, a group he's worked 
overtime to court. 
</P>
<P>
	Plans for a live debate at WOI-TV studios the night before the  
GOP straw poll were canceled Thursday after just three candidates -- 
Alexander, commentator Pat Buchanan and Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah -- 
agreed to appear. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the work is pure drudgery, the kind of nuts-and-bolts  
work that goes on in campaign boiler rooms. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes has been running phone banks, both from campaign  
headquarters in Des Moines and from his campaign bus, leaving 
nothing to chance. 
</P>
<P>
	For Bush, the phone banks are searching for ``team leaders,''  
folks who agree to bring along nine others to the straw poll and 
collect a special reward. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole's technique is to find ``ticket captains,'' valued  
backers who volunteer to show up at the straw poll and bring along 
10 friends. 
</P>
<P>
	Tickets are $25 apiece, largely provided by the campaigns.  
People have to be from Iowa and they get one vote each. The 
Republican Party has not said how many they've sold, but say the 
tickets are still selling. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander has worked his way through a brutal, 21-day grind that  
took him to every corner of the state. He admits only to ``low 
six-figure'' spending, but his campaign has focused almost 
exclusively on the straw poll all summer 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan is running a low-budget operation, but his campaign  
office is filled every night with volunteers making phone calls. 
</P>
<P>
	Conservative activist Gary Bauer has been working hard on a  
church-based network, working night and day to lure social 
conservatives. 
</P>
<P>
	Virtually all of the Republican contenders were buzzing around  
the state Thursday, most focusing on the just-opened Iowa State 
Fair. Bauer headed to a cattle exhibit, while former Vice President 
Dan Quayle sought support at a pork exhibit. 
</P>
<P>
	Then there is the logistical headache of getting supporters to  
Ames for the straw poll. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've leased approximately 100 buses,'' said Woolson. ``Our  
strategy has been more of an organizational strategy as opposed to 
those campaigns that are spending money on television and radio.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990813.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 23:00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Padres Honor Gwynn in Ceremony </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Tony Gwynn, who reached the 3,000-hit milestone  
last week at Montreal, was honored in a ceremony before Friday 
night's game against Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Gwynn, appearing at Qualcomm Stadium for the first time since  
getting his 3,000th hit against Montreal's Dan Smith, received four 
standing ovations, including one that lasted 2 1/2 minutes when he was 
introduced. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the highlights of the 55-minute ceremony was the unveiling  
of a banner with a picture of Gwynn and the number 3,000. It joined 
banners of 21 other members of the 3,000-hit club that have hung 
since early in the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Gwynn went 1-for-4 with an RBI single in the eighth inning for  
career hit 3,008, moving him into 20th place past Al Kaline. The 
Padres lost 4-3. 
</P>
<P>
	The Padres plan to hang a banner Saturday to honor Wade Boggs,  
who collected his 3,000th hit Sunday at Tampa Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	Gwynn also presented to Hall of Fame officials his bat, batting  
helmet, pants and shoes he used when he collected hit No. 3,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly all of the living members of the 3,000-hit club  
congratulated Gwynn via video clips, including Hall of Famer Ted 
Williams, the former Boston Red Sox great who has enjoyed a close 
relationship with Gwynn in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	Entertainers Bill Cosby and Jay Leno, and broadcasters Vin  
Scully and Dick Enberg were also among those who sent 
congratulations to Gwynn by video clips. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are really excited,'' Gwynn said at a news conference  
before the game. ``I'm really excited. But as a player, I've got to 
turn the page and move on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gwynn thanked his family, including his wife, Alicia, who  
presented Gwynn with a 3,000-hit leather jacket, and Padres fans 
for their support during his 18-year career. 
</P>
<P>
	A replay of Gwynn's 3,000th hit was shown on the video monitors  
to the cheers of a crowd, estimated to be 50,000 by club officials. 
</P>
<P>
	The start of the game was delayed by 39 minutes because of the  
ceremony. 
</P>
<P>
	``What time is this game supposed to start?'' Gwynn quipped near  
the end. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990813.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 10:54:16 </DATE_TIME>
