<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> X-Files' Duchovny Suing Producer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) -- ``The X-Files'' star David Duchovny  
is suing the show's producer, 20th Century Fox Film Corp., claiming 
Fox gave its own stations sweetheart deals on ``X-Files'' reruns. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit, filed Thursday in Superior Court, claims Fox breached  
Duchovny's contract and paid ``X-Files'' creator Chris Carter more 
than $34 million and promised him a new series to keep him quiet 
about the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit did not specify damages.  
</P>
<P>
	Fox sold the series to its own broadcast network, Fox  
Broadcasting Co., and its own cable network, FX Cable Network. 
Syndication rights were sold to its own group of stations, Fox 
Television Stations. The lawsuit contends that Fox should have sold 
the series to the highest bidder. 
</P>
<P>
	Fox said in a news release that it would not comment. A message  
left at Carter's office Friday was not immediately returned. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990813.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 20:10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 15 Arrested in Prostitution Ring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Nine people were arrested in what the FBI and  
local police say was a family-run prostitution ring that snared at 
least 50 young women and girls from across the Midwest, some as 
young as 14. 
</P>
<P>
	After a two-year investigation, authorities on Thursday unsealed  
a 44-count federal indictment accusing 12 members of the 
Minneapolis-based ``Evans family,'' and three associates, of crimes 
ranging from money laundering to illegal transport of minors. 
</P>
<P>
	Agents described a 17-year-old family-run organization with  
influence in 24 states and Ontario, Canada. Five people people 
remained at large on Friday; police seized five homes and six 
luxury cars. 
</P>
<P>
	The indictment said five brothers and seven nephews worked in  
the Evans ``family business,'' ranging in age from their early 50s 
to a 20-year-old nephew. 
</P>
<P>
	``They grew up seeing that's how their father made money,'' said  
Andrew Schmidt, a city police detective who helped in the 
investigation. The organization started to unravel when two young 
prostitutes were arrested with fake identification in Maryland 
Heights, Mo., in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities say since 1982 the organizers had recruited girls  
mostly between 14 and 18 years old, mostly from Minnesota and 
Wisconsin, and employed them under fake names in escort services 
and massage parlors nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	The women ``serviced three to 10 clients, referred to as  
'tricks,' a day, seven days a week,'' the FBI said, earning between 
$2,000 and $15,000 a week. 
</P>
<P>
	The organization started to unravel when two young prostitutes  
were arrested with fake identification in Maryland Heights, Mo., in 
1997. Within two months, the FBI was asked to help. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
