<DOCNO> APW19990813.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 04:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 15 Accused in Prostitution Ring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- For years, a prostitution ring lured girls and  
young women from across the Midwest into a life of illicit 
servitude and forced them to remain there with beatings, torture 
and rapes, the FBI says. 
</P>
<P>
	After a two-year investigation, authorities on Thursday unsealed  
a 44-count federal indictment accusing 15 members of the 
Minneapolis-based ``Evans family'' of crimes ranging from money 
laundering to illegal transport of minors. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine people were arrested Thursday and six remain at large, said  
William Eubanks of the FBI's St. Louis office. Police also seized 
five homes and six luxury cars, including three Mercedes Benz. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1982, members of the ring -- eight of whom are related --  
allegedly enticed girls as young as 14 to work for massage parlors 
and escort services, the FBI said. The girls were often runaways 
from the Midwest, though some came from regular homes, authorities 
say. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``family'' would force the girls into road trips to 23 other  
states and Canada, earning an estimated $1 million annually for the 
ring, said Detective Joe Delia of the Maryland Heights, Mo. police, 
which helped the FBI break the ring. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is as close to modern slavery as you can get,'' Delia  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The investigation began in 1997 when police became suspicious  
after stopping two prostitutes near St. Louis, authorities said. 
Within two months, the FBI was asked to help. 
</P>
<P>
	The charges were filed here because the ring was discovered in  
the St. Louis area. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators have identified at least 50 women involved in the  
operation over the past 17 years, including 27 involved as minors. 
</P>
<P>
	Most were lured into the ring at shopping centers and dance  
clubs, seduced by initially kind treatment only to be later 
submitted to beatings, torture and rape, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Evanses would place ads for girls (to be) exotic dancers  
or lingerie models and go anywhere young kids hung out,'' said 
police Sgt. Andy Schmidt. Later, he said, ``they would also shame 
them into staying, telling them that their families would never 
take them back because of what they did. It was almost like a 
cult.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some escaped after a few weeks, but others remained in the ring  
for up to seven years, Eubanks said. 
</P>
<P>
	One 15-year-old prostitute told an investigator: ``I'd rather be  
dead than doing what I'm doing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities say the family used cell phones and pagers to keep  
track of the prostitutes. One girl told police she took her pager 
to middle school. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were very skilled at picking them up when they were most  
vulnerable,'' Minneapolis police Detective Andy Schmidt said. 
``It's kind of like a cult, they break them down. It's 
brain-washing.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990813.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 07:40:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> County Fairs Affected by Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CENTREVILLE, Md. (AP) -- Fourteen-year-old Kim Brown swirled a  
moist paper towel along the ebony-colored fur lining the inner ear 
of her sheep. Then she wiped the top of the animal's head to make 
it look shiny and pert for the afternoon sheep show at the Queen 
Anne's County Fair. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim would have liked to clean her sheep from hoof to tail with a  
garden hose, the way she did several times a day last year. But 
this summer she's using damp wash rags as often as she can. 
</P>
<P>
	The devastating Eastern drought, which led Maryland's governor  
to demand that residents conserve water, is making its presence 
felt at this summer's traditional county fairs. 
</P>
<P>
	Animal bathing isn't the only traditional practice being  
restricted -- water-balloon fights are gone, water rides are being 
reconsidered and beverage vendors have been asked to save their 
melted ice for plants. 
</P>
<P>
	At the weeklong Garrett County Fair in western Maryland, manager  
Ralph Miller allows animal baths only on show day and picture day. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just use a three-gallon bucket and a brush,'' Miller said.  
``You save a lot of water that way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Less frequent washing means livestock competing in shows need to  
be kept especially clean. David Butler, whose 200-pound yearling 
ewe was named the grand champion sheep for fitting and showing in 
Garrett County, said he protects his animal from dust by wrapping 
her in a canvas blanket. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Queen Anne's County Fair, which draws nearly 3,000  
visitors a day and ends Saturday, Kim shared another animal hygiene 
tip: ``We keep them in so they don't get dirty as often.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Signs posted throughout the 4-H Park urge water conservation.  
</P>
<P>
	The worsening drought has cost Maryland farmers $72 million in  
lost corn, soybeans, hay and tobacco, the state Department of 
Agriculture said Thursday, and the effects are evident in the 
vegetable and crop categories at county fair contests. 
</P>
<P>
	Gardeners displayed less produce than usual at the Carroll  
County Fair, and farmers were discouraged from competing for prizes 
because of stunted field crops, county 4-H secretary Mary Ellen 
Arbaugh said. 
</P>
<P>
	Fair organizers are cutting other water corners as well.  
</P>
<P>
	The fair in Frederick County won't begin until Sept. 17.  
However, planners are re-examining whether to allow a carnival ride 
that drops people in fake logs down a water slide. 
</P>
<P>
	Fair organizers in Carroll and Queen Anne's counties have  
canceled the end-of-the-fair water balloon battles in which 
livestock farmers traditionally engage their crop-growing cousins. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm kind of disappointed that we won't have it,'' said Mike  
Handleman, 14, as he gingerly sprayed his cow with water. ``But I 
can understand why we can't.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
