<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Aug. 13, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Wholesale Prices Rise in July  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Prices at the wholesale level rose a modest  
0.2 percent in July as a huge jump in energy prices overwhelmed a 
sharp drop in food costs, the Labor Department said today. The 
increase in the Producer Price Index, which measures inflation 
pressures before they reach the consumer, matched the 0.2 percent 
rise in May. July's increase was slightly better than expected with 
many analysts had been anticipating that prices would rise 0.3 
percent in July. But many analysts and investors remain concerned 
that the Federal Reserve wants to raise interest rates, sensing 
rising wage pressures in the tight job market. 

</P>
<P>
	L.A. Suspect Scouted Jewish Institutions  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Suspected gunman Buford Furrow reportedly  
told investigators he did not intend to shoot children at the 
Jewish community center. The Los Angeles Times today says he told 
investigators the three children ``got in the way'' as he tried to 
shoot a 68-year-old receptionist and a teen-age counselor. The 
newspaper says Furrow scouted three prominent Jewish institutions, 
but found security too tight. Flags are flying at half-staff today 
in Southern California in honor of murdered letter carrier Joseph 
Ileto. Prosecutors say Furrow has admitted to shooting Ileto 
because he was not white and worked for the government. 

</P>
<P>
	Disabled Man Requests Death  
</P>
<P>
	ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- Prosecutors say they won't oppose a  
severely disabled man's request to unplug the hospital ventilator 
that has kept him alive since 1967, when he broke his neck in a 
high school gymnasium. Under New York law, patients can opt to 
discontinue lifesaving treatment. Bill White is believed to be one 
of America's longest surviving quadriplegics on a ventilator. In 32 
years, he has rarely left his hospital bed. Monroe County District 
Attorney Howard Relin's office concluded yesterday that White ``has 
the right to refuse treatment.'' Ending White's treatment is likely 
to end his life within minutes. 

</P>
<P>
	94 Killed in Indonesian Rioting  
</P>
<P>
	AMBON, Indonesia (AP) -- Government security forces overwhelmed  
by recent east Indonesian religious rioting that has left at least 
94 people dead denied today that troops gunned down rioters inside 
a church. In the eastern Maluku province, witnesses said the death 
toll from clashes between Muslims and Christians include 24 people 
shot by troops in and around a Protestant church in Galala, a 
suburb of the provincial capital of Ambon. Those shootings were 
Tuesday and Wednesday. Church secretary Benny Tamaela said he saw 
security forces shooting at battling mobs armed with homemade 
spears, bows and arrows and gasoline bombs. 

</P>
<P>
	Italy Accuses Coke in Antitrust Case  
</P>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- Italian authorities have accused Coca-Cola Co. of  
abusing its dominant market position through questionable trade 
practices, according to a preliminary report released today. The 
report alleges Coke offered discounts to retailers who displayed 
its products more prominently than those of competitors. It also 
says the company allegedly discriminated against wholesalers who 
refused to displace competitors' products. In July, European Union 
officials raided Coke's offices in Austria, Denmark, Germany and 
Great Britain as part of an inquiry into the company's marketing 
practices. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Gains 117; Nasdaq Up 54  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks soared in morning trading today with the  
Dow up 117.14 points at 10,906.53 just before 11 a.m. EDT. 
Advancers led decliners 1,604-760 on the New York Stock Exchange. 
The Nasdaq was up 54.95 at 2,604.44. 

</P>
<P>
	Tennis Star Steffi Graf Retires  
</P>
<P>
	HEIDELBERG, Germany (AP) -- Steffi Graf, one of just five players  
to complete the tennis Grand Slam in one year and a dominating 
force for more than a decade, retired from the sport today, saying 
her ``motivation wasn't what it was in the past.'' Even though her 
career has been marked by a series of injuries, she said those had 
nothing to do with her decision. ``Right now, I'm perfectly fit,'' 
Graf said. ``This is no way about injuries.'' In her latest 
comeback, the 30-year-old Graf stunned top-ranked Martina Hingis to 
win the French Open. She then lost in the Wimbledon final to 
Lindsay Davenport. 

</P>
<P>
	Kendall 6-Under on PGA Front Nine  
</P>
<P>
	MEDINAH, Ill. (AP) -- Skip Kendall got off to a blazing start on  
an accommodating Medinah Country Club today, shooting a 6-under 30 
on the front nine to move into contention in the second round of 
the PGA Championship. Kendall, who has never won on the PGA Tour, 
also birdied the 10th hole to get 7-under for the day and was two 
strokes behind first-round leader Sergio Garcia. Garcia was 1-under 
through three holes as Medinah's No. 3 course served notice it 
would not be too challenging to par today. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  




  	   	
</P>
