<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Aug. 13, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin Seeks Approval of Premier  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- President Boris Yeltsin said today that the  
communist-dominated lower house of parliament wouldn't dare 
opposing his new choice for prime minister. Yeltsin abruptly sacked 
Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin and named Vladimir Putin, a former 
KGB spy, as his successor on Monday -- the fourth Cabinet reshuffle 
in 17 months. ``It would be preferable if (Putin) is approved on 
the first attempt,'' Yeltsin said at the start of a meeting in the 
Kremlin with Alexander Kotenkov, his envoy to the lower house, the 
State Duma. 

</P>
<P>
	Iran, Turkey Sign Military Deal  
</P>
<P>
	ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- Turkey and Iran agreed today to cooperate  
more in fighting Kurdish rebels, but failed to come to a deal on 
the very issues that have recently strained their relations. Iran 
refused to assure Turkey it would expel Kurdish rebels from Iran, 
where Ankara claims the rebels have bases. And Turkey refused to 
compensate Iran for a bombing last month that Tehran says hit its 
territory. The signature ceremony followed three days of 
negotiations. 

</P>
<P>
	China Said Mulling Force Vs. Taiwan  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Chinese government officials have warned the  
Clinton administration that Beijing is considering military action 
against Taiwan because of its recent moves toward independence, 
according to published reports. The New York Times and the 
Washington Post reported today that while the warning could be 
saber rattling or psychological warfare aimed at Taiwan, the 
administration believes the threats could be real. Unidentified 
administration officials told the Times that Washington has warned 
Beijing that any military action would force the United States to 
retaliate. 

</P>
<P>
	Suspect in Japan Hijacking Indicted  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese prosecutors charged a 28-year-old man  
today with hijacking a domestic airliner last month and stabbing 
the pilot to death in the cockpit. Yuji Nishizawa is accused of 
commandeering the All Nippon Airways jet just after takeoff from 
Tokyo's Haneda Airport on July 23. He allegedly killed the pilot 
for refusing to let him fly the plane. None of the 503 passengers 
and 13 other crew members was hurt. Nishizawa was subdued after his 
brawl with the pilot and arrested when the plane returned to Tokyo. 

</P>
<P>
	Rugova To Work With U.N. in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Amid a fresh round of Ethnic  
Albanian violence against Serbs, Albanian leader Ibrahim Rugova 
sought to reassure international leaders today that his party will 
cooperate with the United Nations as well as with rival Albanian 
groups. Rugova, who has twice won unofficial presidential 
elections, told reporters his Democratic League of Kosovo party, 
known as the LDK, was prepared to work with Kosovo Liberation Army 
leader Hashim Thaci, who has also laid claim on leadership of the 
province. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton: Mideast Peace Deal Possible  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A land-for-security deal between Israel and  
the Palestinians could be reality within three weeks, President 
Clinton says. Clinton is hoping that Congress will approve the $1.2 
billion in special aid for Israel and $400 million for the 
Palestinian Authority that the House and Senate so far have omitted 
from foreign aid legislation. Clinton made these two points at a 
90-minute meeting yesterday with some 30 American Jewish leaders at 
the White House, a participant, Malcolm Hoenlein, said afterward. 
It was based on the proposition that Israel should seek security by 
relinquishing territory to the Arabs in exchange for promises of 
peace. 

</P>
<P>
	LA Suspect Could Face Death Penalty  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The suspect charged with shooting five people  
at a Jewish community center and later shooting and a 
Filipino-American postal worker may face the death penalty, 
authorities said. Los Angeles County prosecutors yesterday charged 
Buford O. Furrow Jr. with murder and five counts of attempted 
murder -- all filed as hate crimes. Federal prosecutors already had 
charged Furrow in the postman's slaying. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stock Prices Close Higher  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices closed higher today. The Nikkei  
gained 12.20 points to close at 17,435.17. 

</P>
<P>
	Tennis Star Steffi Graf Retires  
</P>
<P>
	HEIDELBERG, Germnay (AP) -- Steffi Graf, who dominated women's  
tennis for a decade before injuries started hindering her career, 
announced today she was retiring from the game. Graf, 30, won 22 
Grand Slam singles titles and had more than 100 victories on the 
WTA Tour. In her latest comeback, Graf posted a stunning, emotional 
victory over top-ranked Martina Hingis to win the French Open this 
summer. She then lost in the Wimbledon final to Lindsay Davenport. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS  
  	   	
</P>
