<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990813.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 18:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Steelers Gain TD Via Instant Replay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- The Pittsburgh Steelers used instant replay to  
gain a touchdown in Friday's exhibition game against Chicago when 
coach Bill Cowher successfully challenged an out-of-bounds call on 
an end zone fumble. 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Fuamatu-Ma'afala of the Steelers blocked Todd Sauerbrun's  
punt into the Bears' end zone, where Hines Ward fell on the ball 
just before it reached the end line. 
</P>
<P>
	The officials initially ruled that Ward slid out of bounds as he  
recovered the ball, a safety. Referee Johnny Grier reversed the 
call after watching a replay on a TV monitor set up behind the 
Steelers' bench. 
</P>
<P>
	Rather than leading 9-7, the Steelers went ahead 14-7 on Ward's  
touchdown with 3:51 left in the first quarter, his second of the 
quarter. He scored earlier on a 45-yard touchdown catch. 
</P>
<P>
	Instant replay returned to the NFL in March with a system that  
allows coaches to challenge two calls per game. 
</P>
<P>
	Replay was in effect from 1986 until 1991, but was voted out in  
1992, in large part because it was delaying games. 
</P>
<P>
	The old system used a replay official who could stop the game on  
a questionable call and make the decision. In the new system, the 
replay official can challenge calls only in the final two minutes 
of each half and in overtime. 
</P>
<P>
	The plays covered by replay are like those in the old system --  
goal-line and sideline plays and possession -- and do not apply to 
penalties. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990813.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 06:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: BNP Gains Control of Paribas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- French banking group Banque Nationale de Paris has  
won control of the Paribas bank and up to 42 percent of Societe 
Generale, a French newspaper reported Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The daily Le Figaro said that according to preliminary results  
of rival tender offers that closed Friday, Paribas shareholders 
pledged between 58 percent and 60 percent of the investment bank's 
shares to BNP and about 32 percent to Societe Generale. 
</P>
<P>
	About 10 percent of Paribas stockholders opted to keep their  
shares, the newspaper said, citing unnamed sources. 
</P>
<P>
	French banking authorities are expected to intervene in the  
takeover battle if BNP ends up with less than 50 percent of Societe 
Generale. 
</P>
<P>
	A merger of the three banks would create the world's first $1  
trillion bank in terms of assets. 
</P>
<P>
	The bidding war has pitted BNP against Societe Generale, which  
both aimed to create a global banking giant. 
</P>
<P>
	It began last March, when BNP trumped a friendly merger between  
Societe Generale and Paribas, offering $37 billion for the two 
banks. Societe Generale and Paribas rejected BNP's surprise offer 
and have spurned its advances since then. 
</P>
<P>
	Societe Generale shareholders tendered between 36 and 42 percent  
of the company's shares to BNP, which would give BNP control of 
between 30 and 35 percent of the voting rights in Societe Generale, 
Le Figaro said. 
</P>
<P>
	French stock market authorities weren't immediately available to  
comment on the report. The three banks also have declined comment 
until the French stock market regulator, Conseil des Marches 
Financiers, announces official results Tuesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
