<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Colts' Bennett To Make Debut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Cornelius Bennett will finally be cheered in  
Indianapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	Bennett was the Colts' first pick in the 1987 draft. But he  
never signed, and forced a trade to Buffalo. Now, having signed 
with Indianapolis in the off-season, he will make his debut with 
the Colts, 12 years belated, against Cincinnati Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be a little strange, after nine years and four  
Super Bowls with Buffalo. Coming in, they always booed every time 
my name was called, which was a lot,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bennett, a five-time Pro Bowl selection who played in his fifth  
Super Bowl with Atlanta last year, hasn't forgotten the 
Indianapolis fans. 
</P>
<P>
	``I always heard them. It's a badge of honor really that they  
remember me and boo. It will be fun for those fans to have their 
fun and cheer for me now,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bennett had arthroscopic surgery on the left knee following the  
Super Bowl and has been working himself slowly into shape. He's 
missed some drills and has not participated in twice-a-day workouts 
with his teammates. 
</P>
<P>
	Bennett didn't play last week when the Colts opened their  
exhibition schedule in a 9-6 loss at Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	``The knee is coming along fine and I know that I'll be ready  
when it counts,'' he said. ``I think I'm as fast as I need to be 
out here with these young guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Colts' defense ranked 29th among the league's 30 teams in  
nearly every statistic last season. They are looking to the 
6-foot-3, 240-pound linebacker for leadership on and off the field. 
</P>
<P>
	``The main thing is just keeping him healthy and getting him out  
there on the field,'' said second-year quarterback Peyton Manning. 
</P>
<P>
	``A number of the defensive guys have already talked about just  
what his presence can do for a defense. He's been there before, 
played in a lot of big games, most obviously the five Super 
Bowls.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bennett expects to play only a few series against Cincinnati.  
The Colts are saving him for the season opener Sept. 12 at home 
against Buffalo. 
</P>
<P>
	Both the Colts and Bengals are expected to play without their  
first-round draft picks. Indianapolis didn't sign running back 
Edgerrin James until Thursday and the Bengals haven't reached an 
agreement with quarterback Akili Smith. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bengals are also missing veteran wide receiver Carl Pickens,  
who has been designated the team's franchise player. Pickens, 29, 
has said he will sit out a season and forego a year's pay -- about 
$3.5 million -- rather than play for the Bengals again. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
