<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pipe Sanction Request Clears Hurdle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Commerce Department can consider punitive  
tariffs on foreign steel pipes used by oil and natural gas 
producers, a U.S. panel ruled Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. International Trade Commission found evidence that  
shipments of seamless pipes from Japan, the Czech Republic, 
Romania, South Africa and Mexico have or could hurt the U.S. steel 
industry, which blames low-priced imports for thousands of layoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	The preliminary 6-0 ruling clears the way for Commerce to  
determine whether producers in those countries engaged in illegal 
pricing. If the department finds illegal pricing, the commission 
will make a final injury ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	Tariffs could lead to higher prices for pipes bought by oil and  
gas companies, which are struggling themselves because of dwindling 
prices. Several months would pass before any tariffs would be 
imposed, but steel users say the impact could be felt sooner. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market adjusts to a preliminary ruling as if it were a  
final ruling,'' said Brian Petty, senior vice president for 
government affairs with the International Association of Drilling 
Contractors. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department finds illegal pricing in almost every  
case it considers, although sometimes not to the extent alleged by 
the U.S. industry involved. The commission makes a final injury 
ruling that allows imposition of tariffs in only about half the 
cases. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. steel industry, proceeding with trade complaints that  
target about a half-dozen product lines, already won tariffs on 
Japanese shipments of the core product, hot-rolled carbon steel. 
The hot-rolled case has contributed to recent reductions in import 
levels. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reality is some companies don't make that much hot-rolled  
steel, so these (other) cases have a big impact on them,'' said 
Greg Mastel, program director for international trade studies at 
the Center for National Policy, a Washington think tank. ``Also, 
some countries don't make as much hot-rolled as other products.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Imports surged last year in the wake of the Asian financial  
crisis, which reduced demand for steel abroad and prompted foreign 
producers to unload goods in U.S. markets. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest case was filed by the United Steelworkers of America  
and five companies, including U.S. Steel Group and its joint 
venture with Kobe Steel of Japan. The industry charged that the 
foreign producers sold their products in the United States at 
prices below production costs. 
</P>
<P>
	While the industry won tariffs on Japanese hot-rolled shipments,  
the U.S. government reached separate deals last month to let Russia 
and Brazil avoid tariffs by voluntarily curbing steel shipments. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, the commission closed out the Russian and Brazilian  
cases by determining the illegal pricing involved caused actual or 
threatened injury. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
