<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Voices' Play Not Scary Enough </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *An AP Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Sometimes a scare isn't enough.  
</P>
<P>
	There are several spooky moments in ``Voices in the Dark,'' a  
convoluted thriller by John Pielmeier that arrived Thursday at 
Broadway's Longacre Theater. 
</P>
<P>
	But audiences are more likely to scratch their heads than shiver  
at Pielmeier's tortured tale of a radio talk show therapist trapped 
in an isolated mountain cabin and tormented by an unseen maniac, 
who chats with her on the phone. This guy, who has electronically 
altered his voice, wants to do more than talk. He has murder on his 
mind. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem with ``Voices in the Dark'' is not that it doesn't  
work as a thriller. It doesn't work as a play. Peppered with purple 
dialogue and outdated psychobabble, ``Voices'' collapses on itself 
as it rushes toward a preordained face-off between hunter and prey. 
</P>
<P>
	Our heroine, Lil, has come up to the Adirondacks to repair her  
faltering marriage with a philandering hubby. The helpmate never 
makes it to the cabin because of the snow. Lil has enough visitors 
to keep her busy, though. There's Owen, the local simpleton whose 
crush on the woman manifests itself in odd ways. And Blue, Owen's 
best buddy, another local yokel whose strange personality radiates 
a sinister ambiguity. 
</P>
<P>
	Pielmeier pads the play -- probably to confuse the audience. For  
example, he brings in Lil's broadcast producer who urges her to 
take a more high-profile job on television where cameras will show 
the desperate people who dial in for help. 
</P>
<P>
	The evening opens with Lil on the air. Her radio program is  
prophetically called ``Last Resort'' -- and she is seen and heard 
counseling a victim of child abuse. Voices play big roles in this 
show and credit sound designer T. Richard Fitzgerald that they work 
as effectively as they do. 
</P>
<P>
	Director Christopher Ashley pushes things at a furious pace,  
which is wise, not allowing theatergoers time to think about the 
impossibilities of the story. 
</P>
<P>
	The play's beleaguered heroine is portrayed by a game Judith  
Ivey, one of the theater's most likable actresses. Ivey has an 
ingratiating stage personality. She also has a sense of humor which 
fitfully comes through here, despite some of the raunchy talk that 
always seems to center on sex. 
</P>
<P>
	The other performers are even more prisoners of the plot. Peter  
Bartlett is wasted as the campy radio producer, while Raphael 
Sbarge plays the childlike Owen with convincing naturalness. John 
Ahlin turns in an unnerving performance as the irritating Blue, and 
Zach Grenier manages to be particularly obnoxious as an aggressive 
policeman. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Act 2 finale, Ivey tussles effectively with her assailant  
(don't worry -- the identity will not be revealed here). By then the 
lights have gone out in the cabin and the battle takes place in 
semi-darkness. 
</P>
<P>
	Fight director B.H. Barry stages some pretty effective and  
violent fisticuffs. No wonder Ivey thanks her Pilates instructor 
and personal trainer in the theater program. 
</P>
<P>
	The rustic log cabin setting, designed by David Gallo and Lauren  
Helpern, is splendid -- complete with a Jacuzzi and a collection of 
deer heads that includes ``Bambi's father,'' according to one of 
the characters. It looks like the kind of place where one could 
actually have a fun vacation and get away from plays like ``Voices 
in the Dark.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990813.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 06:10:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wholesale Prices Rise in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Prices at the wholesale level rose a modest  
0.2 percent in July as a huge jump in energy prices overwhelmed a 
sharp drop in food costs, the Labor Department said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The increase in the Producer Price Index, which measures  
inflation pressures before they reach the consumer, matched the 0.2 
percent rise in May. Wholesale prices had actually fallen 0.1 
percent in June, only the second decline this year. 
</P>
<P>
	July's increase was slightly better than expected. Many analysts  
had been anticipating that prices would rise 0.3 percent in July. 
Financial markets liked the good news on inflation. The bond market 
staged an immediate rally, pushing the yield down on Treasury's 
30-year bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	The moderate advance in wholesale prices, if matched at the  
consumer level, could ease concerns somewhat at the Federal Reserve 
about a potential breakout of inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	However, many analysts and investors are still worried that the  
central bank will raise interest rates for a second time this year 
on Aug. 24. Their fear is that the economy is still growing too 
strongly and could spark inflation down the road. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate report, the Commerce Department said today that  
the level of inventories held by businesses on shelves and backlots 
rose 0.3 percent in June, but sales climbed at an even faster 0.9 
percent pace. 
</P>
<P>
	That brought the inventory-to-sales ratio to 1.34, meaning it  
would take 1.34 months to exhaust inventories at the June sales 
pace. Analysts see the current inventory level as posing no threat 
that businesses will be forced to cut back production to work off 
unwanted supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	So far this year, wholesale prices have been rising at an annual  
rate of 1.7 percent, compared to no change for all of 1998. The 
pickup in this year's wholesale prices is coming from big increases 
in energy costs, which had been falling for much of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	For July, energy costs rose 3.4 percent, led by a hefty 12.7  
percent increase in gasoline prices, an advance that motorists felt 
at the pumps last month. 
</P>
<P>
	The July gain in gasoline prices was the largest since a 26  
percent surge in April, which helped push overall wholesale prices 
up by 0.5 percent in April, the biggest increase this year. That 
gain plus an even sharper rise in consumer prices in April put the 
Fed on inflation alert and led to a June 30 increase in a key Fed 
interest rate, the first hike in two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Gasoline prices had reached their highest point in more than 18  
months in July partly because of production cuts by the 
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, as well as a pickup 
in demand from recovering economies in Asia and Latin America. 
</P>
<P>
	But a nationwide check of gasoline stations by the Lundberg  
Survey has shown a slowing in the rate of price increases at the 
pump in the last two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	The 3.4 percent rise in energy costs in July was partially  
offset by a 0.9 percent drop in food prices. Beef prices, which had 
risen sharply in June, declined by 3.4 percent in July, the biggest 
one-month drop since February 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Vegetable prices also were down a sharp 8.1 percent in July, led  
by steep declines in the price of cauliflower, broccoli, tomatoes, 
and green peppers. 
</P>
<P>
	Fruit prices also were down, declining 3.2 percent as the price  
of blueberries, nectarines, melons and peaches all fell. 
</P>
<P>
	Excluding the volatile energy and food categories, wholesales  
prices were unchanged in July, after having fallen 0.2 percent in 
June. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside of food and energy, inflation was kept in check by a 0.2  
percent drop in the price of new cars. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990813.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 15:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Irwin Always a Factor at Medinah  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEDINAH, Ill. (AP) -- Jack Nicklaus has Augusta National. Hale  
Irwin has Medinah. 
</P>
<P>
	The PGA Championship may represent the strongest field ever  
assembled for a major, but the 54-year-old Irwin looked like he was 
enjoying another banner day on the Senior PGA Tour on Friday by 
working himself into contention after two rounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the kind of course that I think elicits out of me my best  
golf,'' Irwin said after a 3-under 69, putting him at 139 going 
into the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Every time Medinah Country Club holds a major championship,  
Irwin seems to be around the lead. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine years ago, he became the oldest U.S. Open champion when he  
beat Mike Donald in a 19-hole playoff at Medinah. And in the 1975 
U.S. Open at Medinah, Irwin missed the playoff by one stroke and 
finished in a tie for third. He probably would have been a factor 
in the 1949 U.S. Open, but he was only 4. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've had success here,'' Irwin said. ``It's not as if I don't  
know the golf course. It's not as if this is a bad venue for me -- 
just the opposite. I feel comfortable playing the golf course.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The gallery flocked to see Sergio Garcia, the teen-age  
sensation, try to build his lead in the PGA Championship. They 
wound up cheering for a senior citizen. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hey, you're not 50,'' someone yelled from the gallery after  
Irwin saved par from the bunker on No. 16. 
</P>
<P>
	This caused Irwin to stop in his tracks, look back and smile.  
</P>
<P>
	``You're right,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Irwin's play for 36 holes is reminiscent of what Nicklaus did at  
Augusta National in 1998, when the six-time Masters champion made a 
Sunday charge and tied for sixth. At 58, Nicklaus became the oldest 
player to finish in the top 10 in the Masters. 
</P>
<P>
	Medinah hasn't held enough majors to give Irwin that level of  
comfort and confidence, but even the gallery that swelled to 
four-deep by the end of his round sense something magical watching 
him turn back the clock. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't look in the mirror and see gray hair, and you can't  
look in the mirror and see a kid with freckles,'' Irwin said. ``You 
don't pay attention to how old they are. They are players in the 
field who are trying to beat you. And if you feel as if you're 
going to be beaten by these players, you will be beaten. 
</P>
<P>
	``But I don't like to think that way.''  
</P>
<P>
	He never has. Irwin, who already has won five tournaments and  
$1.5 million on the senior tour, has been playing without the 
pressure he feels on the 50-and-over circuit to be at the top of 
every tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	Then again, ``I didn't come here to be the token old fellow,''  
said Irwin, who received a special exemption to play this PGA 
Championship. 
</P>
<P>
	His age may show off the tee. Garcia and Phil Mickelson were  
hitting 7-irons while Irwin had to pull a 4-iron to reach the same 
green. But he hit them well, and had just as many birdie 
opportunities. 
</P>
<P>
	Whether he can keep it up, not even Irwin knows. The oldest  
player to win a major championship was Julius Boros, who won the 
PGA Championship in 1968 at age 48. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I can continue playing as I have been,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Irwin has been playing so well, he was even asked whether Ben  
Crenshaw might consider him for the Ryder Cup team should be win 
this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``Are we going to get paid?'' Irwin cracked. He quickly added,  
``I'd pay to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Irwin would give anything for two more rounds at Medinah. If  
not, there's always the 2006 PGA Championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Irwin will be 61, but the PGA of America might consider  
extending him another exemption. 
</P>
<P>
	After all, it will be played at Medinah.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990813.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 23:40:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Columbine Victim, Father Face Fights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ENGLEWOOD, Colo. (AP) -- When Richard Castaldo was shot eight  
times and critically wounded in the Columbine rampage, his father 
jumped on a plane and flew 1,500 miles to be at his bedside. 
</P>
<P>
	But as he tended to his now paralyzed son, Rick Castaldo learned  
that he had his own battle to fight -- against Hodgkin's disease, a 
form of cancer that attacks the lymph nodes. 
</P>
<P>
	Castaldo could have become overwhelmed by the one-two punch of  
the tragedies. Instead, he came up with a plan: He gave up his job, 
moved to Colorado from his Manassas, Va. home, and began 
chemotherapy here so he could support his son. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't have the time to be sick,'' the 45-year-old said as he  
and a cousin poured concrete at his new home, which he is making 
wheelchair-accessible for his son. ``The worst thing you can do is 
sit around and mope about your misfortune.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was about lunchtime on April 20 when Richard, 17, was sitting  
outside Columbine with classmate Rachel Scott. 
</P>
<P>
	Seniors Eric Harris, 18, and Dylan Klebold, 17, both heavily  
armed, turned a corner and opened fire, killing Miss Scott and 
hitting Richard eight times. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard played dead, lying in a pool of his own blood while the  
gunmen strode into the school. They eventually killed a dozen 
students and a teacher and wounded at least 23 before they 
committed suicide. 
</P>
<P>
	Castaldo watched the tragedy unfold on CNN from Virginia, hoping  
to get a glance of his son, while Richard's mother, in Littleton, 
went to the scene. When he learned Richard was among those shot, he 
rushed to Denver to see his son. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first thing he asked was how long I was going to stay,''  
he said. ``I said, `As long as you want.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	Only six days before the younger Castaldo was wounded, his  
father had surgery to remove swollen lymph nodes. While he was 
tending to Richard, Castaldo got the news that he had Hodgkin's, a 
neoplastic disease characterized by enlargement of the lymph nodes, 
spleen and liver. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite his diagnosis, Castaldo isn't feeling sorry for himself.  
</P>
<P>
	``Anything I have to go through is a minor inconvenience  
compared to him,'' Castaldo said of his son. ``Just imagine. You 
can't do even the simplest thing like tie your shoe. You look at 
your legs but you can't move your feet. And still he has this 
amazing attitude.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the past four months, father and son have settled into a  
routine. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard remains at Craig Hospital, where he is learning to  
adjust to life without the use of his legs. The floppy-haired, 
quiet teen-ager spends six hours to eight hours a day at pool 
therapy, wheelchair classes and even driving lessons. 
</P>
<P>
	He is the only victim of the tragedy still hospitalized. He is  
scheduled to be released next Friday, four days after classes 
resume at Columbine. He plans, at least initially, to move in with 
his dad and return to Columbine so he can graduate with his 
classmates. 
</P>
<P>
	Rick Castaldo holds down a job as an electrical engineer  
specializing in aviation safety while undergoing chemotherapy and 
radiation treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the Castaldos' biggest concerns is money. Richard's  
medical bills have topped $800,000 so far. 
</P>
<P>
	The Castaldos have insurance, but that only covers initial  
rehabilitation. They have received $150,000 of the nearly $5 
million in donations that poured in after the massacre. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard is grateful that his father has been able to be around  
during his rehabilitation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just him being here helps,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Richard is confident that his father will recover.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think he's going to be fine. They caught it early,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	As he sits in a wheelchair, Richard also holds onto a glimmer of  
hope that he may one day walk again. 
</P>
<P>
	``They said 10 years ago it was a lost cause, but now I guess  
they're not saying that anymore. They're doing a lot of spinal cord 
research and stuff,'' he said. ``But I'm pretty much just trying to 
live my life ... without that ... in my head.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The teen-ager is determined not to let his condition stop him.  
He has already gone whitewater rafting, canoeing, fishing and 
go-carting with his dad. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm pretty much just taking off with my life where I left off,  
I guess ... except for a few things,'' Richard said. ``I don't 
think it's gonna really change the way I look at life.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
