<HEADLINE> Small Plane Crashes in Florida </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PEMBROKE PINES, Fla. (AP) -- A single-engine plane crashed into a  
home just after takeoff on Friday, killing both people aboard and 
burning down the house. 
</P>
<P>
	All six people in the house were able to escape before the  
explosion and fire. 
</P>
<P>
	The Piper PA28-140 registered in Broward County to a law firm  
crashed about a mile from the airport. The plane did not catch fire 
immediately, so the people inside were able to escape before it 
destroyed the house and the car parked out front. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never seen anything go up like this,'' said George  
Finger, a neighbor who saw the plane crash into the home's roof. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said they were not sure who was aboard the plane,  
which was en route to Spanish Cay, Bahamas. 
</P>
<P>
	``The airplane burned so bad we cannot read the number on the  
airplane,'' said Jorge Prellezo, regional director of the National 
Transportation Safety Board in Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	The NTSB and the Federal Aviation Administration are  
investigating. 
  	   	
</P>
