<HEADLINE> Ill. Court Nixes Boy Scout Gay Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A Chicago judge has ordered the Boy Scouts to  
stop barring gay applicants in hiring decisions, saying that the 
policy amounts to illegal discrimination. 
</P>
<P>
	``The mere sexual orientation of an employee ... is not related  
to any nondiscriminatory basis for denying opportunities for 
employment,'' Circuit Judge Stephen A. Schiller said in a ruling 
handed down Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling followed by one week a New Jersey Supreme Court  
ruling that the ouster of assistant scoutmaster James Dale violated 
state law. 
</P>
<P>
	Schiller upheld a 1996 decision by the city's Commission on  
Human Relations, which barred a policy under which the Chicago Area 
Council of the Boy Scouts in 1992 denied job consideration to gay 
Eagle Scout Keith Richardson. He complained to the commission. 
</P>
<P>
	George Davidson, a New York attorney who represents the Boy  
Scouts of America, said the council wants to appeal the decision. 
  	   	
</P>
