<DOCNO> APW19990813.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 15:40:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AltaVista Offers Free Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- AltaVista, a Web destination that  
persistently lags in popularity, thinks it's hit on the perfect 
gimmick to try to catch up to industry leaders Yahoo! and America 
Online: Free Internet access. 
</P>
<P>
	The strategy's success depends on how many consumers willingly  
subject themselves to a constant stream of advertisements. 
AltaVista requires customers to click on a window of ads and Web 
links on the computer screen at least once an hour, or be 
disconnected. 
</P>
<P>
	But if AltaVista succeeds in luring millions of Internet  
customers, as well as many more visitors to its network of sites, 
it could trigger a new movement by large access providers. 
AltaVista says it's signed up 50,000 users since launching the 
service Thursday and aims for 1 million users within a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Several small upstarts, such as ZapMe! and Bigger.net, currently  
offer free Internet access that elsewhere costs up to $260 or more 
a year. But AltaVista stands out as the first major Web brand to 
join the trend. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's inevitable that these types of services will be  
offered,'' said AltaVista spokesman David Emanuel. ``We think it's 
a very viable economic model.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But some weren't so sure other providers would swap the monthly  
fees they rely on for revenue for less certain advertising sales. 
Joe Laszlo, who follows Internet usage for the Jupiter 
Communications research firm, said AltaVista's action is unlikely 
to force the top Internet content providers to provide free access. 
</P>
<P>
	AOL, which drew more than 5 million new users in the past year  
despite raising its rates by $2 a month to $21.95, has no plans to 
give away the store, spokeswoman Tricia Primrose said. 
</P>
<P>
	AltaVista, based in Palo Alto, Calif., was sold by Compaq  
Computer Corp. in June to the Internet investment firm CMGI Inc. 
for $2.5 billion in a deal that has not yet closed. 
</P>
<P>
	It is depending on 1stUp.com in San Francisco for computers and  
other hardware needed to provide Internet access. 
</P>
<P>
	Some analysts say AltaVista, which ranked No. 10 among Web sites  
last month, has little choice but to take a radical approach. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have to because they're so far behind,'' said Charlene  
Li, an analyst with Forrester Research. ``AOL and Yahoo! are just 
huge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Only 1 million of the 63 million people online in the United  
States dial in for free, but that's changing as computer makers and 
even banks have begun to bundle free access with their own 
traditional services. 
</P>
<P>
	``From a consumer point of view, it's a bonanza,'' Li said. But  
profit margins will be tight, and few companies can afford to 
follow suit for long, she warned. 
</P>
<P>
	``There will be somebody coming out next week offering free  
Internet service to compete with AltaVista that doesn't require 
clicking on an ad. So the bar will keep going down, down, down,'' 
she predicted. 
</P>
<P>
	Some smaller companies offering free access, such as Bigger.net,  
have foundered over complaints of poor service and an endless 
streams of ads. 
</P>
<P>
	Matthias Gordon-Murer, a woodworker in San Francisco, eagerly  
signed up for FreeMac's offer of a new iMac computer next month in 
exchange for paying for three years of Internet access -- a $720 
commitment. 
</P>
<P>
	Now that AltaVista is offering the same access for free, he's  
not sure the new computer is worth it. And like AltaVista, FreeMac 
will monitor his Internet usage to send advertising in his 
direction -- a condition he'd rather do without. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's sort of like an electronic collar,'' said Gordon-Murer.  
``It turns me off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To sign up for AltaVista FreeAccess, users must provide the  
company with demographic information including age, sex and ZIP 
code. Describing shopping habits and favorite Web sites is 
optional. The information -- and the ability to follow every mouse 
click the users make -- will be used to target the ads. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990813.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 17:50:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Young and Old Collide at PGA  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEDINAH, Ill. (AP) -- Old age and treachery beats youth and skill  
every time. 
</P>
<P>
	Except this once.  
</P>
<P>
	The past and the future collided Friday at the PGA Championship  
and this time they just split the difference. The ``token old 
fella,'' as 54-year-old Hale Irwin referred to himself, toured 
Medinah Country Club in the company of ``El Nino,'' as everyone 
refers to 19-year-old Sergio Garcia, and both finished the round at 
5 under par, within shouting distance of the top of the 
leaderboard. 
</P>
<P>
	And the disparate ways they arrived there just might be one of  
the best things about golf. 
</P>
<P>
	But don't get misty-eyed just yet. This isn't a story about  
shared experience, about wise counsel being passed down from one 
generation to the next. On the contrary. 
</P>
<P>
	Irwin won his third U.S. Open the last time it was played at  
Medinah, in 1990, and so might be singularly qualified to pass on 
advice to anybody under 30 on how to play the golf course. 
</P>
<P>
	But when asked whether he had imparted any sage words to the  
Spanish teen-ager, who wasn't even born until four months after 
Irwin had won his first Open, the older man's expression went 
blank. 
</P>
<P>
	``You mean,'' he said, ``like the facts of life?''  
</P>
<P>
	Garcia, for his part, wanted it known that he didn't need help  
understanding the birds and bees, nor for that matter, Medinah's 
bunkers and trees. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I know how to play the golf course,'' he said. ``I  
think I'm doing fine the way I'm playing. We were talking about 
clubs and those kinds of things, but nothing really, really 
important.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest surprise, though, is that they were able to talk  
about anything at all. Garcia's average driving distance for the 
first two rounds of the PGA is 298 yards; Irwin's is 257. Typical 
of the day, Garcia was so far ahead of Irwin after striping a drive 
on No. 3 that somebody stumbling onto the scene might have assumed 
they were playing in different threesomes. 
</P>
<P>
	Not to worry. They arrived at every green together thanks to the  
heavy metal being played by Irwin. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is every bit as accurate with a 4-iron as the rest of the  
guys are with 7-irons,'' marveled 29-year-old Phil Mickelson, the 
third member of the group. ``I honestly believe that if he played 
on the regular tour full-time, he'd win at least once a year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There was a time when Irwin would have dismissed that estimate  
with a laugh -- as way too low. 
</P>
<P>
	He starred as a defensive back at Colorado in the 1960s, went on  
to win 20 times on the regular PGA Tour in 27 years and has added 
another two dozen victories to his resume since joining the seniors 
four years ago. He is as nasty a contestant as golf allows. Better 
yet, it might be the last sport gentle enough that Irwin can fight 
age to a standstill. 
</P>
<P>
	``What you have to do as a competitor,'' he said, ``is put a bag  
over everybody's head, including your own. That way, you can't look 
in the mirror and see gray hair or a kid with freckles. You just 
don't -- you don't pay attention to how old they are. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I'm comparing my distance with Garcia and Mickelson,  
those two specifically, I can't compete. But my irons are pretty 
good. I keep the ball in play, I make a putt every now and again 
and that's my game. 
</P>
<P>
	``That may be their game on an occasional basis, but maybe not  
as frequently as I. So,'' Irwin finished, ``things even out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Translation: On this day, Garcia hit every one of the first 12  
greens, promptly missed six birdie tries inside 12 feet and 
finished with 33 putts in a round of 1-over 73. Irwin hit 12 greens 
total, but needed only 27 putts to cobble together a round of 69. 
</P>
<P>
	Though they were tied approaching the final green, Irwin got  
there first and bathed briefly in the cheers of a gallery much 
closer in age to him than Garcia, a crowd old enough to remember 
his stirring win on the first extra hole after an 18-hole playoff 
nearly a decade ago. 
</P>
<P>
	As the roar grew, Irwin doffed his cap to the crowd. Then he  
turned and extended it toward Garcia, almost as if he were ushering 
the youngster into the spotlight. Respectfully, the young Spaniard 
pulled off his own cap and simply let the moment linger, passing on 
the temptation to respond with an in-kind gesture -- which, 
considering his age, would have been something along the lines of 
``raise the roof.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then the old man and the young one both made pars, and went  
their separate ways again. 
</P>
<P>
	``Can you think of anything you have in common with Hale besides  
golf?'' Garcia was asked. 
</P>
<P>
	``No,'' he replied.  
</P>
<P>
	As if to underscore that, Irwin was asked a few moments later  
what kind of mental and physical adjustments he would have to make 
in the next few days, going from contending for a major against 
young lions this weekend to defending his title in a senior event 
in Boston the next. 
</P>
<P>
	``Well,'' Irwin said, brightening, ``I won't be the oldest  
player there.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is a sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write  
to him at jlitke@ap.org. 
  	   	
</P>
