<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> VP Ousted Over Chicago Power Outages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The lights in the city are back on, but a top  
official at Commonwealth Edison is out. 
</P>
<P>
	A day after a power outage plunged a portion of downtown into  
darkness and sent confused commuters home early, a vice president 
handed in his resignation. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul McCoy had run the distribution system for the utility,  
already under fire for outages that left 100,000 without power 
during July's brutal heat wave. Officials at Unicom, ComEd's parent 
company, said it needed to make changes at the top level. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, if we had been performing better, he would still be  
here,'' Robert Manning, a Unicom vice president, said of McCoy. 
``Obviously, we're disappointed with the performance of our system, 
of our organization in that regard. And consequently, Paul has 
resigned.'' 
</P>
<P>
	ComEd officials say they restored power to all customers near  
and in downtown by 4 a.m. Friday. However, they struggled with more 
outages later in the day on the city's south and west sides. 
</P>
<P>
	About 1,400 customers were affected by those outages, which were  
not related to Thursday's problems. Power was fully restored by 
late afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Friday, ComEd was sued by two companies who say they lost  
money due to the outages and a man who says he injured his knee as 
he stumbled around in the dark. The lawsuit seeks class-action 
status. 
</P>
<P>
	Manning said the utility is not legally responsible for damages  
because of power outages. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
