<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Aug. 13, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Questions on Gore's Abortion Stance  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Al Gore's position on federally funded  
abortions for poor women needs clarification, Democratic rival Bill 
Bradley said Thursday. ``I think it is time for him to answer what 
his position is,'' Bradley said. ``On this issue in particular 
you've got to say what you believe.'' Gore spokesman Chris Lehane 
tried to clarify Gore's position when asked Thursday about the vice 
president's position on federal funding for abortions. Lehane said 
Gore's position has been to support the current federal law -- 
``federal funding of abortion in situations involving incest, rape 
and when the life of the mother is endangered.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Japan OKs Joint U.S. Missile Plan  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's Cabinet today endorsed a plan to research a  
missile defense system with the United States, a project spurred in 
part by North Korea's ballistic missile program, a government 
official said. Tokyo and Washington agreed last year to jointly 
research the defense system, and the Japanese government already 
has set aside $8.4 million for it in this year's budget. The 
project was announced last year just weeks after North Korea fired 
a rocket that sailed over northern Japan and into the Pacific. Many 
fear Pyongyang is preparing to test a second missile. 

</P>
<P>
	Spy Case Could Prompt Punishment  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A former director of the Los Alamos nuclear  
weapons lab and two former counterintelligence officers face 
possible discipline arising from the mishandling of a China spy 
investigation at the research center, officials said. Energy 
Secretary Bill Richardson said Thursday he strongly urged lab 
officials to take disciplinary action against the three, including 
the scientist who headed the prestigious lab for nearly a dozen 
years. Neither Richardson nor Los Alamos officials would name the 
three officials, citing privacy policies. But sources familiar with 
the internal investigation said one of them was Siegfried ``Sig'' 
Hecker, who was director of the New Mexico weapons lab from 1986 to 
1997. 

</P>
<P>
	House Lawmakers Fund Colleagues  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With control of the House at stake, lawmakers  
are opening their campaign checkbooks as never before to help 
colleagues facing tough re-election races. More than a year away 
from Election Day, incumbents already have given away more than $1 
million. ``It's a matter of political economics as well as 
friendship and personality,'' said Rep. James Rogan, R-Calif., 
whose role as a House manager during President Clinton's 
impeachment trial helped put him on the GOP endangered list. His 
colleagues already have helped him to the tune of $53,000. Federal 
lawmakers facing easy re-election campaigns long have shared their 
financial largesse with their less fortunate brethren, either 
through their campaign committees or through political action 
committees they control. 

</P>
<P>
	Study Shows Teen Pregnancy Pattern  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two-thirds of sexually active teen-age girls  
are having sex with boys close to their own age, according to a 
first-ever study that also found that those girls who have older 
partners are much more likely to end up with babies. By looking at 
all teen sex, not just liaisons that lead to childbirth, the new 
data refine earlier research that found most teen mothers had older 
partners. Only about 7 percent of sexually active girls ages 15 to 
17 had partners who were at least six years older than they were. 
But these girls accounted for 19 percent of the teen pregnancies. 

</P>
<P>
	LA Suspect Could Face Death Penalty  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The suspect charged with shooting five people  
at a Jewish community center and later shooting and a 
Filipino-American postal worker may face the death penalty, 
authorities said. Los Angeles County prosecutors on Thursday 
charged Buford O. Furrow Jr. with murder and five counts of 
attempted murder -- all filed as hate crimes. Federal prosecutors 
already had charged Furrow in the postman's slaying. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Are Lower  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices fell moderately Friday. The  
Nikkei lost 82.93 points to 17,340.04. On Wall Street, the Dow 
gained 1.59 points to 10,789.39 at Thursday's close. 

</P>
<P>
	Davenport, Williams Win at Acura  
</P>
<P>
	MANHATTAN BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- Top-seed Lindsay Davenport,  
feeling refreshed after a few days off, defeated Anke Huber 6-2, 
6-2 Thursday in her first match in the Acura Classic. Davenport 
needed just 58 minutes to dispatch the German, who pushed her to 
the limit before losing 7-5, 7-5 last week in the quarterfinals at 
Carlsbad, Calif. In other play, No. 6 Serena Williams defeated No. 
4 Aranxta Sanchez-Vicario 6-2, 6-3 in a quarterfinal match for her 
first victory in five career meetings with the Spaniard. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
  	   	
</P>
