<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Lawmakers Share Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rep. Jay Dickey, a Republican representing an  
Arkansas district that gave favorite son President Clinton 60 
percent of the vote, has more than doubled his fund-raising this 
year to prepare for a strong Democratic challenge next fall. 
</P>
<P>
	He got help from his Republican colleagues, who contributed  
almost $27,000 to his campaign. ``To get it early like this really 
helps,'' Dickey said. 
</P>
<P>
	Across the country, with control of the House at stake, both  
Democratic and Republican lawmakers are opening their campaign 
checkbooks as never before. More than a year away from Election 
Day, incumbents already have given away more than $1 million, both 
to needy colleagues and to strong challengers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a matter of political economics as well as friendship and  
personality,'' said Rep. James Rogan, R-Calif., whose role as a 
House manager during Clinton's impeachment trial helped put him on 
the GOP endangered list. His colleagues already have helped him to 
the tune of $53,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Across the aisle, Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee  
chairman Patrick Kennedy of Rhode Island sent a letter asking House 
Democrats to help 14 ``marginal freshman members,'' complete with 
names and addresses of their campaign committees. ``Please send as 
much as you can,'' he wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal lawmakers facing easy re-election campaigns long have  
shared their financial largesse with their less fortunate brethren, 
either through their campaign committees or through political 
action committees they control. 
</P>
<P>
	But with the Democrats needing just five seats to capture  
control of the House from the majority Republicans, never before 
have so many given so much so soon. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've always believed that sitting on my wallet wasn't helpful  
to anyone,'' said Rep. John Boehner, R-Ohio. ``Giving it to those 
candidates who needed it was important -- and especially early money 
to needy candidates. It helps show credibility, puts them on the 
map and wards away potential challengers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boehner boosted his contributions to GOP candidates to $91,658  
between January and June, up 55 percent over the $61,800 he gave 
during the same period two years earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Others increased their donations even more. House Majority  
Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, gave $10,500 to GOP candidates during 
the first six months of 1997. This year, his contribution total was 
$119,500. Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., gave just $500 to 
Democratic candidates in the first six months of 1997. During the 
same period this year, he contributed $38,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The three top House Republican leaders boosted their giving by  
529 percent, from $67,087 during the first six months of 1997 to 
$421,990 during the same period this year. The three top Democratic 
leaders increased their contributions from $7,000 to $91,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides giving directly to their colleagues, lawmakers have  
donated more than $2 million to the parties' congressional campaign 
committees, which also aid vulnerable incumbents. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a widespread recognition on the part of members that  
we are on the verge of retaking the House,'' said John Del Cecato, 
a spokesman for the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee. 
``We've seen an unprecedented surge in support from members who 
want to be a part of making that happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This dollar generosity is coupled with a general fund-raising  
increase by House candidates overall: 23 raised at least $500,000 
during the first six months of 1999, compared with just three 
during the same period in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Dickey more than doubled his fund-raising take during the first  
six months of 1999 as compared to two years ago, from $191,713 to 
$446,723. 
</P>
<P>
	Money from colleagues has gone to vulnerable incumbents such as  
Rush Holt, a New Jersey Democratic freshman. Two years ago at this 
time, Holt had raised $7,896 and had $6,241 in the bank. Through 
June 30, he had taken in $571,239 and had a bank account balance of 
$486,918. His Democratic colleagues had given him $16,500. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Republican side, Rep. Jack Quinn of New York, who  
switched his position and voted to impeach Clinton, raised $287,528 
during the first six months of the year, double the $140,864 he 
took in during the same period in 1997. He had $466,598 in the 
bank, as compared to $92,122 as of June 30, 1997. GOP lawmakers 
contributed more than $40,000 to his campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's especially satisfying when your colleagues think enough  
of the work you do to add their hard-earned funds to my effort,'' 
Quinn said. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those contributing to Quinn's campaign was fellow New York  
Republican James Walsh, who shared $20,000 from his campaign 
committee with his GOP colleagues. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like being a chairman,'' said Walsh, who would lose his post  
as chairman of the House Appropriations subcommittee that handles 
veterans and housing programs should the Democrats recapture the 
House. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
