<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mayor Pushes Spanish in Texas Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EL CENIZO, Texas (AP) -- The mayor of a Mexican border community  
says he doesn't know and doesn't care how many of the town's 
residents are illegally in the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayor Rafael Rodriguez stood fast Thursday behind ordinances  
adopted last week declaring the town a ``safe haven'' for illegal 
immigrants and requiring Spanish at City Council meetings. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't know who's legal or illegal. I would treat anyone the  
same, whether they're here illegally or not,'' said Rodriguez, who 
was once an undocumented resident. ``We're residents and we don't 
want to create problems by getting into private lives.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Any city worker who helps the U.S. Border Patrol uncover  
undocumented immigrants will be fired, the mayor said. 
</P>
<P>
	El Cenizo, incorporated in 1989, is an impoverished town with a  
high population of first-generation immigrants, both documented and 
undocumented. It sits alongside the Rio Grande about 10 miles south 
of Laredo. 
</P>
<P>
	City secretary Elsa Degollado estimated the city has about 7,800  
Spanish-speaking residents, about 1,000 of whom probably are in the 
United States illegally. 
</P>
<P>
	She said many undocumented immigrants living in El Cenizo leave  
their homes daily to make a living -- seeking temporary employment 
as gardeners, housekeepers or construction workers. 
</P>
<P>
	``These people need to feed their families,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	The other new ordinance stipulates that local government  
transactions be conducted in Spanish; an English translation is 
provided with 48 hours of notice. 
</P>
<P>
	In compliance with state and federal laws, written ordinances  
will be adopted in English and translated into Spanish. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodriguez himself does not speak English and says it's  
discrimination in City Council meetings ``not to speak Spanish and 
explain what is going on.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
