<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coffee, Wheat Futures Higher  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Coffee futures surged Friday on forecasts for frost in growing  
regions of Brazil, the world's largest producer. 
</P>
<P>
	On other commodity markets, wheat was higher, soybeans mixed and  
crude oil rose. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffee for September delivery rose 4.85 cents to 98.60 cents a  
pound on the Board of Trade of the City of New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffee rallied as traders weighed news of the cold front moving  
across parts of Brazil. The market's response was a reversal of 
Thursday's action, when coffee futures prices fell as traders bet 
the Brazilian cold front was unlikely to cause any damage. 
</P>
<P>
	While most of this year's coffee crop has already been  
harvested, frost could damage trees that will produce next year's 
crop. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures prices were higher while corn and soybeans were  
mixed Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat opened mixed before turning mostly higher on strong export  
news. The crop production report released by the U.S. Agriculture 
Department on Thursday -- bearish for corn and soybean prices -- 
wasn't as negative for wheat. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans opened lower, following through on Thursday's sharp  
decline, which was caused in part by the crop production report 
that suggested more of this year's crop will survive the summer 
heat wave than had been expected. Heavy rains in parts of southern 
Illinois and southern Indiana also weighed on prices, analysts 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices in some contract months turned to the positive side in a  
mixed day. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn also closed mixed as market participants weighed whether  
Thursday's crop report was overstated in its harvest forecasts. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery rose 5 cents to $2.85 3/4 a bushel;  
December corn fell 1/2 cent to $2.22 3/4 a bushel; December oats fell 1/2 
cent to $1.16 a bushel; November soybeans fell 2 1/4 cents to $4.54 a 
bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading resumed on time Friday a day after the Board of Trade  
closed an hour early due to power outages in Chicago's downtown 
Loop area. The problems were blamed on the failures of two power 
transmission cables. 
</P>
<P>
	Live cattle futures were higher and feeder cattle mixed on the  
Chicago Mercantile Exchange, while lean hogs were mixed and pork 
bellies higher. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle rose 0.55 cent to 66.05 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle fell 0.13 cent to 77.27 cents a pound; August lean 
hogs rose 0.15 cent to 54.60 cents a pound; February pork bellies 
rose 1.38 cents to 58.20 cents a pound. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude oil futures were higher in trading on the New York  
Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Oil futures were boosted by news that North Sea supplies will be  
cut next month, and word that a joint-venture between Texaco Inc. 
and Chevron Corp. was forced to stop pumping oil off the coast of 
Nigeria because of violent protests against the government. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude oil for September delivery rose 19 cents to $21.67 a  
barrel. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
