<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stakes High in Iowa Straw Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DAVENPORT, Iowa (AP) -- Free food. Free music. Free admittance.  
It's easy to dismiss the Iowa straw poll as a political 
free-for-all, but it's more than that to nine Republican 
presidential candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	Their campaigns could rise and fall based on the high-profile,  
high-stakes contest Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the only thing shaping the race for a while,'' said  
Rich Galen, a GOP political operative who flew from Washington to 
witness the spectacle. ``We'll have no way to measure what's going 
on other than polls and money for months.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The ``straw poll'' is an unscientific beauty contest, eerily  
unpredictable. Not once has the straw poll winner gone on to win 
the nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	``In a straw poll, money talks,'' Lamar Alexander, whose  
campaign is struggling and strapped for cash, grumbled Friday as he 
grilled pork chops at the State Fair. ``I don't think there's a 
front-runner before anyone votes'' in the February caucuses. 
</P>
<P>
	Any Iowa resident with a ticket ($25 each, purchased by  
campaigns for anybody who asks) can cast a vote after a day of free 
food, live music and curious sideshows -- such as the sight of 
Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson riding his Harley Davidson in support 
of George W. Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, the Texas governor, holds a wide lead in public polls and  
a tenfold lead in the earliest political test: fund-raising. A 
convincing victory would suggest that he can also organize at local 
levels. A weak showing would tarnish the aura of inevitability Bush 
has so carefully crafted since his landslide re-election in Texas 
in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	He has spent at least $750,000 on the straw poll, but the figure  
does not include priceless aid provided by trade associations and 
state politicians who know how to organize in Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	His campaign will dispatch 100 buses across the state to haul  
voters to the Ames, Iowa, site. Aides estimate that 300 to 400 of 
the supporters will be Hispanic, newcomers to Iowa GOP politics. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many of you may have never participated'' in Republican events  
like Saturday's straw poll, Bush told Hispanic leaders here Friday. 
``It's important that you participate, important that you come.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Forbes, a millionaire conservative seeking his first  
elective office, is expected to be competitive with Bush. He must 
do well to show that his money and message can convert to votes; a 
poor showing, even in a straw poll, could raise questions about his 
electability. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're making no predictions on win, place or show,'' Forbes  
said Friday after his bus rolled into the fairground blaring 
``Stars and Stripes Forever'' from a loudspeaker. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes has easily topped the $1 million mark to rent buses,  
throw parties for supporters, staff phone banks, mail recruitment 
letters and air television advertisements. He bought a half-hour of 
time Friday night for a televised town hall. 
</P>
<P>
	Little-known Washington activist Gary Bauer could make a name  
for himself with a top-tier finish. 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer, a former domestic policy adviser in the Reagan White  
House, has quietly canvassed Iowa churches and plumbed his contacts 
with the home-schooling community. He hopes to replicate the work 
of religious broadcaster Pat Robertson, who won the 1987 straw poll 
in a shocker that demonstrated the below-the-radar power of social 
conservative voters. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think there's a chance for a shocker,'' Bauer said Friday.  
``There may be a few surprises like a significant number of 
minorities supporting me. I think it would be a shock if I finished 
in the top half considering I don't have the money like Bush or 
Forbes, and I'm not a celebrity like Elizabeth Dole.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dole is the other big question mark. The former president of the  
American Red Cross is drawing huge crowds of young and professional 
women, who may or may not turn out Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The straw poll likely is Alexander's last stand. The former  
Tennessee governor, who has focused all his energies on Iowa, needs 
to show his political organization is worth keeping alive. 
</P>
<P>
	He must finish third, maybe fourth, to remain viable,  
Alexander's supporters say. 
</P>
<P>
	Dan Quayle has not made Saturday do-or-die, but his campaign  
needs a boost. 
</P>
<P>
	He likes to say that, as a former vice president, nobody doubts  
he is ready to be president but they wonder if he could get 
elected. The straw poll may be Quayle's best and last chance to 
show that he is a serious vote-getter. 
</P>
<P>
	Pat Buchanan is competing against Quayle and Bauer to carry the  
mantle for social conservatives. He was the top conservative 
candidate in 1992 and 1996, and could show Saturday that he is 
still a force. ``Do not let anyone buy your straw poll,'' he said 
Friday during a local radio interview. ``Do not let anyone buy your 
caucuses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alan Keyes is a marginal threat to win the nomination, but drew  
several hundred staunch conservatives to the 1996 Iowa poll. 
</P>
<P>
	Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch is a late-comer to the race. He is trying  
to build his base, beginning with fellow Mormons. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. John McCain of Arizona has nothing to win or lose Saturday.  
He called the poll a ``sham'' and refused to participate. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
