<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Police Regret Pepper Spray Comment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- The city's police commissioner  
apologized Friday for a course that taught cadets that pepper spray 
doesn't always subdue Mexican-Americans and other ethnic groups 
because of their tolerance for spicy foods. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no empirical or scientific evidence to support these  
statements,'' Commissioner Ronnie Watson said, adding that such 
instruction will be dropped from the cadet curriculum. 
</P>
<P>
	Police in the city of Harvard University use the spray, a  
mixture of cayenne pepper, resin and oil stored in an aerosol pump, 
to quell people resisting arrest. Police call it ``O.C.,'' short 
for oily resin of capsicum, another name for peppers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can guarantee you the ingestion of pepper orally does not  
increase the resistance of eye tissue to pepper spray,'' said Dr. 
Nicolas Carballeira, director of policy and planning at the Latino 
Health Institute. ``If it weren't so inherently racist it would be 
amusing because it is that ridiculous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cambridge officer Frank Gutoski taught the course in which  
cadets were told that people exposed to hot peppers at an early age 
develop a resistance to the spray. He said the information came 
from the Massachusetts Criminal Justice Council. But council 
officials denied the recommendation was theirs. 
</P>
<P>
	Gutoski and other Cambridge police officials did not return  
calls for comment Friday. Earlier this week, Gutoski told the 
Cambridge Chronicle newspaper that longtime ingestion of spicy 
foods minimizes the spray's effect. 
</P>
<P>
	``The people that it doesn't affect are people who have consumed  
cayenne peppers from the time they are small children, and this 
generally breaks into ethnic categories,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Extensive handling of spicy foods -- either on a farm or in a  
processing plant -- makes people less susceptible to pepper spray, 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mexican-Americans tend to be pickers. So, with Cajuns,  
Mexican-Americans, Pakistani, Indian .... what happens is the O.C. 
is effective for a much shorter time,'' Gutoski said. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995 -- the year for which the most recent statistics are  
available -- about 8 percent of Cambridge's 96,000 residents were 
Latino, 15 percent were black and 9 percent Asian, according to a 
study by the University of Massachusetts-Boston. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
