<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Five Dead in Calif. Home Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTERVILLE, Calif. (AP) -- Federal and local officials on Friday  
were investigating the deaths of five people found in a house that 
exploded. 
</P>
<P>
	The bodies of all five -- a man, his wife and three children --  
were found in the wreckage of the house and were burned beyond 
recognition, Fire Chief Frank Guyton said. Autopsies were to be 
completed Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokeswoman for the federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and  
Firearms, said Friday that the man shot his wife and three young 
daughters before setting off the explosion. But local officials 
said there was no evidence of a shooting and the cause of the fire 
was still under investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	``That information is absolutely erroneous. No conclusions have  
been arrived at,'' said police Capt. Silva Rodriguez. ``There's no 
evidence or indication that a firearm was used.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Contacted again later Friday, the ATF spokeswoman, Marti McKee,  
said she had ``misspoke'' earlier and could neither confirm nor 
deny the shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	The girls were 11, 7 and 2 years old, McKee said.  
</P>
<P>
	Neighbors reported the explosion Thursday night and the house  
was engulfed in flames when firefighters arrived minutes later. 
</P>
<P>
	Porterville is 150 miles north of Los Angeles.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
