<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oregon Adoption Law on Hold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALEM, Ore. (AP) -- Oregon's law opening up birth records to  
adult adoptees will be kept on hold for an additional 90 days, the 
Oregon Court of Appeals decided Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Approved by voters last fall, the adoption law gives adult  
adoptees the right to see their original birth certificates, which 
frequently have the names of one or both birth parents. 
</P>
<P>
	Legal challenges have prevented the law from taking effect so  
far, but supporters of the law had hoped the appeals court would 
allow it to take effect immediately. 
</P>
<P>
	But the appeals court Friday issued an order preventing the law  
from taking effect for 90 days, unless the court is able to reach a 
ruling before then on a constitutional challenge to the law. 
</P>
<P>
	Anxious adoptees who support the law said that finding their  
birth parents could help detect potential health problems and, more 
importantly, give them a sense of identity. 
</P>
<P>
	``This waiting is just absolutely hell. There are adoptees who  
are dying to know,'' Helen Hill, the chief petitioner for the birth 
records law, said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 900 adoptees have requested birth certificates under  
Measure 58. 
</P>
<P>
	But Frank Hunsaker, an attorney who represents six birth mothers  
who are suing the state, said the records should be kept 
confidential while the courts decide the measure's 
constitutionality. 
</P>
<P>
	Hunsaker said the adoption law violates the implied contract the  
women thought they had with the state that their identities would 
be protected. 
</P>
<P>
	If the records are opened before the courts decide the  
constitutionality of the measure, he said, ``Quite simply, the cat 
would be out of the bag.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A Marion County judge last month upheld the law, saying that the  
Oregon Constitution contains no promise of secrecy for women who 
give up their babies for adoption. That is the decision now being 
reviewed by the appeals court. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
