<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Aug. 13, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Pentagon Clarifies Gay Policy  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon announced mandatory training on  
anti-harassment guidelines for all troops beginning with boot camp, 
an update of its ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy for gays in the 
military. The directives make no basic changes in the practices and 
protections in place since 1994. Michelle Benecke, co-director of 
the Servicemembers Legal Defense Network, the leading advocacy 
group on the issue of gays in the military, said the real issue 
``is whether leaders will be committed at every level to stop 
anti-gay harassment.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Hatch Resents Charge of Intolerance  
</P>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Sen. Orrin Hatch says he resents any  
implication that he is intolerant: He said that when he told fellow 
Republicans at their state convention two months ago that they 
should be proud of their party because ``we don't have the gays and 
lesbians with us,'' he didn't intend the comment to sound 
prejudicial. The Utah lawmaker was just pointing out that ``gays 
and lesbians, by and large, are very intelligent, highly educated, 
high-earning people, who support mainly Democrats,'' he told The 
Salt Lake Tribune in a story for today's editions. 

</P>
<P>
	Bush Predicts Success in Straw Poll  
</P>
<P>
	CEDAR RAPIDS, Iowa (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush said today  
he has ``a good chance'' of winning the Iowa Straw Poll over his 
Republican competitors. Bush said the straw poll will be a good 
test of his campaign organization. Tomorrow's straw poll is an Iowa 
GOP fund-raiser traditionally seen as an early gauge of 
organizational strength, but this summer's event took inflated 
importance, partially because Bush declared he would go all out to 
win it. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia Mulls Wider War in Caucasus  
</P>
<P>
	MAKHACHKALA, Russia (AP) -- Russia launched new airstrikes and  
sent reinforcements to bolster an offensive against Islamic 
militants today in Dagestan. The acting prime minister said the 
campaign might be carried into neighboring Chechnya. The threat to 
strike Chechnya, which fought a war of secession against Russia 
from 1994 to 1996, was the strongest indication yet that the 
uprising in Dagestan -- a Russian republic in the Caucasus region -- 
could lead to a wider war. 

</P>
<P>
	Experts Urge Quick Serbia Reforms  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A group of experts today warned that  
Yugoslavia needs to move quickly to oust President Slobodan 
Milosevic. The Pact for Stability -- comprised of economists, legal 
experts and writers -- said Serbia would face civil war if the 
government and opposition parties fail to support a transitional 
government of independent experts. The group envisions a transition 
that would foster economic recovery and re-establish Serbia's ties 
with the world. 

</P>
<P>
	Israel Coalition Govt. Faces Split  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Ehud Barak's coalition government faced a  
possible split Friday when two religious parties threatened to quit 
in a controversy over the Sabbath. The parties made their threat 
after Barak authorized the transportation of equipment on the 
Sabbath day. Under Orthodox Jewish custom, driving is forbidden on 
the Sabbath, which lasts from sundown Friday until sundown 
Saturday. The arrangement between the religious parties and 
government is that work is not done on the Sabbath if it can be 
postponed. But wide loads have always been transported overnight on 
the Sabbath because traffic jams would result if they were moved on 
a weekday. 

</P>
<P>
	AltaVista Offers Free Internet  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- AltaVista, a Web destination that  
persistently lags in popularity, thinks it's hit on the perfect 
gimmick to try to catch up to industry leaders Yahoo! and America 
Online: Free Internet access. The strategy's success depends on how 
many consumers willingly subject themselves to a constant stream of 
advertisements. AltaVista requires customers to click on a window 
of ads and Web links on the computer screen at least once an hour, 
or be disconnected. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Closes Up 184.26  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks soared today as a new government report  
suggested inflation remains in check. The Dow Jones industrial 
average closed up 184.26 at 10,973.65., a gain of 1.7 percent. On 
the NYSE, advancers led decliners 1,953-1,044. The Nasdaq closed up 
85.66 at 2,635.15. 

</P>
<P>
	Lee Westwood Has PGA Clubhouse Lead  
</P>
<P>
	MEDINAH, Ill. (AP) -- Teen-ager Sergio Garcia faltered, while  
54-year-old Hale Irwin kept up his improbable run today and they 
both finished the second round of the PGA Championship at 139, one 
stroke behind clubhouse leader Lee Westwood. Westwood took the 
early lead by firing a 68 today for a 138 total, while Skip Kendall 
shot a course record 65 to tie with Garcia and Irwin. Kendall used 
some spectacular iron play and a streaky putter to make eight 
birdies against a lone bogey on the par-3 13th. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SUZANNE ROWLAND  



  	   	
</P>
