<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Magazine Ditches Import Car Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Motor Trend magazine is ditching its Import  
Car of the Year award in response to the increasing globalization 
of the automobile market. 
</P>
<P>
	Mergers and the use of foreign assembly plants by automakers in  
recent years has made it tougher to tell the difference between an 
import and a domestic car, C. Van Tune, editor-in-chief of the Los 
Angeles-based magazine, said in a statement Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Beginning with year 2000 models, Motor Trend will simply pick a  
``Car of the Year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The change comes as Motor Trend celebrates its 50th year of  
publication. 
</P>
<P>
	The import award was established in 1976 to highlight an  
increasing number of imports in the U.S. market. The difference 
between import and domestic cars has been blurred in recent years 
by the merger of Chrysler Corp. and German automaker Daimler-Benz 
AG, as well as the increasing of number of U.S. assembly plants 
owned by other foreign carmakers such as Toyota, Honda and Nissan. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford owns 33 percent of Japanese carmaker Mazda Motor Corp. and  
this year purchased the passenger car division of Sweden's Volvo 
AS. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
