<DOCNO> APW19990813.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 22:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Candidates Gearing Up for Iowa Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMES, Iowa (AP) -- The carnival tents were in place and the  
barbecue warming for a high-test straw poll that could leave some 
Republican presidential campaigns sputtering in the dust. 
</P>
<P>
	Rivals were pointing to Texas Gov. George W. Bush as the one to  
beat today, and a confident-sounding Bush and his aides did 
absolutely nothing to dispel that perception. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to look at it as an opportunity to bolster my  
organization and find out whether we need work -- if we need any 
work at all,'' said Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	The basketball arena and surrounding grounds at Iowa State  
University were set up for a giant party, with free food and music 
by big-name entertainers competing for the politicians' attention. 
</P>
<P>
	For the nine GOP candidates participating the stakes were high,  
although some sought to disparage the vote in advance. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a lot of graveyards in Iowa for front-runners, some  
of them from Texas and some of them who had a lot of money,'' said 
former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander. 
</P>
<P>
	Only Iowa residents can vote in the straw poll, with the state  
Republican Party reaping the proceeds from sales of $25 tickets. 
The various campaigns are buying the tickets and passing them out 
to anyone who pledges to vote for them. 
</P>
<P>
	Iowa Republican Party officials estimated initially that 12,000  
to 15,000 people would show up for the vote, but they have been mum 
on ticket sales. That made handicapping the outcome of the event 
tricky. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote is getting heavy attention because a large and diverse  
GOP field is running hard in key early states like Iowa, but 
there's nothing to offer a measure of their standing. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the only thing shaping the race for a while,'' said  
Rich Galen, a Republican operative. ``We'll have no way to measure 
what's going on other than polls and money for months.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush was spending at least $750,000 on the straw poll, and  
others said publisher Steve Forbes was spending even more and that 
the event was money-driven. 
</P>
<P>
	Only Arizona Sen. John McCain opted to stay away, and he blasted  
the vote even as his rivals were arriving for it. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Iowa straw poll has degenerated into a spending frenzy  
where the winner is not the candidate who is best able to define a 
vision for America's future, but who can rent the most buses and 
buy the most votes,'' McCain said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush had publicly set a goal of getting 5,000 backers to the  
event, and aides were confidently predicting they would exceed that 
goal, perhaps substantially. Bush is far ahead in raising money, 
and a demonstration of organizational prowess from a candidate who 
only this summer began campaigning in Iowa would be a big boost. 
</P>
<P>
	Falling short would suggest there are organizational weaknesses  
others could exploit. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no shortage of effort by the major contenders. Bush  
sent 100 buses around Iowa to gather supporters, and Forbes has 
waged an intense grassroots campaign for nearly two months. He 
rejected arguments about money. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you don't have a message, money won't get you much,'' said  
Forbes. ``The only way they will come is if they believe in you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The event took on new intensity when Bush decided to not only  
join in the effort, but to compete hard to win. ``I'm glad we made 
the decision,'' he said. ``Our organization was anxious to work 
hard to see whether we can perform.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush was getting substantial help from his backing of much of  
Iowa's GOP establishment, veteran organizers who brought him a 
ready-made campaign organization. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes also has something riding on the event, because he has  
spent heavily on the event and on early television advertising and 
needs to demonstrate that can be converted into real votes. He 
vowed to be competitive. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're making no predictions on win, place or show,'' said  
Forbes. ``We're using this as a benchmark in our drive to the 
caucuses'' next year that will award delegates to the Republican 
National Convention. 
</P>
<P>
	Conservative activist Gary Bauer hoped to gain support with a  
church-based network but he was likely to get competition from 
commentator Alan Keyes. ``I think there's a chance for a shocker,'' 
Bauer said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Elizabeth Dole is the other question mark. The former president  
of the American Red Cross draws big crowds of young and 
professional women, who may or may not turn out. 
</P>
<P>
	Dan Quayle argues that, as a former vice president, he's  
prepared to serve, but he needs a chance to demonstrate he can get 
votes as well as govern. 
</P>
<P>
	Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch is a latecomer to the race. He is trying  
to build his base, beginning with fellow Mormons. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
