<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tennis Star Steffi Graf Retires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HEIDELBERG, Germnay (AP) -- Steffi Graf, who dominated women's  
tennis for a decade before injuries started hindering her career, 
announced today she was retiring from the game. 
</P>
<P>
	Graf, 30, won 22 Grand Slam singles titles and had more than 100  
victories on the WTA Tour. 
</P>
<P>
	In her latest comeback, Graf posted a stunning, emotional  
victory over top-ranked Martina Hingis to win the French Open this 
summer. She then lost in the Wimbledon final to Lindsay Davenport. 
</P>
<P>
	She announced her retirement at a news conference in Heidelberg,  
near her hometown of Bruehl. Graf has an apartment in Heidelberg. 
</P>
<P>
	Graf won 107 WTA titles in a career that paralleled that of  
Germany's male star, Boris Becker. 
</P>
<P>
	Becker and Graf were responsible for making tennis one of the  
most popular and lucrative sports in Germany. Becker also retired 
earlier this year, playing his last match at Wimbledon. 
</P>
<P>
	Graf won more than $20 million in her career and spent a record  
377 weeks as No. 1 in women's rankings. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1988, she completed a ``Golden Slam,'' winning the four  
majors and adding the Olympic gold. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicknamed ``Fraulein Forehand'' for her devastating forehand  
shot that was her trademark, Graf suffered personal setbacks late 
in her career. 
</P>
<P>
	Her father, Peter, spent time in prison after being convicted  
for evading taxes on her earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	A long list of injuries hindered her in the last few years and  
Graf spent long spells off the circuit and began losing to lower 
ranked players she would normally beat with ease. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
