<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 17:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mets and Royals Exchange Pitchers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- The Kansas City Royals and New York Mets  
exchanged minor league pitchers Friday with the Royals receiving 
Derek Wallace and Jeremy Jackson going to the Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	Kansas City, which has blown 25 save opportunities going into  
Friday's game against Tampa Bay, said that Wallace would join the 
major league club. A roster move will be made upon his arrival. 
</P>
<P>
	``We hope that Derek can strengthen our bullpen, not only for  
the remainder of this year, but also as we look towards the 2000 
season,'' Royals president and assistant general manager Allard 
Baird said. 
</P>
<P>
	It will be Wallace's second stint in the Royals organization.  
Kansas City got him from the Cubs in April 1995 in a trade that 
sent Brian McRae to Chicago. The Royals then sent him to the Mets 
in July of that year. 
</P>
<P>
	Wallace, who pitched in 19 games for the Mets in 1996, was 2-5  
with a 3.60 ERA in 36 appearances this season at Triple-A Norfolk. 
He was a member of the silver-medal winning United States team at 
the recently completed Pan American Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson was a 10th-round pick for the Royals in 1998. The  
left-hander was 4-5 with a 4.41 ERA in 13 starts this season for 
Single-A West Virginia. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
